d6ccb71f13794d51edebaea4.cloudfront.net (CloudFront)","X-Amz-Cf-Pop","MRS53-P2","X-Amz-Cf-Id","8WajCarnQC9zcyrTYC1NpKIcElHBRhNeGzPU7cHybys-J7f_M-qtEg=="],"rawTrailers":[],"redirects":[],"req":"[Circular]","responseUrl":"https://api.deepseek.com/v1/chat/completions","socket":null,"statusCode":402,"statusMessage":"Payment Required","upgrade":false,"url":""},"reusedSocket":false,"sendDate":false,"shouldKeepAlive":true,"strictContentLength":false,"timeoutCb":null,"upgradeOrConnect":false,"useChunkedEncodingByDefault":true,"writable":true},"response":{"config":{"adapter":["xhr","http","fetch"],"allowAbsoluteUrls":true,"data":"{\"model\":\"deepseek-chat\",\"messages\":[{\"role\":\"system\",\"content\":\"You are a helpful assistant that summarizes documents. \\n              Return a JSON object with exactly this structure:\\n              {\\n                \\\"brief\\\": \\\"string (2-3 sentences)\\\",\\n                \\\"mainPoints\\\": [\\\"string\\\", \\\"string\\\", ...] (3-5 bullet points),\\n                \\\"keyPhrases\\\": [\\\"string\\\", \\\"string\\\", ...] (5-10 key terms)\\n              }\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"Please summarize the following document.\\n\\nProvide a brief overview, 3-5 main points, and 5-10 key phrases.\\n\\nDocument:\\n\\nOf the k subsamples, a single subsample is retained as the validation\\ndata for testing the model, and the remaining k - 1 subsamples are\\nused as training data.\\nThe cross-validation process is then repeated k times (the folds),\\nwith each of the k subsamples used exactly once as the validation data.\\nThe k results from the folds can then be averaged to produce a single\\nestimation.\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 42 / 60\\nK-fold Cross Validation\\nHow K-Fold Cross-Validation Works?\\nAlgorithm\\nRandomly divide E into k separate subsets (usually k = 10): E1...Ek\\nFor i:1→ k\\nLearning set: ⋃ Ej , 1 ≤ j ≤ k, j 6 = i\\nValidation set: Ei\\nCV =\\n∑k\\ni=1 NRMSEi\\nk\\nNRMSEi =\\n√ ∑\\nj (yj − ˆyj )2\\nn/k\\n¯y\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 43 / 60\\nK-fold Cross Validation\\nCross Validation of Models\\nCross-validation makes it possible to compare two different models.\\nOne model is considered more effective than another if its CV is smaller.\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 44 / 60\\nK-fold Cross Validation\\nLeave-One-Out Cross-Validation (LOOCV)\\n\\u0004 K-fold cross validation taken to its logical extreme\\n\\u0004 K = N (the number of data points in the set)\\n\\u0004 N separate times, the function approximator is trained on all the data\\nexcept for one point and a prediction is made for that point.\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 45 / 60\\nK-fold Cross Validation\\nExercise\\nCompare KNN (K=2) and Linear Regression using K-fold cross validation\\n(K=2)\\nxi yi\\n1 0.5\\n2 2.5\\n3 2.0\\n4 4.0\\n5 3.5\\n6 6.0\\n7 5.5\\nMSE = SSE\\nn , RMSE =\\n√\\nSSE\\nn , NRMSE = RMSE\\n¯y\\nCV =\\n∑k\\ni=1 NRMSEi\\nk\\na1 = n(∑ xi yi ) − (∑ xi )(∑ yi )\\nn(∑ x2\\ni ) − (∑ xi )2\\na0 = (∑ x2\\ni )(∑ yi ) − (∑ xi )(∑ xi yi )\\nn(∑ x2\\ni ) − (∑ xi )2\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 46 / 60\\nMultiple Linear Regression\\nMultiple Linear Regression\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 47 / 60\\nMultiple Linear Regression\\nIntroduction\\nSimple Linear Regression: Prediction of variable y depends on one pre-\\ndictor (variable)\\nˆy = f (x) = ax + b\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 48 / 60\\nMultiple Linear Regression\\nMultiple Linear Regression - Definition\\nPrediction of variable y depends on two or more predictors x1, x2, ... , xp\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 49 / 60\\nMultiple Linear Regression\\nMultiple Linear Regression - Definition (cont’d)\\nPrediction of variable y depends on two or more predictors x1, x2, ... , xp\\ny = β0 + β1x1 + β2x2 + β3x3 + ... + βp xp + \\u000f\\nˆy = β0 + β1x1 + β2x2 + β3x3 + ... + βp xp\\nˆyi = ∑p\\nj=1 βj xi,j + β0,\\n2 ≤ p ≤ m-1 / m is the number of variables\\nMeaning of coefficients βi\\n\\u0004 single unit change in xi ⇒ βi change in y (≈ slope concept)\\n\\u0004 positive βi : xi ↑ ⇒ y ↑\\n\\u0004 negative βi : xi ↑ ⇒ y ↓\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 50 / 60\\nMultiple Linear Regression\\nMultiple Linear Regression - Objectives\\n\\u0004 Analyze how y is affected by the different variables/predictor/factors.\\n\\u0004 Determine the relation between y and one or two variables (xi ) (key\\npredictors).\\nI The rest of predictors are added to have a more accurate model\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 51 / 60\\nMultiple Linear Regression\\nMultiple Linear Regression - Example\\nHousing prices\\n\\u0004 Dependent variable: House sale price\\n\\u0004 Key predictor variable: Square footage\\n\\u0004 Other factors/predictors:\\nI Median neighborhood income\\nI Age of the house\\nI size of the lot\\nI etc.\\nProvide more accurate\\ncoefficients for the key\\npredictor variable\\n\\u0004 Suppose you didn’t consider the factor of house age!\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 52 / 60\\nMultiple Linear Regression\\nChoice of Predictors\\n\\u0004 Adding more variables will change the coefficients of other predictor\\nvariables including the key predictor\\n\\u0004 Picking the ”right” variables in MLR is very important\\n\\u0004 Bad choice of predictor variables lead to a wrong prediction ⇒ wrong\\nconclusions\\nI Dummy variables might appear (erroneously) significant\\n\\u0004 Avoid picking variables that are ”overlapping”\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 53 / 60\\nMultiple Linear Regression\\nCalculating Coefficients\\nHow to get a ”good” estimate of y?\\nLeast Square method ⇒ Be Wrong as little as possible (Similar to Simple\\nLinear Regression)\\n\\n\\ny1\\n...\\nyn\\n\\n =\\n\\n\\n1 x1,1 ... x1,p\\n... ... ... ...\\n1 xn,1 ... xn,p\\n\\n x\\n\\n\\nβ0\\n...\\nβp\\n\\n +\\n\\n\\ne1\\n...\\nen\\n\\n\\nY = X ∗ β + e\\nChoose βi to minimize SSE\\nSSE =\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\ne2\\ni =\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\n(yi − ˆyi )2 =\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\n(yi − β0 −\\np\\t∑\\nj=1\\nβj xi,j )2\\nMinimizing SSE ⇒ d(SSE )\\ndβ = 0 ⇒ β = (X t X )−1X t Y\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 54 / 60\\nMultiple Linear Regression\\nCalculating Coefficients - Example\\nFind ˆy = f (x1, x2)\\ny x1 x2\\n5 1 2\\n8 2 3\\n9 3 2\\n12 4 3\\nY = X β + e\\nβ = (X t X )−1X t Y\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 55 / 60\\nMultiple Linear Regression\\nCalculating Coefficients - Example\\nFind ˆy = f (x1, x2)\\ny x1 x2\\n5 1 2\\n8 2 3\\n9 3 2\\n12 4 3\\nY = X β + e\\nβ = (X t X )−1X t Y\\nY = [5 8 9 12], X =\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n1 1 2\\n1 2 3\\n1 3 2\\n1 4 3\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 55 / 60\\nMultiple Linear Regression\\nCalculating Coefficients - Example\\nFind ˆy = f (x1, x2)\\ny x1 x2\\n5 1 2\\n8 2 3\\n9 3 2\\n12 4 3\\nY = X β + e\\nβ = (X t X )−1X t Y\\n(X t X )−1X t =\\n\\n\\n1.5 −1 1.5 −1\\n−0.25 −0.25 0.25 0.25\\n−0.25 0.75 −0.75 0.25\\n\\n\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 55 / 60\\nMultiple Linear Regression\\nCalculating Coefficients - Example\\nFind ˆy = f (x1, x2)\\ny x1 x2\\n5 1 2\\n8 2 3\\n9 3 2\\n12 4 3\\nY = X β + e\\nβ = (X t X )−1X t Y\\n(X t X )−1X t =\\n\\n\\n1.5 −1 1.5 −1\\n−0.25 −0.25 0.25 0.25\\n−0.25 0.75 −0.75 0.25\\n\\n\\nβ = (β0, β1, β2) = (1, 2, 1)\\nˆy = (5, 8, 9, 12), SSE = 0\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 55 / 60\\nMultiple Linear Regression\\nChoosing the predictors\\nFirst Method: Combination\\nfor m = 3 (y , x1, x2, there are four possibilities\\n\\u0004 y = f (x1, x2)\\n\\u0004 y = f (x1)\\n\\u0004 y = f (x2)\\n\\u0004 y = β0\\nm variables ⇒ 2m−1 possibilities ⇒ too high complexity when n is \\u001d\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 56 / 60\\nMultiple Linear Regression\\nModel Evaluation - Background\\nR2 = (1 − SSE /TSS) ∈ [0, 1]\\nSSE = Sum of Square Errors\\nTSS = Total Sum of Squares\\nSSE =\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\n(yi − ˆy )2\\nTSS =\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\n(yi − ¯y )2\\nhigher R2 ⇒ better predictive\\nmodel\\nclose to 1 ⇒ Perfect Model\\nclose to 0 ⇒ Null Model\\nSSE < TSS since in worst case scenario\\nthe model found is the null model\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 57 / 60\\nMultiple Linear Regression\\nModel Evaluation (cont’d)\\nProblem with R2 : It always increases as you add new variables but this\\ndoesn’t mean that our model is better!\\nSolution: Adjusted R2\\nR2\\na = 1 − (1 − R2) (n − 1)\\n(n − p − 1) = 1 − SSE\\nTSS\\n(n − 1)\\n(n − p − 1)\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 58 / 60\\nMultiple Linear Regression\\nChoosing the Predictors (cont’d)\\nSecond Method: Direct Selection\\n\\u0004 Initialization: Start with null model: ˆy = β0 = ¯y\\n\\u0004 Step 1: add one variable at a time and check the model which have\\nthe greatest Adj. R2\\n\\u0004 Step 2:\\nI if Adj. R2 of the new model=1 ⇒ perfect model\\nI Else if Adj. R2 is less or equal to that of the previous model ⇒ take\\nthe previous model\\nI Else go to step 1\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 59 / 60\\nMultiple Linear Regression\\nExercise\\nChoose the ”best” predictor using the Direct selection Method\\nA B C D\\n1 2 14 3\\n3 5 23 4\\n7 9 17 8\\n4 5 19 6\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 60 / 60\\nMultiple Linear Regression\\nExercise\\nChoose the ”best” predictor using the Direct selection Method\\nInitialization : start with null model (adj. R2 = 0)\\nA B C D\\n1 2 14 3\\n3 5 23 4\\n7 9 17 8\\n4 5 19 6\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 60 / 60\\nMultiple Linear Regression\\nExercise\\nChoose the ”best” predictor using the Direct selection Method\\nInitialization : start with null model (adj. R2 = 0)\\n\\u0004 Iteration 1 :\\nI A=f(B), Adj-R2=0.973\\nI A=f(C), Adj-R2=-0.4\\nI A=f(D), Adj-R2=0.95\\nI A=f(B) is the best model, since 0.973>0\\ncontinue\\nA B C D\\n1 2 14 3\\n3 5 23 4\\n7 9 17 8\\n4 5 19 6\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 60 / 60\\nMultiple Linear Regression\\nExercise\\nChoose the ”best” predictor using the Direct selection Method\\nInitialization : start with null model (adj. R2 = 0)\\n\\u0004 Iteration 1 :\\nI A=f(B), Adj-R2=0.973\\nI A=f(C), Adj-R2=-0.4\\nI A=f(D), Adj-R2=0.95\\nI A=f(B) is the best model, since 0.973>0\\ncontinue\\n\\u0004 Iteration 2:\\nI A=f(B,C) : Adj-R2=0.94\\nI A=f(B,D) : Adj-R2=1\\nA B C D\\n1 2 14 3\\n3 5 23 4\\n7 9 17 8\\n4 5 19 6\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 60 / 60\\nMultiple Linear Regression\\nExercise\\nChoose the ”best” predictor using the Direct selection Method\\nInitialization : start with null model (adj. R2 = 0)\\n\\u0004 Iteration 1 :\\nI A=f(B), Adj-R2=0.973\\nI A=f(C), Adj-R2=-0.4\\nI A=f(D), Adj-R2=0.95\\nI A=f(B) is the best model, since 0.973>0\\ncontinue\\n\\u0004 Iteration 2:\\nI A=f(B,C) : Adj-R2=0.94\\nI A=f(B,D) : Adj-R2=1\\nA B C D\\n1 2 14 3\\n3 5 23 4\\n7 9 17 8\\n4 5 19 6\\nA=f(B,D) is the selected model (perfect model)\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 60 / 60\"}],\"temperature\":0.3,\"max_tokens\":1000,\"response_format\":{\"type\":\"json_object\"}}","env":{},"headers":{"Accept":"application/json, text/plain, */*","Accept-Encoding":"gzip, compress, deflate, br","Authorization":"Bearer sk-e6c25806e5b7447e98a4ec0199a93bc0","Content-Length":"10671","Content-Type":"application/json","User-Agent":"axios/1.13.4"},"maxBodyLength":-1,"maxContentLength":-1,"method":"post","timeout":0,"transformRequest":[null],"transformResponse":[null],"transitional":{"clarifyTimeoutError":false,"forcedJSONParsing":true,"silentJSONParsing":true},"url":"https://api.deepseek.com/v1/chat/completions","xsrfCookieName