{"code":"ERR_BAD_REQUEST","config":{"adapter":["xhr","http","fetch"],"allowAbsoluteUrls":true,"data":"{\"model\":\"deepseek-chat\",\"messages\":[{\"role\":\"system\",\"content\":\"You are a helpful assistant that summarizes documents. \\n              Return a JSON object with exactly this structure:\\n              {\\n                \\\"brief\\\": \\\"string (2-3 sentences)\\\",\\n                \\\"mainPoints\\\": [\\\"string\\\", \\\"string\\\", ...] (3-5 bullet points),\\n                \\\"keyPhrases\\\": [\\\"string\\\", \\\"string\\\", ...] (5-10 key terms)\\n              }\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"Please summarize the following document.\\n\\nProvide a brief overview, 3-5 main points, and 5-10 key phrases.\\n\\nDocument:\\nThe Probability of an event A occurring when it is\\nknown that some events B has occurred is called a\\nconditional probability.\\nIt is denoted by\\nP(A B)\\nThe symbol P(A B) is usually read “ the probability\\nof A given B”\\nNote:\\n P(A or B) = P(A  B)\\n P(A and B) = P(A  B)\\nConditional Probability\\n1\\n2\\nExample 1- 25\\nA die is tossed once. If the appearing number is even,\\nwhat is the probability it is greater than 3?\\nSolution\\nFor one toss, the sample space is\\nS={ 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6}\\nA : Even number\\nA={ 2, 4, 6} ( new sample space) ( A  S)\\nB : Greater than 3\\n3\\nRelative to the sample space A, we find that B\\ncontains two elements\\nB  A={4,6}\\nThen P(BA)=2/3\\n1 2\\n3 4\\n5 6\\nS\\nB\\nِ\\nA\\n4\\n• Conditional probability may be computed if\\none understands its meaning.\\n• The condition reduces the sample space to a\\nnew set.\\n• Hence, normal probability computations can\\nbe performed with this new sample space.\\nComputation\\n5\\nExample 1- 26\\nSuppose S is the population of adults in a small town\\nwho have completed the requirement for college\\ndegree. We shall categorize them according to gender\\nand employment status\\nIf the one chosen is employed. What is the probability\\nthat he is a man?\\nEmployed Unemployed Total\\nMale 460 40 500\\nFemale 140 260 400\\nTotal 600 300 900\\n6\\nSolution\\nConsider the following events\\nE: The one chosen is employed\\nE= 600 ( the new sample space)\\nM: A man is chosen\\nM= 460\\n460 \\t23\\n( \\t| \\t) 600 \\t30\\nP M \\tE \\t \\t\\n7\\nExample 1- 27\\nA die is thrown twice. If a six appears what is the\\nprobability of a sum greater than 8?\\nSolution\\nA: A six appears\\nB: Sum greater than 8.\\nP(B | A) = ?\\nP(B | A) = P(A B)/P(A)=7/11\\n           \\n          \\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n6\\t,\\t5\\t,\\t6\\t,\\t4\\t,\\t6\\t,\\t3\\t,\\t6\\t,\\t2\\t,\\t6\\t,\\t1\\n6\\t,\\t6\\t,\\t5\\t,\\t6\\t,\\t4\\t,\\t6\\t,\\t3\\t,\\t6\\t,\\t2\\t,\\t6\\t,\\t1\\t,\\t6\\n8\\nNote that\\nS= { (1,1), (1,2), (1,3), (1,4), (1,5),…….…(6,6)}\\nNS=36\\nA= { (1,6), (2,6), (3,6), (4,6), (5,6), (6,6), ……}\\nNA= 11\\nB= { (3,6),(4,5), (4,6),(5,5),(5,6), (6,6), (6,5), (6,4), (6,3),\\n(5,4)}\\nP(B)=10/36\\nAB= { (3,6), (4,6),(5,6), (6,6), (6,5), (6,4), (6,3)}\\nP(AB)=7/36\\nP(B | A) = (7/36)/(11/36)= =P(A  B) / P(A)=7/11\\n9\\nThe conditional probability of B, given A, is\\nwith P(A) > 0,( \\t)\\n( \\t| \\t) ( \\t)\\nP A \\tB\\nP B \\tA P A\\n\\n\\nExample 1- 28\\nGiven P(A) = 0.3, P(B) = 0.6, P(A  B) =\\n0.1,Find\\nP(A | B)\\nP(B | A)\\nP(A | Bc)\\nDefinition\\n10\\nSolution\\n(a) P(A | B) = P(A  B) / P(B)\\n= 0.1/0.6 = 1/6\\n(b) P(B | A) = P(A  B) / P(A)\\n= 0.1/0.3 = 1/3\\n(c) P(A | Bc) = P(A  Bc) / P(Bc)\\n= [P(A)  P(A  B)] / [1  P(B)]\\n= [0.3  0.1] / [1  0.6] = 1/2\\n11\\nIf in an experiment the events A and B can both occur,\\nthen the conditional probability definition leads to the\\nfollowing important rule:\\nP(A  B) = P(A) P(B | A)\\nSince, the events A  B and B  A are equivalent it\\nfollows that\\nP(A  B) = P(B) P(A | B)\\nMultiplication rule\\n12\\nExample 1- 29\\nA fuse box contains 20 fuses, of which 5 are defective.\\nIf two fuses are selected at random and removed from\\nthe box in succession without replacement. What is the\\nprobability that both of them are defective?\\nSolution\\nA: the first is defective\\nB: the second is defective\\nAB: both are defective\\nP(A  B) = P(A) P(B | A)\\n= (5/20)(4/19)=1/19\\n13\\nTwo events A and B are independent if the occurrence\\nof one of them\\t\\ndoes not affect the probability of the\\noccurrence of the second one\\nIn Example 1- 30, the two events\\n{First is red}, {Second is red}\\nare dependent.\\nIf the experiment is changed such that the first selected\\nball is put again, then these two events are clearly\\nindependent.\\nIndependent Events\\n14\\nTwo events A and B are independent if and only if\\nP(B | A) = P(B) or P(A | B) = P(A)\\nThen:\\nP(A  B) = P(A) P(B)\\nIndependence\\ndefinition\\nDefinition\\n15\\nExample 1- 31\\nGiven that A and B are independent with P(A)=1/2,\\nP(A  B) = 2/3. Compute\\n(a) P(A | B)\\n(b) P(B)\\n(c) P(A | Bc)\\nSolution\\nP(A | B) = P(A) = 1/2\\n(b) P(A  B) = P(A) + P(B)  P(A  B)\\n= P(A) + P(B)  P(A) P(B)\\nP(B) = 1/3\\n16\\n(c) P(A | Bc) = P(A  Bc) / P(Bc)\\n= [P(A)P(A  B)] / [1P(B)]\\n= [P(A)P(A) P(B)] / [1P(B)]\\n= P(A) [1 P(B)] / [1P(B)]\\n= P(A)=1/2\\nHence, A and Bc are also independent.\\n17\\nExample 1- 32\\nAn electronic system consists of four components as\\nshown in Fig. below. The system works if\\ncomponents A and B work and either of the\\ncomponents C or D work.\\nThe reliability ( probability of working) of each\\ncomponent is also shown in Figure. Find the\\nprobability that:\\n(a) The entire system works\\n(b) The component C does not work, given that the\\nentire system work.\\nAssume that four components work independently.\\n0.9\\nA\\n0.9\\nB\\n0.8\\n0.8\\nC\\nD\\n \\t\\t \\t \\t \\t \\t \\t \\t \\t\\n \\t \\t \\t \\t \\t\\t \\t\\n \\t \\t \\t \\t \\t\\t \\t\\n \\t \\t \\t \\t \\t\\t \\t\\n \\t \\t \\t \\t \\t\\t \\t \\t7776\\t.\\t0\\t2\\t.\\t0\\t2\\t.\\t0\\t1\\t9\\t.\\t0\\t9\\t.\\t0\\n8\\t.\\t0\\t1\\t8\\t.\\t0\\t1\\t1\\t9\\t.\\t0\\t9\\t.\\t0\\n1\\t.\\t.\\n1\\t.\\t.\\n.\\t.\\t)\\t(\\n\\t\\t\\n\\t\\t\\t\\n\\t\\t\\n\\t\\t\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\nC\\tC\\nC\\nD\\tC\\tP\\tB\\tP\\tA\\tP\\nD\\tC\\tP\\tB\\tP\\tA\\tP\\nD\\tC\\tP\\tB\\tP\\tA\\tP\\tD\\tC\\tB\\tA\\tP\\tS\\tP\\n(a) S: Entire system work\\n \\t\\t \\t \\t \\t \\t \\t \\t \\t\\n \\t \\t \\t \\t \\t \\t \\t \\t \\t\\t \\t\\tD\\tC\\tP\\tD\\tP\\tC\\tP\\tB\\tP\\tA\\tP\\nD\\tC\\tP\\tB\\tP\\tA\\tP\\tD\\tC\\tB\\tA\\tP\\tS\\tP\\n\\t\\t\\t\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\n.\\t.\\n.\\t.\\t)\\t(\\nOther method\\n18\\n0.\\n9\\nA\\n0.\\n9\\nB\\n0.8\\n0.8\\nC\\nD\\n(b) C does not work given the system work\\n \\t \\t \\t  \\t\\n \\t\\n \\t\\n \\t\\n \\t\\n \\t\\n \\t\\n \\t\\n \\t \\t \\t \\t 1667\\t.\\t0\\n7776\\t.\\t0\\n8\\t.\\t0\\t8\\t.\\t0\\t1\\t9\\t.\\t0\\t9\\t.\\t0\\n)\\t(\\n)\\t(\\n/\\n\\n\\n\\n\\t\\t\\n\\n\\t\\t\\t\\n\\n\\t\\t\\t\\n\\n\\n\\t\\nS\\tP\\nD\\tC\\tB\\tA\\tP\\nS\\tP\\nD\\tB\\tA\\tC\\tP\\nS\\tP\\nD\\tC\\tB\\tA\\tC\\tP\\nS\\tP\\nS\\tC\\tP\\nS\\tC\\tP\\tZ\\tP\\nc\\tc\\nc\\tc\\nc\\n\\n19\"}],\"temperature\":0.3,\"max_tokens\":1000,\"response_format\":{\"type\":\"json_object\"}}","env":{},"headers":{"Accept":"application/json, text/plain, */*","Accept-Encoding":"gzip, compress, deflate, br","Authorization":"Bearer sk-e6c25806e5b7447e98a4ec0199a93bc0","Content-Length":"6995","Content-Type":"application/json","User-Agent":"axios/1.13.4"},"maxBodyLength":-1,"maxContentLength":-1,"method":"post","timeout":0,"transformRequest":[null],"transformResponse":[null],"transitional":{"clarifyTimeoutError":false,"forcedJSONParsing":true,"silentJSONParsing":true},"url":"https://api.deepseek.com/v1/chat/completions","xsrfCookieName":"XSRF-TOKEN","xsrfHeaderName":"X-XSRF-TOKEN"},"isAxiosError":true,"level":"error","message":"DeepSeek API error: Request failed with status code 402","name":"AxiosError","