{"level":"info","message":"Mapping JSON to PDFDocument: {\"filename\":\"I3304-2024-2025-Part-1 (1).pdf\",\"file_size\":4689970,\"mime_type\":\"application/pdf\",\"storage_path\":\"uploads\\\\1774034703303_I3304_2024_2025_Part_1__1_.pdf\",\"original_text\":\"\\n\\nI3304\\nNetwork administration and \\nsecurity\\nAhmad Fadlallah\\nAli RAAD\\n1\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nReferenceTextbooks\\n2\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nOutline\\n•Introduction \\n๏Introduction to the course\\n๏Recall Network Basics (I2208)\\n•Network Layer\\n๏IP packet structure (Recall)\\n๏Static Routing\\n๏Dynamic Routing Algorithm\\n๏Dynamic Routing Protocols\\n๏NAT (Network Address Translation)\\n•Transport Layer\\n๏Function of the transport layer\\n๏UDP Protocol\\n๏TCP Protocol\\n-Connection management\\n-Flow control\\n-Congestion control\\n•Application Layer\\nHTTP protocol\\nFTP protocol\\nMail protocols\\nDNS\\n•Introduction to Security\\nSecurity services\\nCryptography\\nDigital Signature\\nPrinciple of network security \\nprotocols\\n3\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s the Internet: “nuts and bolts”view\\n•Billions of connected computing \\ndevices: \\n๏hosts = end systems \\n๏running network apps\\n•Communication links\\n๏fiber, copper, radio, satellite\\n๏transmission rate: bandwidth\\n•Packet switches: forward packets \\n(chunks of data)\\n๏Routers and switches\\nWired links\\nwireless\\nlinks\\nrouter\\nsmartphone\\nPC\\nserver\\nWireless laptop\\nmobile network\\nglobal ISP\\nregional ISP\\nhome \\nnetwork\\ninstitutional\\nnetwork\\n4\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\n“Fun” Internet-connected devices\\nIP picture frame\\nhttp://www.ceiva.com/\\nWeb-enabled  toaster +\\nweather forecaster\\nInternet phones\\nInternet \\nrefrigerator\\nSlingbox:  watch,\\ncontrol cable TV remotely\\nTweet-a-watt: \\nmonitor energy  use\\nsensorized,\\nbed\\nmattress\\n5\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s the Internet: “nuts and bolts” view\\n•Internet: “network of networks”\\n๏Interconnected ISPs\\n6\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s the Internet: “nuts and bolts” view\\n•Protocolscontrol sending, \\nreceiving of messages\\n๏e.g., TCP, IP, HTTP, Skype,  \\n802.11\\n•Internet  standards\\n๏RFC: Request for comments\\n๏IETF: Internet Engineering Task \\nForce\\nmobile network\\nglobal ISP\\nregional ISP\\nhome \\nnetwork\\ninstitutional\\nnetwork\\n7\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s the Internet: a service view\\n•Infrastructure that provides \\nservices to applications:\\n๏Web, VoIP, email, games, e-\\ncommerce, social nets, ...\\n•Provides programming \\ninterface to apps\\n๏hooks that allow sending \\nand receiving  app programs \\nto “connect”to Internet\\n๏Provides service options, \\nanalogous to postal service\\nmobile network\\nglobal ISP\\nregional ISP\\nhome \\nnetwork\\ninstitutional\\nnetwork\\n8\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s a protocol?\\n•“what’s the time?”\\n•“I have a question”\\n•introductions\\n•Machines rather than \\nhumans\\n•All communication activity \\nin Internet governed by \\nprotocols\\nHuman protocols\\nNetwork protocols\\n... specific messages sent\\n... specific actions taken when messages \\nreceived, or other events\\nprotocolsdefine format, orderof \\nmessages sent and received\\namong network entities, and \\nactions takenon message \\ntransmission, receipt\\n9\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s a protocol?\\nQ:other human protocols? \\n10\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhy layering?\\nDealing with complex systems:\\n•Explicit structure allows identification, relationship of \\ncomplex system’s pieces\\n•Modularizationeases maintenance, updating of \\nsystem\\n๏Change of implementation of layer’s service \\ntransparent to rest of system\\n11\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nAnalogy\\nIk vind \\nkonijnen \\nleuk\\nL: Ducth\\nFax:#\\nIk vind \\nkonijnen \\nleuk\\nL: Dutch\\nI like \\nrabbits\\nMessage\\nInformation \\nfor the \\nremote \\ntranslator\\nInformation \\nfor the \\nremote \\nsecretary\\nIk vind \\nkonijnen \\nleuk\\nL: Ducth\\nFax:#\\nIk vind \\nkonijnen \\nleuk\\nL: Ducth\\nJ’aime \\nbien les \\nlapins\\nArabic & English\\nChinese & French\\nProfessor B\\nTranslator\\nSecretary\\nuse fax\\nuse Dutch\\nSecretary\\nTranslator\\nProfessor A\\n12\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nReference Models\\n•There are two competing models for how the \\nsoftware is layered: the OSIand the TCPmodels.  \\n•OSI (Open Systems Interconnection)\\n๏Developed by ISO (International Standards \\nOrganization)\\n๏7 layers\\n•TCP (Transfer Control Protocol)\\n๏Used in the ARPANET and in the Internet.  \\n๏Common mechanism that is surpassing the OSI Model.  \\n๏5 layers\\n13\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nReference Models\\n14\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nInternet Protocol Stack\\n•Application: supporting network applications\\n๏FTP, SMTP, HTTP\\n•Transport: process-process data transfer\\n๏TCP, UDP\\n•Network: routing of datagrams from source \\nto destination\\n๏IP, routing protocols\\n•Link: data transfer between neighboring  \\nnetwork elements\\n๏Ethernet, 802.111 (WiFi), PPP\\n•Physical: bits “on the wire”\\n15\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nISO/OSI reference model\\n•Presentation: allow applications to \\ninterpret meaning of data, e.g., \\nencryption, compression, machine-\\nspecific conventions\\n•Session: synchronization, check-\\npointing, recovery of data exchange\\n•Internet stack “missing”these \\nlayers!\\n๏these services, if needed, must be \\nimplemented in application\\n๏needed?\\n16\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nsource\\napplication\\ntransport\\nnetwork\\nlink\\nphysical\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nM\\nsegment\\nH\\nt\\ndatagram\\ndestination\\napplication\\ntransport\\nnetwork\\nlink\\nphysical\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nH\\nl\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nM\\nM\\nnetwork\\nlink\\nphysical\\nlink\\nphysical\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nH\\nl\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nH\\nl\\nM\\nrouter\\nswitch\\nEncapsulation\\nmessage\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nM\\nH\\nn\\nframe\\n17\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nReference Models\\n•Headers, Data, and Trailers\\n•Encapsulation\\n18\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTCP/IP MODEL\\n19\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nInternet Layers\\n•Internet Model\\n๏Dominant model in data communications and networking \\n๏5 ordered layers; often referred to as TCP/IP protocol suite \\n20\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nInternet Layers\\n21\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nPeer-to-Peer Processes\\n22\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nAn exchange using the Internet model\\n23\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nPhysical Layer\\n•Physical characteristics of interfaces and media \\n๏Representation of bits without interpretation \\n๏Data rate: number of bits per second \\n๏Synchronization of bits \\n24\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nThe physical layer is responsible  for \\ntransmitting  individual bits from one \\nnode to the next.\\nNote:\\n25\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTransmission Media\\n26\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nData link Layer\\nData Link Layer Responsibilities\\n•Defines framesinto manageable data units \\n๏Physical addressing \\n๏Flow control \\n๏Error control \\n๏Access control \\n27\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nThe data link layer is responsible for \\ntransmitting  frames from \\none node to the next.\\nNote:\\n28\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nNode-to-Node delivery\\n29\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\n802.3 MAC frame\\n•Preamble–7 bytesof alternating 0s and 1s to alert the receiver and allow it to \\nsynchronize\\n•Start Frame Delimiter (SFD) –1 byte –10101011 signals the beginning of a frame, \\nlast chance for synchronization –last 2 bits are 11\\n•Destination address (DA) –6 bytes –contains the physical address of the destination \\nstation or stations\\n•Source address (SA) –6 bytes –contains the physical address of the sender\\n•Length/type–if less than 1518 then it defines the length of the data field –if more \\nthan 1536 then it defines the type of the PDU packet that is encapsulated\\n•Data–data encapsulated from upper-layer protocols : 46 ~ 1500 bytes\\n•CRC–CRC-32\\n30\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nNetwork layer\\n•Network Layer Responsibilities\\n๏Source-to-destination delivery, possibly across multiple \\nnetworks \\n๏Logical addressing \\n๏Routing\\n31\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nThe network layer is responsible  for \\nthe delivery of packets from  the \\noriginal source to the \\nfinal destination.\\nNote:\\n32\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSource-to-Destination delivery\\n33\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nPosition of IPv4 in TCP/IP protocol suite\\nIPv4\\n34\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv4\\n•Best-effort delivery\\n๏IPv4 is an unreliableand connectionlessdatagram protocol\\n๏Abest-effort delivery service.\\n๏best-effort IPv4 provides no error control or flow control(except for \\nerror detection on the header).\\n•Connectionless protocol\\n๏Each datagram is handled independently\\n๏Datagrams sent by the source to the same destination could\\n-Arrive out of order\\n-be lost or corrupted during transmission.\\n๏IPv4 relies on a high-level protocol to take of all these problem.\\n35\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv4 Datagrams\\n•Packets in the IPv4 layer are called Datagrams.\\n36\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nver\\nlength\\n32 bits\\ndata \\n(variable  length,\\ntypically a TCP \\nor UDP segment)\\n16-bit identifier\\nInternet\\nchecksum\\ntime to\\nlive\\n32 bit source IP address\\nIP protocol version number\\nheader length (bytes)\\nmax number\\nremaining hops\\n(decremented at \\neach router)\\nfor\\nfragmentation/\\nreassembly\\ntotal datagram\\nlength (bytes)\\nupper layer protocol\\nto deliver payload to\\nhead.\\nlen\\ntype of\\nservice\\n“type” of data \\nflgs\\nfragment\\noffset\\nupper\\nlayer\\n32 bit destination IP address\\nOptions (if any)\\nE.g. timestamp,\\nrecord route\\ntaken, specify\\nlist of routers \\nto visit.\\nhow much overhead \\nwith TCP?\\n20 bytes of TCP\\n20 bytes of IP\\n= 40 bytes + app \\nlayer overhead\\nIP datagram format\\n37\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv4 Datagram (cont’d)\\n•A datagram is a variable-length packet consisting of a \\nheaderand data.\\n•Header\\n๏Length : 20 –60 bytes\\n๏Contains information essential to routing and delivery.\\n•Version (VER) : It defines the Version of IPv4. it is 4.\\n•Header Length (HLEN) : Defining the total length of \\nthe datagram header in 4-byte words.\\n38\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv4 Datagram (cont’d)\\n•Protocol \\n๏Defining the higher level protocol that uses the \\nservices of the IP layer\\n-TCP, UDP, ICMP, and IGMP\\n-Multiplexing data from different higher level protocols\\nValueProtocol\\n1ICMP\\n2IGMP\\n6TCP\\n8EGP\\n17UDP\\n89OSPF\\n39\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv6 Datagram\\n40\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv6 Datagram\\n41\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSubnet with VLSM\\n192.168.10.0/24\\n42\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nRegular Subnet\\n7subnets; The largest subnet needs 60hosts \\nIf 3bits for subnet (8 subnets) 5bits for host (32 hosts)\\nIf 6bits for host (64 hosts) 2bits for subnet (4 subnets)\\n192.168.10.0/24\\n43\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nExercise\\n•A multinational  company  wishes to have an IPv4 addressing  plan for the new \\nbranch it has created  in Beirut. The Beirut branch has 5 departments  as follows:\\n๏Human Resources  Management  (HRM) with 12 staff;\\n๏Engineering  (ENG) with 23 staff ;\\n๏Information  system (IS) with 8 staff;\\n๏Marketing  and sales (MS) with 50 staff;\\n๏Accounting and auditing  (AA) with 15 staff.\\n•In total,  the Beirut branch has 108 staff. The network  allocated  for the branch is \\n192.168.100.0/24. While taking into account the evolution  of the branch, divide  the \\nnetwork  into several  sub-networks  according  to the departments.\\n•You should fill the below  table  for each department/  sub-network.  Briefly explain \\nthe different  choices.\\n44\\nDept. \\nName\\nNetwork \\naddress\\nPrefix \\nlength\\nUsableIP address  range\\n(First –Last)\\nBroadcast address\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nForwarding -Routing\\n223.1.1.1\\n223.1.1.3\\n223.1.1.4\\n223.1.2.2\\n223.1.2.1\\n223.1.2.6\\n223.1.3.2\\n223.1.3.1\\n223.1.3.27\\n223.1.1.2\\n223.1.7.0\\n223.1.7.1\\n223.1.8.0223.1.8.1\\n223.1.9.1\\n223.1.9.2\\nDestination \\nNetwork\\nNext hopInterface\\n0.0.0.0223.1.1.3FastEthernet\\nFastEthernet\\nDestination \\nNetwork\\nNext hopInterface\\n223.1.3.0/24223.1.7.1FastEthernet0/0\\n223.1.2.0/24223.1.9.1FastEthernet0/1\\n45\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIntroduction to Routing\\nStatic Routing\\n•Static Route Characteristics:\\n๏Must be configured manually\\n๏Must be adjusted manually by \\nthe administrator when there \\nis a change in the topology\\n๏Good for small non-redundant \\nnetworks\\n๏Often used in conjunction \\nwith a dynamic routing \\nprotocolfor configuring a \\ndefault route\\n46\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIntroduction to Routing\\nDynamic Routing\\n•Dynamic Routes Automatically:\\n๏Discover remote networks\\n๏Maintain up-to-date \\ninformation\\n๏Choose the best path to the \\ndestination\\n๏Find new best paths when \\nthere is a topology change\\n๏Dynamic routing can also \\nshare static default routes \\nwith the other routers.\\n47\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nAddress Resolution -ARP\\n48\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nMAC addresses and ARP\\n•IP address: \\n๏“Low” Network-layer address for interface\\n๏Used for layer 3 (network layer) forwarding\\n•MAC (or LAN or physical or Ethernet) address: \\n๏Function: used “locally” to get frame from one interface to \\nanother physically-connected interface (same network, in \\nIP-addressing sense)\\n๏48 bit MAC address (for most LANs) burned in NIC ROM, \\nalso sometimes software settable\\n๏e.g.: 1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD\\nhexadecimal (base 16) notation\\n(each “numeral” represents 4 bits)\\n49\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nLAN addresses and ARP\\neach adapter on LAN has unique LANaddress\\nadapter\\n1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD\\n58-23-D7-FA-20-B0\\n0C-C4-11-6F-E3-98\\n71-65-F7-2B-08-53\\nLAN\\n(wired or\\nwireless)\\n50\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nLAN addresses (more)\\n•MAC address allocation administered by IEEE\\n•Manufacturer buys portion of MAC address space (to \\nassure uniqueness)\\n•Analogy:\\n๏MAC address: like Social Security Number\\n๏IP address: like postal address\\n•MAC flat address  ➜portability \\n๏can move LAN card from one LAN to another\\n•IP hierarchical address not portable\\n๏address depends on IP subnet to which node is attached\\n51\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nARP: Address Resolution Protocol\\n•ARP table: each IP node (host, \\nrouter) on LAN has a ARP table\\n–IP/MAC address mappings for some \\nLAN nodes:\\n•< IP address; MAC address; TTL>\\n–TTL (Time To Live): time after which \\naddress mapping will be forgotten \\n(typically 20 min)\\nQuestion:how to determine\\ninterface’s MAC address, \\nknowing its IP address?\\n1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD\\n58-23-D7-FA-20-B0\\n0C-C4-11-6F-E3-98\\n71-65-F7-2B-08-53\\nLAN\\n137.196.7.23\\n137.196.7.78\\n137.196.7.14\\n137.196.7.88\\nIP addressMAC addressTTL\\n137.196.7.1458-23-D7-FA-20-B0\\n20\\n52\\nUse arpcommand to display ARP table on Windows or Linux\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nARP protocol: same LAN\\n1.A wants to send datagram to B\\n๏B’s MAC address not in A’s ARP table.\\n2.A broadcasts ARP query packet, containing B's IP address \\n๏Destination MAC address = FF-FF-FF-FF-FF-FF\\n๏All nodes on LAN receive ARP query \\n3.B receives ARP packet, replies to A with its (B's) MAC address\\n๏frame sent to A’s MAC address (unicast)\\n4.A caches (saves) IP-to-MAC address pair in its ARP table until \\ninformation becomes old (times out) \\n๏soft state: information that times out (goes away) unless refreshed\\n•ARP is “plug-and-play”:\\n๏Nodes create their ARP tables without intervention from net \\nadministrator\\n53\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nARP operation\\n54\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nHardware Type –\\nEthernet is type 1\\nProtocol Type-\\nIPv4=x0800\\nHardware Length: \\nlength of Ethernet \\nAddress (6)\\nProtocol Length: \\nlength of IPv4 \\naddress (4)\\nARP packet\\n55\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nThe ARP packet is encapsulated within an Ethernet packet.\\nNote: Type field for Ethernet is x0806\\nEncapsulation of ARP packet\\n56\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nFour cases using ARP\\n57\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nARP Example \\n58\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nARP –A each step\\nARP: Who has this IP?\\nARP: Who has this IP?\\nARP: Who has this IP?\\n59\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nDefault Gateways\\n•Devices need the following information \\nfor network access: IP address, subnet \\nmask, and default gateway.\\n•When a host sends a packet to a device \\nthat is on the same IP network, the packet \\nis forwarded out the host interface to the \\ndestination device. The router does not \\nneed to get involved.\\n•When a host sends a packet to a device on \\na different IP network, the packet is \\nforwarded to the default gateway because \\nthe host device cannot communicate with \\ndevices outside of the local network.\\n•The default gateway is the device that \\nroutes traffic from the local network to \\ndevices on remote networks, such as \\ndevices on the Internet.\\nRouters are also usually configured with their own default gateway.\\n60\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•walkthrough: send datagram from A to B via R\\n–Focus on addressing –at IP (datagram) and MAC layer \\n(frame)\\n–Assume A knows B’s IP address\\n–Assume A knows IP address of first hop router, R (how?)\\n–Assume A knows R’s MAC address (how?)\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\n61\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•A creates IP datagram with IP source A, destination B \\n•A creates link-layer frame with R's MAC address as \\ndestination address, frame contains A-to-B IP datagram\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\nMAC src: 74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nMAC dest: E6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\n62\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•Frame sent from A to R\\n•Frame received at R, datagram removed, passed \\nup to IP\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\nMAC src: 74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nMAC dest: E6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\n63\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•R forwards datagram with IP source A, destination B \\n•R creates link-layer frame with B's MAC address as \\ndestination address, frame contains A-to-B IP \\ndatagram\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\nMAC src: 1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\nMAC dest: 49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\n64\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•R forwards datagram with IP source A, destination B \\n•R creates link-layer frame with B's MAC address as \\ndestination address, frame contains A-to-B IP \\ndatagram\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\nMAC src: 1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\nMAC dest: 49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\n65\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•R forwards datagram with IP source A, destination B \\n•R creates link-layer frame with B's MAC address as dest, frame \\ncontains A-to-B IP datagram\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\nMAC src: 1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\nMAC dest: 49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\n* Check out the online interactive exercises for more \\nexamples:  http://gaia.cs.umass.edu/kurose_ross/interactive/\\n66\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIntroduction to Routing\\nRouter Packet Forwarding Decision\\n•What happens when the router receives the frame \\nfrom the host device?\\n67\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nSend a Packet\\n•PC1 must determine if the destination IPv4 address is on the same network. \\n•If it is on the same network, PC1 will obtain the destination MAC address from its ARP cache or use an \\nARP request.\\n•Because the destination network is on a different network, PC1 forwards the packet to its default \\ngateway.\\n68\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nSend a Packet\\n•To determine the MAC address of the default gateway, PC1 checks its ARP table for \\nthe IPv4 address of the default gateway and its corresponding MAC address. \\n๏An ARP request is sent if it is not found.\\n•When PC1 has the MAC address of Router R1, it can forward the packet. \\n69\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nForward to the Next Hop\\n•R1 examines the destination MAC address which matches the MAC address \\nof the receiving interface and copies the frame into its buffer.\\n•R1 identifies the Ethernet Type field as 0x800 which indicates that the \\nEthernet frame contains an IPv4 packet in the data portion of the frame.\\n70\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nForward to the Next Hop\\n•R1 de-encapsulates the Ethernet frame.\\n•Because the destination IPv4 address of the packet, 192.168.4.10,   does not match \\nany of the directly connected networks on R1, R1 searches the routing table for a \\ncorresponding route.\\n๏R1’s Routing Table has a route for the 192.168.4.0/24 network.\\n71\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nForward to the Next Hop\\n•The routethat R1 finds to the 192.168.4.0/24 network has a next-hopaddressof \\n192.168.2.2 and an exit interface of FastEthernet0/1.\\n•This will require that the IPv4 packet be encapsulated in a new Ethernet frame with \\nthe destination MAC address of the IPv4 address of the next-hop router, 192.168.2.2\\n72\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nForward to the Next Hop\\n•Because the exit interface is on an Ethernet network, R1 must resolve the \\nnext-hop IPv4 address with a destination MAC address using ARP, assuming \\nit is not in its ARP cache.\\n•When R1 has the MAC address for the next-hop, the Ethernet frame is \\nforwarded out of the FastEthernet0/1 interface of R1.\\n73\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nPacket Routing\\n•R2 examines the destination MAC address\\n๏Because it matches the MAC address of its receiving interface, R2 copies the \\nframe into its buffer.\\n•R2 determines that that frame contains an IPv4 packet in the data portion \\nof the frame.\\n74\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nPacket Routing\\n•R2 de-encapsulates the Ethernet frame.\\n•Because the destination IP address is on a different network, \\nthe routing table is searched to find a corresponding route for \\nthe destination IPv4 address. \\n75\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nPacket Routing\\n•The routing table of R2 has a routeto the 192.168.4.0/24 network \\nwith a next-hop IPv4 address of 192.168.3.2 and an exit interface of \\nSerial 0/0/0.   \\n•Because the exit interface is not Ethernet, R2 does not have to \\nresolve the next-hop IP-v4 address with a destination MAC address.\\n76\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nPacket Routing\\n•The IPv4 packet is encapsulatedinto a new data link frame used by \\nthe exit interface and sent out the Serial 0/0/0 exit interface.\\n•Because there are no MAC addresses on serial interfaces, R2 sets the \\ndata link destination address to an equivalent of a broadcast.\\n77\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nReach the Destination\\n•R3 copies the data link PPP frame into its buffer.\\n•R3 de-encapsulatesthe data link PPP frame.\\n•R3 searches the routing table for the destination IPv4 address of the \\npacket.\\n78\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nReach the Destination\\n•Because the destination network is on R3’s directly connected network, the \\npacket can be sent directly and does not need to be sent to another router.\\n•Because the exit interface is a directly connected Ethernet network, R3 \\nmust resolve the destination IPv4 address of the packet with a destination \\nMAC address by either finding it in its ARP cache or send out an ARP \\nrequest.\\n79\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nInternet Control Message Protocol \\n•The Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) \\n•Specified in [RFC 792], \\n•Used by hosts and routers to communicate network-\\nlayer information to each other. \\n•Most typical use of ICMP is for error reporting\\n•Often considered part of IP, but architecturally it lies \\njust above IP, as ICMP messages are carried inside IP \\ndatagrams. \\n๏ICMP messages are carried as IP payload\\n80\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nICMP Type and Code \\nTypeCode Description\\n00echo reply (ping)\\n30destination network unreachable\\n31destination host unreachable\\n32destination protocol unreachable\\n33destination port unreachable\\n36destination network unknown\\n37destination host unknown\\n80echo request (ping)\\n90route advertisement\\n100router discovery\\n110TTL expired\\n120bad IP header\\n81\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTrace Route –ICMP\\n•Source sends series of UDP segments (or ICMP Echo request) to destination host\\n๏First has TTL =1\\n๏Second has TTL=2, etc.\\n๏Unlikely port number\\n•When n\\nth\\ndatagram arrives to n\\nth\\nrouter:\\n๏Router discards datagram\\n๏Sends to source an ICMP message (type 11, code 0)\\n๏Datagram includes router IP address. Traceroute does DNS lookup to find name of router \\n(if any)\\n•When ICMP message arrives, source calculates RTT\\n•Traceroute repeat the process 3 times (To get average RTT)\\n•Stopping criterion\\n๏UDP segment eventually arrives at destination host\\n๏Destination returns ICMP “port unreachable” packet (type 3, code 3)\\n82\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTrace Route –ICMP\\n83\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTransport layer\\nThe transport layer is responsible for delivering segments from a source process to a \\nfinal destination process.\\n84\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTransport layer\\n•Transport Layer Responsibilities\\n๏Process-to-process delivery of entire message \\n๏Port addressing \\n๏Segmentation and reassembly \\n๏Connection control: connectionless or connection-oriented \\n๏End-to-end flow control \\n๏End-to-end error control \\n85\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nApplication Layer\\n•The application layer is responsible for providing \\nservices to the user.\\n86\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nThanks !\\n87\",\"summary\":\"Here's a detailed summary of the provided text, organized into logical bullet points:\\n\\n---\\n\\n### **I3304: Network Administration and Security - Course Overview and Fundamentals**\\n\\n**1. Course Identification & Instructors:**\\n    *   **Course Code:** I3304\\n    *   **Course Title:** Network Administration and Security\\n    *   **Academic Year:** 2023-2024\\n    *   **Instructors:** Ahmad Fadlallah, Ali RAAD\\n\\n**2. Course Outline (Future Topics):**\\n    *   **Introduction:** Course introduction, recall Network Basics (I2208).\\n    *   **Network Layer:** IP packet structure (recall), Static/Dynamic Routing Algorithms & Protocols, NAT (Network Address Translation).\\n    *   **Transport Layer:** Function, UDP Protocol, TCP Protocol (Connection Management, Flow Control, Congestion Control).\\n    *   **Application Layer:** HTTP, FTP, Mail protocols, DNS.\\n    *   **Introduction to Security:** Security services, Cryptography, Digital Signature, Principles of network security protocols.\\n\\n**3. What is the Internet?**\\n    *   **\\\"Nuts and Bolts\\\" View:**\\n        *   Billions of connected computing devices (hosts/end systems) running network applications.\\n        *   Communication links: Fiber, copper, radio, satellite, characterized by **transmission rate (bandwidth)**.\\n        *   Packet switches: Routers and switches that forward data chunks (packets).\\n        *   The Internet is a \\\"network of networks,\\\" interconnected by Internet Service Providers (ISPs).\\n    *   **\\\"Service View\\\":**\\n        *   An infrastructure providing services to applications (e.g., Web, VoIP, email, games, e-commerce).\\n        *   Offers a programming interface (hooks) for applications to connect and exchange data.\\n\\n**4. Protocols and Layering:**\\n    *   **What is a Protocol?**\\n        *   Governs all communication activity in the Internet.\\n        *   Defines the format, order of messages sent and received among network entities, and the actions taken upon message transmission or receipt.\\n    *   **Why Layering?**\\n        *   Manages complexity by providing explicit structure, identifying relationships between system pieces.\\n        *   Modularization eases maintenance and updating of the system.\\n        *   Changes in a layer's implementation are transparent to the rest of the system.\\n    *   **Encapsulation:**\\n        *   The process where data from an upper layer is wrapped with headers (and sometimes trailers) from the current layer as it moves down the protocol stack.\\n        *   Each layer adds its own control information, treating the upper layer's data as its payload.\\n\\n**5. Reference Models: OSI vs. TCP/IP**\\n    *   **OSI (Open Systems Interconnection) Model:**\\n        *   Developed by ISO (International Standards Organization).\\n        *   Comprises 7 layers.\\n        *   Includes Presentation and Session layers for data interpretation (encryption, compression) and synchronization, which are \\\"missing\\\" from the core Internet stack and, if needed, implemented in applications.\\n    *   **TCP/IP Model (Internet Protocol Stack):**\\n        *   Dominant model in data communications and networking, used in ARPANET and the Internet.\\n        *   Comprises 5 ordered layers.\\n\\n**6. The Internet Protocol Stack (TCP/IP Layers):**\\n    *   **Application Layer:**\\n        *   **Function:** Supports network applications, provides services to the user.\\n        *   **Protocols:** FTP, SMTP, HTTP, DNS.\\n    *   **Transport Layer:**\\n        *   **Function:** Process-to-process data transfer, delivering segments from a source process to a final destination process.\\n        *   **Responsibilities:** Port addressing, segmentation and reassembly, connection control (connectionless or connection-oriented), end-to-end flow control, end-to-end error control.\\n        *   **Protocols:** TCP, UDP.\\n    *   **Network Layer:**\\n        *   **Function:** Routing of datagrams from the source to the final destination.\\n        *   **Responsibilities:** Source-to-destination delivery (potentially across multiple networks), logical addressing, routing.\\n        *   **Protocols:** IP, routing protocols.\\n    *   **Link Layer (Data Link Layer):**\\n        *   **Function:** Data transfer between neighboring network elements, transmitting frames from one node to the next.\\n        *   **Responsibilities:** Defines frames, physical addressing, flow control, error control, access control.\\n        *   **Protocols:** Ethernet, 802.11 (WiFi), PPP.\\n        *   **802.3 MAC Frame Structure (Ethernet):**\\n            *   **Preamble (7 bytes):** Alternating 0s and 1s for receiver synchronization.\\n            *   **Start Frame Delimiter (SFD) (1 byte):** `10101011`, signals frame beginning, last chance for synchronization.\\n            *   **Destination Address (DA) (6 bytes):** Physical (MAC) address of the destination.\\n            *   **Source Address (SA) (6 bytes):** Physical (MAC) address of the sender.\\n            *   **Length/Type:**\\n                *   < 1518 bytes: Defines length of the data field.\\n                *   > 1536 bytes: Defines the type of the encapsulated PDU packet (e.g., `0x0800` for IPv4).\\n            *   **Data (46-1500 bytes):** Encapsulated data from upper-layer protocols.\\n            *   **CRC (CRC-32):** Cyclic Redundancy Check for error detection.\\n    *   **Physical Layer:**\\n        *   **Function:** Transmitting individual bits from one node to the next (\\\"bits on the wire\\\").\\n        *   **Responsibilities:** Defines physical characteristics of interfaces and media, representation of bits (without interpretation), data rate, synchronization of bits.\\n        *   **Transmission Media:** Wired links, wireless links.\\n\\n**7. Network Layer Concepts and Protocols (Detailed):**\\n    *   **IPv4 (Internet Protocol Version 4):**\\n        *   **Characteristics:**\\n            *   An **unreliable** and **connectionless** datagram protocol.\\n            *   Provides a **best-effort delivery service**, meaning no guarantees for error control, flow control (except header error detection), or delivery order.\\n            *   Each datagram is handled independently; datagrams can arrive out of order, be lost, or corrupted.\\n            *   Relies on higher-level protocols (e.g., TCP) to handle these issues.\\n        *   **Datagram Format:** Variable-length packet consisting of a header and data.\\n            *   **Header Length:** 20-60 bytes.\\n            *   **Key Header Fields:**\\n                *   **Version (VER):** Defines the IP version (value `4` for IPv4).\\n                *   **Header Length (HLEN):** Total header length in 4-byte words.\\n                *   **Total Length:** Total datagram length (header + data) in bytes.\\n                *   **Time To Live (TTL):** Maximum number of hops, decremented at each router; datagram discarded if TTL reaches zero.\\n                *   **Protocol:** Defines the higher-level protocol using IP services (e.g., `1` for ICMP, `6` for TCP, `17` for UDP).\\n                *   **Header Checksum:** Used for error detection only on the header.\\n                *   **Source IP Address (32-bit):** Sender's logical address.\\n                *   **Destination IP Address (32-bit):** Receiver's logical address.\\n                *   **Options (if any):** E.g., timestamp, record route.\\n            *   **Overhead:** Typically 20 bytes for IP + 20 bytes for TCP = 40 bytes (plus application overhead).\\n    *   **IPv6 (Internet Protocol Version 6):** Mentioned as a datagram type, but no specific header details provided in these slides.\\n    *   **Subnetting with VLSM (Variable Length Subnet Mask):** Introduced as a practical exercise for IP addressing plan in a multinational company branch.\\n    *   **Routing:**\\n        *   **Static Routing:**\\n            *   Manually configured and adjusted by the administrator.\\n            *   Suitable for small, non-redundant networks.\\n            *   Often used with dynamic routing for configuring a default route.\\n        *   **Dynamic Routing:**\\n            *   Automatically discovers remote networks.\\n            *   Maintains up-to-date routing information.\\n            *   Chooses the best path and finds new paths upon topology changes.\\n            *   Can also share static default routes.\\n    *   **ARP (Address Resolution Protocol):**\\n        *   **Purpose:** To determine an interface's MAC (Media Access Control) address, given its IP address.\\n        *   **MAC Address:**\\n            *   Also known as LAN, physical, or Ethernet address.\\n            *   Used locally to get a frame between physically-connected interfaces on the same network.\\n            *   48-bit address, typically burned into the NIC ROM (e.g., `1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD`).\\n            *   Flat address space, administered by IEEE, allows portability of LAN cards.\\n            *   Analogy: Like a Social Security Number.\\n        *   **IP Address:**\\n            *   Network-layer (logical) address.\\n            *   Used for Layer 3 forwarding.\\n            *   Hierarchical address, depends on the IP subnet, and is not portable.\\n            *   Analogy: Like a postal address.\\n        *   **ARP Table:** Each IP node (host, router) on a LAN maintains a table of IP/MAC address mappings, including a **Time To Live (TTL)** after which mappings are forgotten (e.g., 20 min).\\n        *   **ARP Protocol Operation (same LAN):**\\n            1.  A wants to send a datagram to B, but B's MAC address is not in A's ARP table.\\n            2.  A broadcasts an ARP query packet (destination MAC `FF-FF-FF-FF-FF-FF`) containing B's IP address.\\n            3.  B receives the query and replies to A with its (B's) MAC address (unicast frame).\\n            4.  A caches the IP-to-MAC address pair in its ARP table until it times out (\\\"soft state\\\").\\n            *   ARP is \\\"plug-and-play,\\\" requiring no network administrator intervention.\\n        *   **ARP Packet Structure:** Includes fields for Hardware Type (Ethernet = `1`), Protocol Type (IPv4 = `x0800`), Hardware Length (6 for Ethernet MAC), Protocol Length (4 for IPv4), sender/target MAC and IP addresses.\\n        *   **Encapsulation of ARP Packet:** An ARP packet is encapsulated within an Ethernet frame; the Ethernet Type field for ARP is `x0806`.\\n    *   **Default Gateways:**\\n        *   The default gateway is a device (usually a router) that routes traffic from the local network to devices on remote networks (e.g., the Internet).\\n        *   Hosts need IP address, subnet mask, and default gateway for network access.\\n        *   Packets to devices on the same IP network are forwarded directly.\\n        *   Packets to devices on a different IP network are forwarded to the default gateway.\\n    *   **Router Packet Forwarding (Detailed Walkthrough):**\\n        1.  **Host (PC1) to Router (R1):**\\n            *   PC1 determines the destination is on a different network.\\n            *   PC1 gets R1's MAC address (from ARP cache or ARP request).\\n            *   PC1 encapsulates the IP packet in an Ethernet frame with R1's MAC as the destination.\\n            *   PC1 forwards the frame to R1.\\n        2.  **Router (R1) Processing:**\\n            *   R1 receives the frame, recognizes its MAC address, and copies it.\\n            *   R1 identifies the Ethernet Type (`0x800`) indicating an IPv4 packet.\\n            *   R1 de-encapsulates the Ethernet frame, extracting the IPv4 packet.\\n            *   R1 checks the destination IP address against its routing table.\\n            *   R1 finds a route, determining the next-hop IP address and exit interface.\\n            *   If the exit interface is Ethernet, R1 resolves the next-hop IP to MAC address (via ARP or cache).\\n            *   R1 encapsulates the *original* IPv4 packet (source and destination IPs remain unchanged) into a *new* Ethernet frame with the next-hop's MAC as the destination and R1's exit interface MAC as the source.\\n            *   R1 forwards the new frame out the specified exit interface.\\n        3.  **Intermediate Router (R2) Processing (e.g., Serial Link):**\\n            *   R2 receives the frame, de-encapsulates it.\\n            *   R2 searches its routing table for the destination IP.\\n            *   R2 finds a route with a next-hop IP and a *serial* exit interface.\\n            *   For serial interfaces, MAC address resolution is not required; R2 encapsulates the IPv4 packet into a data link frame for the serial interface (e.g., PPP) with a broadcast-equivalent destination address.\\n            *   R2 sends the frame to the next router.\\n        4.  **Final Router (R3) to Destination Host:**\\n            *   R3 receives the frame, de-encapsulates it.\\n            *   R3 finds the destination IP is on its directly connected network.\\n            *   R3 resolves the destination host's IP to MAC address (via ARP or cache).\\n            *   R3 encapsulates the IPv4 packet into a new Ethernet frame with the destination host's MAC and R3's exit interface MAC.\\n            *   R3 sends the frame directly to the destination host.\\n            *   **Key Point:** The IP source and destination addresses remain constant throughout the end-to-end journey; only the MAC source and destination addresses change at each hop.\\n    *   **ICMP (Internet Control Message Protocol):**\\n        *   **Purpose:** Used by hosts and routers to communicate network-layer information to each other, primarily for error reporting.\\n        *   **Architecture:** Architecturally lies just above IP; ICMP messages are carried as IP payload.\\n        *   **Common Types and Codes:**\\n            *   `0, 0`: Echo Reply (ping response).\\n            *   `3, 0-7`: Destination Unreachable (network, host, protocol, port, fragmentation needed, source route failed, etc.).\\n            *   `8, 0`: Echo Request (ping request).\\n            *   `11, 0`: Time Exceeded (TTL expired in transit).\\n    *   **Trace Route (using ICMP):**\\n        *   **Mechanism:** Source sends a series of UDP segments (or ICMP Echo requests) to the destination, starting with a **TTL (Time To Live) of 1**, then `2`, `3`, and so on. Unlikely port numbers are used for UDP.\\n        *   **Router Behavior:** When the *n*th datagram arrives at the *n*th router, its TTL expires. The router discards the datagram and sends an **ICMP \\\"Time Exceeded\\\" message (Type 11, Code 0)** back to the source, including the router's IP address. Traceroute performs a DNS lookup to find the router's name.\\n        *   **Source Behavior:** Upon receiving the ICMP message, the source calculates the Round Trip Time (RTT). This process is repeated 3 times for each TTL value to get an average.\\n        *   **Stopping Criterion:** When the UDP segment eventually reaches the destination host, the host returns an **ICMP \\\"Port Unreachable\\\" packet (Type 3, Code 3)** because the destination port is likely closed. This signal marks the end of the trace.\\n\\n---\"}","timestamp":"2026-03-20 21:25:40"}
