{"file_size":4689970,"filename":"I3304-2024-2025-Part-1 (1).pdf","level":"info","message":"Input object for PDFDocument:","mime_type":"application/pdf","original_text":"\n\nI3304\nNetwork administration and \nsecurity\nAhmad Fadlallah\nAli RAAD\n1\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nReferenceTextbooks\n2\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nOutline\n•Introduction \n๏Introduction to the course\n๏Recall Network Basics (I2208)\n•Network Layer\n๏IP packet structure (Recall)\n๏Static Routing\n๏Dynamic Routing Algorithm\n๏Dynamic Routing Protocols\n๏NAT (Network Address Translation)\n•Transport Layer\n๏Function of the transport layer\n๏UDP Protocol\n๏TCP Protocol\n-Connection management\n-Flow control\n-Congestion control\n•Application Layer\nHTTP protocol\nFTP protocol\nMail protocols\nDNS\n•Introduction to Security\nSecurity services\nCryptography\nDigital Signature\nPrinciple of network security \nprotocols\n3\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nWhat’s the Internet: “nuts and bolts”view\n•Billions of connected computing \ndevices: \n๏hosts = end systems \n๏running network apps\n•Communication links\n๏fiber, copper, radio, satellite\n๏transmission rate: bandwidth\n•Packet switches: forward packets \n(chunks of data)\n๏Routers and switches\nWired links\nwireless\nlinks\nrouter\nsmartphone\nPC\nserver\nWireless laptop\nmobile network\nglobal ISP\nregional ISP\nhome \nnetwork\ninstitutional\nnetwork\n4\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\n“Fun” Internet-connected devices\nIP picture frame\nhttp://www.ceiva.com/\nWeb-enabled  toaster +\nweather forecaster\nInternet phones\nInternet \nrefrigerator\nSlingbox:  watch,\ncontrol cable TV remotely\nTweet-a-watt: \nmonitor energy  use\nsensorized,\nbed\nmattress\n5\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nWhat’s the Internet: “nuts and bolts” view\n•Internet: “network of networks”\n๏Interconnected ISPs\n6\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nWhat’s the Internet: “nuts and bolts” view\n•Protocolscontrol sending, \nreceiving of messages\n๏e.g., TCP, IP, HTTP, Skype,  \n802.11\n•Internet  standards\n๏RFC: Request for comments\n๏IETF: Internet Engineering Task \nForce\nmobile network\nglobal ISP\nregional ISP\nhome \nnetwork\ninstitutional\nnetwork\n7\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nWhat’s the Internet: a service view\n•Infrastructure that provides \nservices to applications:\n๏Web, VoIP, email, games, e-\ncommerce, social nets, ...\n•Provides programming \ninterface to apps\n๏hooks that allow sending \nand receiving  app programs \nto “connect”to Internet\n๏Provides service options, \nanalogous to postal service\nmobile network\nglobal ISP\nregional ISP\nhome \nnetwork\ninstitutional\nnetwork\n8\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nWhat’s a protocol?\n•“what’s the time?”\n•“I have a question”\n•introductions\n•Machines rather than \nhumans\n•All communication activity \nin Internet governed by \nprotocols\nHuman protocols\nNetwork protocols\n... specific messages sent\n... specific actions taken when messages \nreceived, or other events\nprotocolsdefine format, orderof \nmessages sent and received\namong network entities, and \nactions takenon message \ntransmission, receipt\n9\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nWhat’s a protocol?\nQ:other human protocols? \n10\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nWhy layering?\nDealing with complex systems:\n•Explicit structure allows identification, relationship of \ncomplex system’s pieces\n•Modularizationeases maintenance, updating of \nsystem\n๏Change of implementation of layer’s service \ntransparent to rest of system\n11\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nAnalogy\nIk vind \nkonijnen \nleuk\nL: Ducth\nFax:#\nIk vind \nkonijnen \nleuk\nL: Dutch\nI like \nrabbits\nMessage\nInformation \nfor the \nremote \ntranslator\nInformation \nfor the \nremote \nsecretary\nIk vind \nkonijnen \nleuk\nL: Ducth\nFax:#\nIk vind \nkonijnen \nleuk\nL: Ducth\nJ’aime \nbien les \nlapins\nArabic & English\nChinese & French\nProfessor B\nTranslator\nSecretary\nuse fax\nuse Dutch\nSecretary\nTranslator\nProfessor A\n12\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nReference Models\n•There are two competing models for how the \nsoftware is layered: the OSIand the TCPmodels.  \n•OSI (Open Systems Interconnection)\n๏Developed by ISO (International Standards \nOrganization)\n๏7 layers\n•TCP (Transfer Control Protocol)\n๏Used in the ARPANET and in the Internet.  \n๏Common mechanism that is surpassing the OSI Model.  \n๏5 layers\n13\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nReference Models\n14\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nInternet Protocol Stack\n•Application: supporting network applications\n๏FTP, SMTP, HTTP\n•Transport: process-process data transfer\n๏TCP, UDP\n•Network: routing of datagrams from source \nto destination\n๏IP, routing protocols\n•Link: data transfer between neighboring  \nnetwork elements\n๏Ethernet, 802.111 (WiFi), PPP\n•Physical: bits “on the wire”\n15\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nISO/OSI reference model\n•Presentation: allow applications to \ninterpret meaning of data, e.g., \nencryption, compression, machine-\nspecific conventions\n•Session: synchronization, check-\npointing, recovery of data exchange\n•Internet stack “missing”these \nlayers!\n๏these services, if needed, must be \nimplemented in application\n๏needed?\n16\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nsource\napplication\ntransport\nnetwork\nlink\nphysical\nH\nt\nH\nn\nM\nsegment\nH\nt\ndatagram\ndestination\napplication\ntransport\nnetwork\nlink\nphysical\nH\nt\nH\nn\nH\nl\nM\nH\nt\nH\nn\nM\nH\nt\nM\nM\nnetwork\nlink\nphysical\nlink\nphysical\nH\nt\nH\nn\nH\nl\nM\nH\nt\nH\nn\nM\nH\nt\nH\nn\nM\nH\nt\nH\nn\nH\nl\nM\nrouter\nswitch\nEncapsulation\nmessage\nM\nH\nt\nM\nH\nn\nframe\n17\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nReference Models\n•Headers, Data, and Trailers\n•Encapsulation\n18\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nTCP/IP MODEL\n19\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nInternet Layers\n•Internet Model\n๏Dominant model in data communications and networking \n๏5 ordered layers; often referred to as TCP/IP protocol suite \n20\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nInternet Layers\n21\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nPeer-to-Peer Processes\n22\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nAn exchange using the Internet model\n23\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nPhysical Layer\n•Physical characteristics of interfaces and media \n๏Representation of bits without interpretation \n๏Data rate: number of bits per second \n๏Synchronization of bits \n24\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nThe physical layer is responsible  for \ntransmitting  individual bits from one \nnode to the next.\nNote:\n25\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nTransmission Media\n26\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nData link Layer\nData Link Layer Responsibilities\n•Defines framesinto manageable data units \n๏Physical addressing \n๏Flow control \n๏Error control \n๏Access control \n27\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nThe data link layer is responsible for \ntransmitting  frames from \none node to the next.\nNote:\n28\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nNode-to-Node delivery\n29\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\n802.3 MAC frame\n•Preamble–7 bytesof alternating 0s and 1s to alert the receiver and allow it to \nsynchronize\n•Start Frame Delimiter (SFD) –1 byte –10101011 signals the beginning of a frame, \nlast chance for synchronization –last 2 bits are 11\n•Destination address (DA) –6 bytes –contains the physical address of the destination \nstation or stations\n•Source address (SA) –6 bytes –contains the physical address of the sender\n•Length/type–if less than 1518 then it defines the length of the data field –if more \nthan 1536 then it defines the type of the PDU packet that is encapsulated\n•Data–data encapsulated from upper-layer protocols : 46 ~ 1500 bytes\n•CRC–CRC-32\n30\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nNetwork layer\n•Network Layer Responsibilities\n๏Source-to-destination delivery, possibly across multiple \nnetworks \n๏Logical addressing \n๏Routing\n31\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nThe network layer is responsible  for \nthe delivery of packets from  the \noriginal source to the \nfinal destination.\nNote:\n32\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSource-to-Destination delivery\n33\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nPosition of IPv4 in TCP/IP protocol suite\nIPv4\n34\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIPv4\n•Best-effort delivery\n๏IPv4 is an unreliableand connectionlessdatagram protocol\n๏Abest-effort delivery service.\n๏best-effort IPv4 provides no error control or flow control(except for \nerror detection on the header).\n•Connectionless protocol\n๏Each datagram is handled independently\n๏Datagrams sent by the source to the same destination could\n-Arrive out of order\n-be lost or corrupted during transmission.\n๏IPv4 relies on a high-level protocol to take of all these problem.\n35\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIPv4 Datagrams\n•Packets in the IPv4 layer are called Datagrams.\n36\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nver\nlength\n32 bits\ndata \n(variable  length,\ntypically a TCP \nor UDP segment)\n16-bit identifier\nInternet\nchecksum\ntime to\nlive\n32 bit source IP address\nIP protocol version number\nheader length (bytes)\nmax number\nremaining hops\n(decremented at \neach router)\nfor\nfragmentation/\nreassembly\ntotal datagram\nlength (bytes)\nupper layer protocol\nto deliver payload to\nhead.\nlen\ntype of\nservice\n“type” of data \nflgs\nfragment\noffset\nupper\nlayer\n32 bit destination IP address\nOptions (if any)\nE.g. timestamp,\nrecord route\ntaken, specify\nlist of routers \nto visit.\nhow much overhead \nwith TCP?\n20 bytes of TCP\n20 bytes of IP\n= 40 bytes + app \nlayer overhead\nIP datagram format\n37\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIPv4 Datagram (cont’d)\n•A datagram is a variable-length packet consisting of a \nheaderand data.\n•Header\n๏Length : 20 –60 bytes\n๏Contains information essential to routing and delivery.\n•Version (VER) : It defines the Version of IPv4. it is 4.\n•Header Length (HLEN) : Defining the total length of \nthe datagram header in 4-byte words.\n38\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIPv4 Datagram (cont’d)\n•Protocol \n๏Defining the higher level protocol that uses the \nservices of the IP layer\n-TCP, UDP, ICMP, and IGMP\n-Multiplexing data from different higher level protocols\nValueProtocol\n1ICMP\n2IGMP\n6TCP\n8EGP\n17UDP\n89OSPF\n39\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIPv6 Datagram\n40\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIPv6 Datagram\n41\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSubnet with VLSM\n192.168.10.0/24\n42\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nRegular Subnet\n7subnets; The largest subnet needs 60hosts \nIf 3bits for subnet (8 subnets) 5bits for host (32 hosts)\nIf 6bits for host (64 hosts) 2bits for subnet (4 subnets)\n192.168.10.0/24\n43\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nExercise\n•A multinational  company  wishes to have an IPv4 addressing  plan for the new \nbranch it has created  in Beirut. The Beirut branch has 5 departments  as follows:\n๏Human Resources  Management  (HRM) with 12 staff;\n๏Engineering  (ENG) with 23 staff ;\n๏Information  system (IS) with 8 staff;\n๏Marketing  and sales (MS) with 50 staff;\n๏Accounting and auditing  (AA) with 15 staff.\n•In total,  the Beirut branch has 108 staff. The network  allocated  for the branch is \n192.168.100.0/24. While taking into account the evolution  of the branch, divide  the \nnetwork  into several  sub-networks  according  to the departments.\n•You should fill the below  table  for each department/  sub-network.  Briefly explain \nthe different  choices.\n44\nDept. \nName\nNetwork \naddress\nPrefix \nlength\nUsableIP address  range\n(First –Last)\nBroadcast address\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nForwarding -Routing\n223.1.1.1\n223.1.1.3\n223.1.1.4\n223.1.2.2\n223.1.2.1\n223.1.2.6\n223.1.3.2\n223.1.3.1\n223.1.3.27\n223.1.1.2\n223.1.7.0\n223.1.7.1\n223.1.8.0223.1.8.1\n223.1.9.1\n223.1.9.2\nDestination \nNetwork\nNext hopInterface\n0.0.0.0223.1.1.3FastEthernet\nFastEthernet\nDestination \nNetwork\nNext hopInterface\n223.1.3.0/24223.1.7.1FastEthernet0/0\n223.1.2.0/24223.1.9.1FastEthernet0/1\n45\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIntroduction to Routing\nStatic Routing\n•Static Route Characteristics:\n๏Must be configured manually\n๏Must be adjusted manually by \nthe administrator when there \nis a change in the topology\n๏Good for small non-redundant \nnetworks\n๏Often used in conjunction \nwith a dynamic routing \nprotocolfor configuring a \ndefault route\n46\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIntroduction to Routing\nDynamic Routing\n•Dynamic Routes Automatically:\n๏Discover remote networks\n๏Maintain up-to-date \ninformation\n๏Choose the best path to the \ndestination\n๏Find new best paths when \nthere is a topology change\n๏Dynamic routing can also \nshare static default routes \nwith the other routers.\n47\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nAddress Resolution -ARP\n48\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nMAC addresses and ARP\n•IP address: \n๏“Low” Network-layer address for interface\n๏Used for layer 3 (network layer) forwarding\n•MAC (or LAN or physical or Ethernet) address: \n๏Function: used “locally” to get frame from one interface to \nanother physically-connected interface (same network, in \nIP-addressing sense)\n๏48 bit MAC address (for most LANs) burned in NIC ROM, \nalso sometimes software settable\n๏e.g.: 1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD\nhexadecimal (base 16) notation\n(each “numeral” represents 4 bits)\n49\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nLAN addresses and ARP\neach adapter on LAN has unique LANaddress\nadapter\n1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD\n58-23-D7-FA-20-B0\n0C-C4-11-6F-E3-98\n71-65-F7-2B-08-53\nLAN\n(wired or\nwireless)\n50\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nLAN addresses (more)\n•MAC address allocation administered by IEEE\n•Manufacturer buys portion of MAC address space (to \nassure uniqueness)\n•Analogy:\n๏MAC address: like Social Security Number\n๏IP address: like postal address\n•MAC flat address  ➜portability \n๏can move LAN card from one LAN to another\n•IP hierarchical address not portable\n๏address depends on IP subnet to which node is attached\n51\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nARP: Address Resolution Protocol\n•ARP table: each IP node (host, \nrouter) on LAN has a ARP table\n–IP/MAC address mappings for some \nLAN nodes:\n•< IP address; MAC address; TTL>\n–TTL (Time To Live): time after which \naddress mapping will be forgotten \n(typically 20 min)\nQuestion:how to determine\ninterface’s MAC address, \nknowing its IP address?\n1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD\n58-23-D7-FA-20-B0\n0C-C4-11-6F-E3-98\n71-65-F7-2B-08-53\nLAN\n137.196.7.23\n137.196.7.78\n137.196.7.14\n137.196.7.88\nIP addressMAC addressTTL\n137.196.7.1458-23-D7-FA-20-B0\n20\n52\nUse arpcommand to display ARP table on Windows or Linux\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nARP protocol: same LAN\n1.A wants to send datagram to B\n๏B’s MAC address not in A’s ARP table.\n2.A broadcasts ARP query packet, containing B's IP address \n๏Destination MAC address = FF-FF-FF-FF-FF-FF\n๏All nodes on LAN receive ARP query \n3.B receives ARP packet, replies to A with its (B's) MAC address\n๏frame sent to A’s MAC address (unicast)\n4.A caches (saves) IP-to-MAC address pair in its ARP table until \ninformation becomes old (times out) \n๏soft state: information that times out (goes away) unless refreshed\n•ARP is “plug-and-play”:\n๏Nodes create their ARP tables without intervention from net \nadministrator\n53\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nARP operation\n54\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nHardware Type –\nEthernet is type 1\nProtocol Type-\nIPv4=x0800\nHardware Length: \nlength of Ethernet \nAddress (6)\nProtocol Length: \nlength of IPv4 \naddress (4)\nARP packet\n55\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nThe ARP packet is encapsulated within an Ethernet packet.\nNote: Type field for Ethernet is x0806\nEncapsulation of ARP packet\n56\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nFour cases using ARP\n57\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nARP Example \n58\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nARP –A each step\nARP: Who has this IP?\nARP: Who has this IP?\nARP: Who has this IP?\n59\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nDefault Gateways\n•Devices need the following information \nfor network access: IP address, subnet \nmask, and default gateway.\n•When a host sends a packet to a device \nthat is on the same IP network, the packet \nis forwarded out the host interface to the \ndestination device. The router does not \nneed to get involved.\n•When a host sends a packet to a device on \na different IP network, the packet is \nforwarded to the default gateway because \nthe host device cannot communicate with \ndevices outside of the local network.\n•The default gateway is the device that \nroutes traffic from the local network to \ndevices on remote networks, such as \ndevices on the Internet.\nRouters are also usually configured with their own default gateway.\n60\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\n•walkthrough: send datagram from A to B via R\n–Focus on addressing –at IP (datagram) and MAC layer \n(frame)\n–Assume A knows B’s IP address\n–Assume A knows IP address of first hop router, R (how?)\n–Assume A knows R’s MAC address (how?)\nR\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\n222.222.222.220\n111.111.111.110\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\n111.111.111.112\n111.111.111.111\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nA\n222.222.222.222\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\n222.222.222.221\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\nB\n61\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\n•A creates IP datagram with IP source A, destination B \n•A creates link-layer frame with R's MAC address as \ndestination address, frame contains A-to-B IP datagram\nR\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\n222.222.222.220\n111.111.111.110\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\n111.111.111.112\n111.111.111.111\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nA\n222.222.222.222\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\n222.222.222.221\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\nB\nIP\nEth\nPhy\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\nMAC src: 74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nMAC dest: E6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\n62\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nR\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\n222.222.222.220\n111.111.111.110\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\n111.111.111.112\n111.111.111.111\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nA\n222.222.222.222\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\n222.222.222.221\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\nB\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\n•Frame sent from A to R\n•Frame received at R, datagram removed, passed \nup to IP\nIP\nEth\nPhy\nIP\nEth\nPhy\nMAC src: 74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nMAC dest: E6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\n63\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nR\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\n222.222.222.220\n111.111.111.110\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\n111.111.111.112\n111.111.111.111\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nA\n222.222.222.222\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\n222.222.222.221\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\nB\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\n•R forwards datagram with IP source A, destination B \n•R creates link-layer frame with B's MAC address as \ndestination address, frame contains A-to-B IP \ndatagram\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\nMAC src: 1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\nMAC dest: 49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\nIP\nEth\nPhy\nIP\nEth\nPhy\n64\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nR\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\n222.222.222.220\n111.111.111.110\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\n111.111.111.112\n111.111.111.111\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nA\n222.222.222.222\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\n222.222.222.221\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\nB\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\n•R forwards datagram with IP source A, destination B \n•R creates link-layer frame with B's MAC address as \ndestination address, frame contains A-to-B IP \ndatagram\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\nMAC src: 1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\nMAC dest: 49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\nIP\nEth\nPhy\nIP\nEth\nPhy\n65\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nR\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\n222.222.222.220\n111.111.111.110\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\n111.111.111.112\n111.111.111.111\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nA\n222.222.222.222\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\n222.222.222.221\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\nB\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\n•R forwards datagram with IP source A, destination B \n•R creates link-layer frame with B's MAC address as dest, frame \ncontains A-to-B IP datagram\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\nMAC src: 1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\nMAC dest: 49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\nIP\nEth\nPhy\n* Check out the online interactive exercises for more \nexamples:  http://gaia.cs.umass.edu/kurose_ross/interactive/\n66\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIntroduction to Routing\nRouter Packet Forwarding Decision\n•What happens when the router receives the frame \nfrom the host device?\n67\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \nSend a Packet\n•PC1 must determine if the destination IPv4 address is on the same network. \n•If it is on the same network, PC1 will obtain the destination MAC address from its ARP cache or use an \nARP request.\n•Because the destination network is on a different network, PC1 forwards the packet to its default \ngateway.\n68\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \nSend a Packet\n•To determine the MAC address of the default gateway, PC1 checks its ARP table for \nthe IPv4 address of the default gateway and its corresponding MAC address. \n๏An ARP request is sent if it is not found.\n•When PC1 has the MAC address of Router R1, it can forward the packet. \n69\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \nForward to the Next Hop\n•R1 examines the destination MAC address which matches the MAC address \nof the receiving interface and copies the frame into its buffer.\n•R1 identifies the Ethernet Type field as 0x800 which indicates that the \nEthernet frame contains an IPv4 packet in the data portion of the frame.\n70\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \nForward to the Next Hop\n•R1 de-encapsulates the Ethernet frame.\n•Because the destination IPv4 address of the packet, 192.168.4.10,   does not match \nany of the directly connected networks on R1, R1 searches the routing table for a \ncorresponding route.\n๏R1’s Routing Table has a route for the 192.168.4.0/24 network.\n71\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \nForward to the Next Hop\n•The routethat R1 finds to the 192.168.4.0/24 network has a next-hopaddressof \n192.168.2.2 and an exit interface of FastEthernet0/1.\n•This will require that the IPv4 packet be encapsulated in a new Ethernet frame with \nthe destination MAC address of the IPv4 address of the next-hop router, 192.168.2.2\n72\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \nForward to the Next Hop\n•Because the exit interface is on an Ethernet network, R1 must resolve the \nnext-hop IPv4 address with a destination MAC address using ARP, assuming \nit is not in its ARP cache.\n•When R1 has the MAC address for the next-hop, the Ethernet frame is \nforwarded out of the FastEthernet0/1 interface of R1.\n73\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\nPacket Routing\n•R2 examines the destination MAC address\n๏Because it matches the MAC address of its receiving interface, R2 copies the \nframe into its buffer.\n•R2 determines that that frame contains an IPv4 packet in the data portion \nof the frame.\n74\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\nPacket Routing\n•R2 de-encapsulates the Ethernet frame.\n•Because the destination IP address is on a different network, \nthe routing table is searched to find a corresponding route for \nthe destination IPv4 address. \n75\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\nPacket Routing\n•The routing table of R2 has a routeto the 192.168.4.0/24 network \nwith a next-hop IPv4 address of 192.168.3.2 and an exit interface of \nSerial 0/0/0.   \n•Because the exit interface is not Ethernet, R2 does not have to \nresolve the next-hop IP-v4 address with a destination MAC address.\n76\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\nPacket Routing\n•The IPv4 packet is encapsulatedinto a new data link frame used by \nthe exit interface and sent out the Serial 0/0/0 exit interface.\n•Because there are no MAC addresses on serial interfaces, R2 sets the \ndata link destination address to an equivalent of a broadcast.\n77\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\nReach the Destination\n•R3 copies the data link PPP frame into its buffer.\n•R3 de-encapsulatesthe data link PPP frame.\n•R3 searches the routing table for the destination IPv4 address of the \npacket.\n78\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\nReach the Destination\n•Because the destination network is on R3’s directly connected network, the \npacket can be sent directly and does not need to be sent to another router.\n•Because the exit interface is a directly connected Ethernet network, R3 \nmust resolve the destination IPv4 address of the packet with a destination \nMAC address by either finding it in its ARP cache or send out an ARP \nrequest.\n79\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nInternet Control Message Protocol \n•The Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) \n•Specified in [RFC 792], \n•Used by hosts and routers to communicate network-\nlayer information to each other. \n•Most typical use of ICMP is for error reporting\n•Often considered part of IP, but architecturally it lies \njust above IP, as ICMP messages are carried inside IP \ndatagrams. \n๏ICMP messages are carried as IP payload\n80\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nICMP Type and Code \nTypeCode Description\n00echo reply (ping)\n30destination network unreachable\n31destination host unreachable\n32destination protocol unreachable\n33destination port unreachable\n36destination network unknown\n37destination host unknown\n80echo request (ping)\n90route advertisement\n100router discovery\n110TTL expired\n120bad IP header\n81\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nTrace Route –ICMP\n•Source sends series of UDP segments (or ICMP Echo request) to destination host\n๏First has TTL =1\n๏Second has TTL=2, etc.\n๏Unlikely port number\n•When n\nth\ndatagram arrives to n\nth\nrouter:\n๏Router discards datagram\n๏Sends to source an ICMP message (type 11, code 0)\n๏Datagram includes router IP address. Traceroute does DNS lookup to find name of router \n(if any)\n•When ICMP message arrives, source calculates RTT\n•Traceroute repeat the process 3 times (To get average RTT)\n•Stopping criterion\n๏UDP segment eventually arrives at destination host\n๏Destination returns ICMP “port unreachable” packet (type 3, code 3)\n82\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nTrace Route –ICMP\n83\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nTransport layer\nThe transport layer is responsible for delivering segments from a source process to a \nfinal destination process.\n84\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nTransport layer\n•Transport Layer Responsibilities\n๏Process-to-process delivery of entire message \n๏Port addressing \n๏Segmentation and reassembly \n๏Connection control: connectionless or connection-oriented \n๏End-to-end flow control \n๏End-to-end error control \n85\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nApplication Layer\n•The application layer is responsible for providing \nservices to the user.\n86\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nThanks !\n87","storage_path":"uploads\\1774035361135_I3304_2024_2025_Part_1__1_.pdf","summary":"Here's a detailed summary of the provided text, organized into bullet points:\n\n## I3304: Network Administration and Security\n\n*   **Instructors**: Ahmad Fadlallah, Ali RAAD\n*   **Academic Year**: 2023-2024\n*   **Reference**: Textbooks are used for the course.\n\n### Course Outline\n\nThe course covers fundamental concepts in network administration and security, structured as follows:\n\n*   **Introduction**\n    *   Introduction to the course.\n    *   Recall Network Basics (from I2208).\n*   **Network Layer**\n    *   IP packet structure (recall).\n    *   Static Routing.\n    *   Dynamic Routing Algorithms.\n    *   Dynamic Routing Protocols.\n    *   NAT (Network Address Translation).\n*   **Transport Layer**\n    *   Function of the transport layer.\n    *   UDP Protocol.\n    *   TCP Protocol:\n        *   Connection management.\n        *   Flow control.\n        *   Congestion control.\n*   **Application Layer**\n    *   HTTP protocol.\n    *   FTP protocol.\n    *   Mail protocols.\n    *   DNS.\n*   **Introduction to Security**\n    *   Security services.\n    *   Cryptography.\n    *   Digital Signature.\n    *   Principle of network security protocols.\n\n### What is the Internet?\n\n*   **\"Nuts and Bolts\" View**:\n    *   Billions of connected computing devices:\n        *   **Hosts (End Systems)**: Run network applications.\n        *   **Communication Links**: Fiber, copper, radio, satellite, characterized by **transmission rate (bandwidth)**.\n        *   **Packet Switches**: Forward packets (chunks of data); includes routers and switches.\n    *   The Internet is a \"network of networks,\" comprised of interconnected ISPs (Internet Service Providers).\n    *   **Protocols**: Control sending and receiving of messages (e.g., TCP, IP, HTTP, Skype, 802.11).\n    *   **Internet Standards**: Defined by RFCs (Request for Comments) and managed by the IETF (Internet Engineering Task Force).\n    *   **\"Fun\" Internet-connected devices**: Examples like IP picture frames, web-enabled toasters, smart refrigerators, and sensorized mattresses highlight the pervasive nature of connectivity.\n\n*   **\"Service\" View**:\n    *   An infrastructure that provides services to applications (e.g., Web, VoIP, email, games, e-commerce, social networks).\n    *   Provides a **programming interface** to applications, allowing them to \"connect\" and offering service options similar to postal services.\n\n### Protocols\n\n*   **Definition**: Protocols define the format, order of messages sent and received among network entities, and actions taken upon message transmission or receipt.\n*   **Analogy (Human vs. Network)**:\n    *   Human protocols (e.g., \"what's the time?\", introductions) involve specific messages and actions.\n    *   Network protocols govern all communication activity in the Internet, but for machines.\n\n### Why Layering?\n\n*   **Purpose**: Dealing with complex systems.\n*   **Benefits**:\n    *   **Explicit structure**: Allows identification and understanding of relationships between system pieces.\n    *   **Modularization**: Eases maintenance and updating.\n    *   **Transparency**: Changes in a layer's service implementation are transparent to the rest of the system.\n\n### Reference Models\n\n*   **Two Competing Models**:\n    *   **OSI (Open Systems Interconnection)**:\n        *   Developed by ISO (International Standards Organization).\n        *   Comprises 7 layers.\n    *   **TCP (Transfer Control Protocol)**:\n        *   Used in ARPANET and the Internet.\n        *   Comprises 5 layers.\n        *   The common mechanism that is surpassing the OSI Model in practical use.\n\n*   **Internet Protocol Stack (TCP/IP - 5 Layers)**:\n    *   **Application Layer**: Supports network applications (e.g., FTP, SMTP, HTTP).\n    *   **Transport Layer**: Process-to-process data transfer (e.g., TCP, UDP).\n    *   **Network Layer**: Routing of datagrams from source to destination (e.g., IP, routing protocols).\n    *   **Link Layer**: Data transfer between neighboring network elements (e.g., Ethernet, 802.11 (WiFi), PPP).\n    *   **Physical Layer**: Bits \"on the wire.\"\n\n*   **ISO/OSI Reference Model (Additional Layers)**:\n    *   **Presentation Layer**: Allows applications to interpret data meaning (e.g., encryption, compression, machine-specific conventions).\n    *   **Session Layer**: Handles synchronization, checkpointing, and recovery of data exchange.\n    *   **Note**: The Internet stack \"missing\" these layers; their services, if needed, must be implemented within the application itself.\n\n### Encapsulation\n\n*   **Process**: As data moves down the protocol stack, each layer adds its own header (and sometimes a trailer for the link layer) to the data received from the layer above.\n*   **Terminology**:\n    *   **Message (M)**: Application layer data.\n    *   **Segment (H_t M)**: Transport layer data with its header.\n    *   **Datagram (H_n H_t M)**: Network layer data with its header.\n    *   **Frame (H_l H_n H_t M T_l)**: Link layer data with its header and trailer.\n\n### Internet Layers: Detailed Breakdown\n\n#### Physical Layer\n\n*   **Responsibilities**:\n    *   Physical characteristics of interfaces and transmission media.\n    *   Representation of bits (without interpretation).\n    *   Data rate (number of bits per second).\n    *   Synchronization of bits.\n*   **Note**: Responsible for transmitting individual bits from one node to the next.\n\n#### Data Link Layer\n\n*   **Responsibilities**:\n    *   Defines **frames** as manageable data units.\n    *   Physical addressing (MAC addresses).\n    *   Flow control.\n    *   Error control.\n    *   Access control.\n*   **Note**: Responsible for transmitting frames from one node to the next.\n\n*   **802.3 MAC Frame Structure (Ethernet)**:\n    *   **Preamble** (7 bytes): Alternating 0s and 1s to alert the receiver and allow synchronization.\n    *   **Start Frame Delimiter (SFD)** (1 byte): 10101011, signals frame start, last chance for synchronization (last 2 bits are 11).\n    *   **Destination Address (DA)** (6 bytes): Physical address of the destination station(s).\n    *   **Source Address (SA)** (6 bytes): Physical address of the sender.\n    *   **Length/Type**: If < 1518, defines data field length; if > 1536, defines type of encapsulated PDU packet.\n    *   **Data** (46 ~ 1500 bytes): Data encapsulated from upper-layer protocols.\n    *   **CRC** (CRC-32): Error detection.\n\n#### Network Layer\n\n*   **Responsibilities**:\n    *   Source-to-destination delivery, possibly across multiple networks.\n    *   Logical addressing (IP addresses).\n    *   Routing (determining the best path).\n*   **Note**: Responsible for the delivery of packets from the original source to the final destination.\n\n*   **IPv4 (Internet Protocol version 4)**:\n    *   **Position**: Lies just above the Link Layer in the TCP/IP suite.\n    *   **Nature**: An unreliable and connectionless datagram protocol.\n    *   **Best-effort delivery**: Provides no error control or flow control (except for header error detection).\n    *   **Connectionless protocol**: Each datagram is handled independently; datagrams from the same source to destination can arrive out of order, be lost, or corrupted. Relies on higher-level protocols (e.g., TCP) to handle these issues.\n    *   **IPv4 Datagrams**: Packets at the IPv4 layer. Variable-length, consisting of a header and data.\n    *   **Header Fields (20-60 bytes)**:\n        *   **Version (VER)**: Defines the IP version (e.g., 4 for IPv4).\n        *   **Header Length (HLEN)**: Total length of the datagram header in 4-byte words.\n        *   **Type of Service (ToS)**: Specifies quality of service parameters.\n        *   **Total Length**: Total length of the datagram, including header and data.\n        *   **Identification (ID)**: Used for fragmentation and reassembly.\n        *   **Flags (FLGS)**: Used for fragmentation.\n        *   **Fragment Offset**: Indicates where in the original datagram this fragment belongs.\n        *   **Time To Live (TTL)**: Maximum number of remaining hops (decremented at each router); prevents loops.\n        *   **Protocol**: Defines the higher-level protocol using IP services.\n            *   1: ICMP\n            *   2: IGMP\n            *   6: TCP\n            *   17: UDP\n            *   89: OSPF\n        *   **Header Checksum**: Error detection for the header only.\n        *   **Source IP Address** (32 bits).\n        *   **Destination IP Address** (32 bits).\n        *   **Options** (if any): E.g., timestamp, record route, specify routers to visit.\n\n*   **IPv6 Datagram**: A newer version with a different header structure (briefly shown, not detailed).\n\n*   **Subnetting with VLSM**:\n    *   **VLSM (Variable Length Subnet Mask)** allows for efficient use of IP addresses by creating subnets of different sizes.\n    *   An exercise is provided to create an IPv4 addressing plan for a company branch using subnetting based on departmental staff counts.\n\n*   **Routing**:\n    *   **Static Routing**:\n        *   **Characteristics**: Configured manually; adjusted manually by an administrator upon topology changes.\n        *   **Use Cases**: Good for small, non-redundant networks. Often used with dynamic routing for configuring a default route.\n    *   **Dynamic Routing**:\n        *   **Characteristics**: Automatically discovers remote networks; maintains up-to-date information; chooses the best path; finds new best paths upon topology changes.\n        *   Can share static default routes with other routers.\n\n*   **Address Resolution Protocol (ARP)**:\n    *   **Purpose**: Resolves an IP address to a corresponding MAC (physical) address.\n    *   **MAC (LAN/Physical/Ethernet) Address**:\n        *   Function: Used \"locally\" to get a frame from one physically connected interface to another within the same network.\n        *   Format: 48-bit address (e.g., 1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD), typically burned into the NIC ROM, sometimes software settable.\n        *   Management: Administered by IEEE, manufacturers buy portions of MAC address space.\n        *   Nature: Flat address, allowing LAN cards to be portable between LANs.\n    *   **IP Address vs. MAC Address**:\n        *   MAC address: Like a Social Security Number (flat, portable).\n        *   IP address: Like a postal address (hierarchical, depends on the IP subnet, not portable if the host moves to a different subnet).\n    *   **ARP Table**:\n        *   Each IP node (host, router) on a LAN maintains an ARP table.\n        *   Stores IP/MAC address mappings for some LAN nodes (e.g., `<IP address; MAC address; TTL>`).\n        *   **TTL (Time To Live)**: Time after which an address mapping is forgotten (typically 20 min).\n    *   **ARP Protocol (Same LAN Scenario)**:\n        1.  A wants to send a datagram to B, but B's MAC is not in A's ARP table.\n        2.  A broadcasts an ARP query packet containing B's IP address (Destination MAC address = FF-FF-FF-FF-FF-FF). All nodes on the LAN receive it.\n        3.  B receives the ARP query and replies to A with its MAC address (unicast frame).\n        4.  A caches the IP-to-MAC address pair in its ARP table until it times out (**soft state**).\n        *   **\"Plug-and-play\"**: Nodes create ARP tables without manual intervention.\n    *   **ARP Packet Structure**: Contains fields like Hardware Type (Ethernet = 1), Protocol Type (IPv4 = x0800), Hardware Length (6 for Ethernet MAC), Protocol Length (4 for IPv4).\n    *   **Encapsulation**: An ARP packet is encapsulated within an Ethernet packet (Ethernet Type field is x0806 for ARP).\n\n*   **Default Gateways**:\n    *   **Essential Information**: Devices need an IP address, subnet mask, and default gateway for network access.\n    *   **Function**:\n        *   If the destination is on the *same IP network*, the packet is forwarded directly to the destination device (router not involved).\n        *   If the destination is on a *different IP network*, the packet is forwarded to the default gateway.\n    *   The default gateway is the device (usually a router) that routes traffic from the local network to devices on remote networks (e.g., the Internet). Routers typically also have their own default gateways.\n\n*   **Packet Forwarding / Routing to another LAN (Detailed Walkthrough)**:\n    1.  **Host A to Router R**:\n        *   A creates an IP datagram (IP source A, IP destination B).\n        *   A creates a link-layer frame with R's MAC address as the destination, encapsulating the IP datagram.\n        *   Frame is sent from A to R.\n    2.  **Router R**:\n        *   R receives the frame, removes the link-layer header/trailer, and passes the IP datagram up to the IP layer.\n        *   R looks up the destination IP (B) in its routing table to determine the next hop and outgoing interface.\n        *   R creates a *new* link-layer frame (with its own MAC as source and B's MAC as destination) and encapsulates the *original* IP datagram (IP source A, IP destination B remain unchanged).\n        *   Frame is sent from R to B.\n    3.  **Host B**:\n        *   B receives the frame, removes the link-layer header/trailer, and passes the IP datagram up to the IP layer.\n        *   B processes the IP datagram.\n    *   **Key Principle**: IP source and destination addresses remain constant throughout the journey, while MAC source and destination addresses change at each hop (between directly connected devices).\n\n*   **Router Packet Forwarding Decision (Step-by-step example)**:\n    1.  **PC1 to R1 (Default Gateway)**:\n        *   PC1 determines destination is on a different network, so it forwards to its default gateway (R1).\n        *   PC1 resolves R1's IP address to its MAC address via ARP (if not in cache).\n        *   PC1 encapsulates the IPv4 packet in an Ethernet frame (dest MAC = R1's interface MAC) and sends it.\n    2.  **R1 to R2**:\n        *   R1 receives the frame, checks dest MAC (matches its interface), de-encapsulates.\n        *   R1 examines the IPv4 packet's destination IP (192.168.4.10) and searches its routing table.\n        *   R1 finds a route with a next-hop IP (192.168.2.2) and exit interface (FastEthernet0/1).\n        *   R1 resolves the next-hop IP (R2's interface IP) to its MAC address via ARP (if not in cache).\n        *   R1 encapsulates the IPv4 packet in a *new* Ethernet frame (dest MAC = R2's interface MAC) and forwards it.\n    3.  **R2 to R3**:\n        *   R2 receives the frame, de-encapsulates.\n        *   R2 searches its routing table for the destination IP.\n        *   R2 finds a route with a next-hop IP (192.168.3.2) and exit interface (Serial 0/0/0).\n        *   Since it's a serial interface (not Ethernet), R2 doesn't use MAC addresses but sets the data link destination to a broadcast equivalent.\n        *   R2 encapsulates the IPv4 packet in a *new* data link frame (e.g., PPP) and sends it out the serial interface.\n    4.  **R3 to Final Destination**:\n        *   R3 receives the PPP frame, de-encapsulates.\n        *   R3 searches its routing table for the destination IP.\n        *   R3 finds the destination network is *directly connected* to its Ethernet interface.\n        *   R3 resolves the destination host's IPv4 address to its MAC address via ARP.\n        *   R3 encapsulates the IPv4 packet in a *new* Ethernet frame (dest MAC = destination host's MAC) and delivers it directly.\n\n*   **Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP)**:\n    *   **Specification**: Specified in [RFC 792].\n    *   **Purpose**: Used by hosts and routers to communicate network-layer information to each other. Most typically for error reporting.\n    *   **Architecture**: Often considered part of IP, but architecturally lies *just above* IP, as ICMP messages are carried inside IP datagrams (as IP payload).\n    *   **Common ICMP Types and Codes**:\n        *   0, 0: Echo reply (ping)\n        *   3, 0-7: Destination network/host/protocol/port unreachable, fragmentation needed, etc.\n        *   8, 0: Echo request (ping)\n        *   11, 0: TTL expired\n        *   12, 0: Bad IP header\n\n*   **Traceroute (using ICMP)**:\n    *   **Process**:\n        1.  Source sends a series of UDP segments (or ICMP Echo requests) to the destination.\n        2.  Each segment/request has an incrementing **Time To Live (TTL)** value, starting from 1.\n        3.  When the *n*-th datagram arrives at the *n*-th router (meaning its TTL reaches 0), the router discards it.\n        4.  The router sends an ICMP \"Time Exceeded\" message (Type 11, Code 0) back to the source, including the router's IP address.\n        5.  The source calculates the Round Trip Time (RTT) based on the ICMP reply. Traceroute typically repeats this process 3 times to get an average RTT.\n        6.  The destination's IP address in the ICMP message allows for a DNS lookup to find the router's name.\n    *   **Stopping Criterion**: When the UDP segment eventually reaches the destination host, the host returns an ICMP \"Port Unreachable\" packet (Type 3, Code 3) because the chosen port number is typically unused.\n\n#### Transport Layer\n\n*   **Responsibilities**:\n    *   Process-to-process delivery of the entire message.\n    *   Port addressing (to identify specific applications).\n    *   Segmentation and reassembly of data.\n    *   Connection control (connectionless for UDP, connection-oriented for TCP).\n    *   End-to-end flow control.\n    *   End-to-end error control.\n*   **Note**: Responsible for delivering segments from a source process to a final destination process.\n\n#### Application Layer\n\n*   **Responsibility**: Providing services to the user (e.g., web browsing, file transfer, email).","timestamp":"2026-03-20 21:36:37"}
{"level":"info","message":"Mapping JSON to PDFDocument: {\"filename\":\"I3304-2024-2025-Part-1 (1).pdf\",\"file_size\":4689970,\"mime_type\":\"application/pdf\",\"storage_path\":\"uploads\\\\1774035361135_I3304_2024_2025_Part_1__1_.pdf\",\"original_text\":\"\\n\\nI3304\\nNetwork administration and \\nsecurity\\nAhmad Fadlallah\\nAli RAAD\\n1\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nReferenceTextbooks\\n2\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nOutline\\n•Introduction \\n๏Introduction to the course\\n๏Recall Network Basics (I2208)\\n•Network Layer\\n๏IP packet structure (Recall)\\n๏Static Routing\\n๏Dynamic Routing Algorithm\\n๏Dynamic Routing Protocols\\n๏NAT (Network Address Translation)\\n•Transport Layer\\n๏Function of the transport layer\\n๏UDP Protocol\\n๏TCP Protocol\\n-Connection management\\n-Flow control\\n-Congestion control\\n•Application Layer\\nHTTP protocol\\nFTP protocol\\nMail protocols\\nDNS\\n•Introduction to Security\\nSecurity services\\nCryptography\\nDigital Signature\\nPrinciple of network security \\nprotocols\\n3\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s the Internet: “nuts and bolts”view\\n•Billions of connected computing \\ndevices: \\n๏hosts = end systems \\n๏running network apps\\n•Communication links\\n๏fiber, copper, radio, satellite\\n๏transmission rate: bandwidth\\n•Packet switches: forward packets \\n(chunks of data)\\n๏Routers and switches\\nWired links\\nwireless\\nlinks\\nrouter\\nsmartphone\\nPC\\nserver\\nWireless laptop\\nmobile network\\nglobal ISP\\nregional ISP\\nhome \\nnetwork\\ninstitutional\\nnetwork\\n4\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\n“Fun” Internet-connected devices\\nIP picture frame\\nhttp://www.ceiva.com/\\nWeb-enabled  toaster +\\nweather forecaster\\nInternet phones\\nInternet \\nrefrigerator\\nSlingbox:  watch,\\ncontrol cable TV remotely\\nTweet-a-watt: \\nmonitor energy  use\\nsensorized,\\nbed\\nmattress\\n5\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s the Internet: “nuts and bolts” view\\n•Internet: “network of networks”\\n๏Interconnected ISPs\\n6\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s the Internet: “nuts and bolts” view\\n•Protocolscontrol sending, \\nreceiving of messages\\n๏e.g., TCP, IP, HTTP, Skype,  \\n802.11\\n•Internet  standards\\n๏RFC: Request for comments\\n๏IETF: Internet Engineering Task \\nForce\\nmobile network\\nglobal ISP\\nregional ISP\\nhome \\nnetwork\\ninstitutional\\nnetwork\\n7\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s the Internet: a service view\\n•Infrastructure that provides \\nservices to applications:\\n๏Web, VoIP, email, games, e-\\ncommerce, social nets, ...\\n•Provides programming \\ninterface to apps\\n๏hooks that allow sending \\nand receiving  app programs \\nto “connect”to Internet\\n๏Provides service options, \\nanalogous to postal service\\nmobile network\\nglobal ISP\\nregional ISP\\nhome \\nnetwork\\ninstitutional\\nnetwork\\n8\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s a protocol?\\n•“what’s the time?”\\n•“I have a question”\\n•introductions\\n•Machines rather than \\nhumans\\n•All communication activity \\nin Internet governed by \\nprotocols\\nHuman protocols\\nNetwork protocols\\n... specific messages sent\\n... specific actions taken when messages \\nreceived, or other events\\nprotocolsdefine format, orderof \\nmessages sent and received\\namong network entities, and \\nactions takenon message \\ntransmission, receipt\\n9\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s a protocol?\\nQ:other human protocols? \\n10\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhy layering?\\nDealing with complex systems:\\n•Explicit structure allows identification, relationship of \\ncomplex system’s pieces\\n•Modularizationeases maintenance, updating of \\nsystem\\n๏Change of implementation of layer’s service \\ntransparent to rest of system\\n11\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nAnalogy\\nIk vind \\nkonijnen \\nleuk\\nL: Ducth\\nFax:#\\nIk vind \\nkonijnen \\nleuk\\nL: Dutch\\nI like \\nrabbits\\nMessage\\nInformation \\nfor the \\nremote \\ntranslator\\nInformation \\nfor the \\nremote \\nsecretary\\nIk vind \\nkonijnen \\nleuk\\nL: Ducth\\nFax:#\\nIk vind \\nkonijnen \\nleuk\\nL: Ducth\\nJ’aime \\nbien les \\nlapins\\nArabic & English\\nChinese & French\\nProfessor B\\nTranslator\\nSecretary\\nuse fax\\nuse Dutch\\nSecretary\\nTranslator\\nProfessor A\\n12\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nReference Models\\n•There are two competing models for how the \\nsoftware is layered: the OSIand the TCPmodels.  \\n•OSI (Open Systems Interconnection)\\n๏Developed by ISO (International Standards \\nOrganization)\\n๏7 layers\\n•TCP (Transfer Control Protocol)\\n๏Used in the ARPANET and in the Internet.  \\n๏Common mechanism that is surpassing the OSI Model.  \\n๏5 layers\\n13\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nReference Models\\n14\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nInternet Protocol Stack\\n•Application: supporting network applications\\n๏FTP, SMTP, HTTP\\n•Transport: process-process data transfer\\n๏TCP, UDP\\n•Network: routing of datagrams from source \\nto destination\\n๏IP, routing protocols\\n•Link: data transfer between neighboring  \\nnetwork elements\\n๏Ethernet, 802.111 (WiFi), PPP\\n•Physical: bits “on the wire”\\n15\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nISO/OSI reference model\\n•Presentation: allow applications to \\ninterpret meaning of data, e.g., \\nencryption, compression, machine-\\nspecific conventions\\n•Session: synchronization, check-\\npointing, recovery of data exchange\\n•Internet stack “missing”these \\nlayers!\\n๏these services, if needed, must be \\nimplemented in application\\n๏needed?\\n16\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nsource\\napplication\\ntransport\\nnetwork\\nlink\\nphysical\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nM\\nsegment\\nH\\nt\\ndatagram\\ndestination\\napplication\\ntransport\\nnetwork\\nlink\\nphysical\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nH\\nl\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nM\\nM\\nnetwork\\nlink\\nphysical\\nlink\\nphysical\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nH\\nl\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nH\\nl\\nM\\nrouter\\nswitch\\nEncapsulation\\nmessage\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nM\\nH\\nn\\nframe\\n17\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nReference Models\\n•Headers, Data, and Trailers\\n•Encapsulation\\n18\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTCP/IP MODEL\\n19\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nInternet Layers\\n•Internet Model\\n๏Dominant model in data communications and networking \\n๏5 ordered layers; often referred to as TCP/IP protocol suite \\n20\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nInternet Layers\\n21\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nPeer-to-Peer Processes\\n22\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nAn exchange using the Internet model\\n23\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nPhysical Layer\\n•Physical characteristics of interfaces and media \\n๏Representation of bits without interpretation \\n๏Data rate: number of bits per second \\n๏Synchronization of bits \\n24\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nThe physical layer is responsible  for \\ntransmitting  individual bits from one \\nnode to the next.\\nNote:\\n25\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTransmission Media\\n26\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nData link Layer\\nData Link Layer Responsibilities\\n•Defines framesinto manageable data units \\n๏Physical addressing \\n๏Flow control \\n๏Error control \\n๏Access control \\n27\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nThe data link layer is responsible for \\ntransmitting  frames from \\none node to the next.\\nNote:\\n28\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nNode-to-Node delivery\\n29\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\n802.3 MAC frame\\n•Preamble–7 bytesof alternating 0s and 1s to alert the receiver and allow it to \\nsynchronize\\n•Start Frame Delimiter (SFD) –1 byte –10101011 signals the beginning of a frame, \\nlast chance for synchronization –last 2 bits are 11\\n•Destination address (DA) –6 bytes –contains the physical address of the destination \\nstation or stations\\n•Source address (SA) –6 bytes –contains the physical address of the sender\\n•Length/type–if less than 1518 then it defines the length of the data field –if more \\nthan 1536 then it defines the type of the PDU packet that is encapsulated\\n•Data–data encapsulated from upper-layer protocols : 46 ~ 1500 bytes\\n•CRC–CRC-32\\n30\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nNetwork layer\\n•Network Layer Responsibilities\\n๏Source-to-destination delivery, possibly across multiple \\nnetworks \\n๏Logical addressing \\n๏Routing\\n31\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nThe network layer is responsible  for \\nthe delivery of packets from  the \\noriginal source to the \\nfinal destination.\\nNote:\\n32\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSource-to-Destination delivery\\n33\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nPosition of IPv4 in TCP/IP protocol suite\\nIPv4\\n34\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv4\\n•Best-effort delivery\\n๏IPv4 is an unreliableand connectionlessdatagram protocol\\n๏Abest-effort delivery service.\\n๏best-effort IPv4 provides no error control or flow control(except for \\nerror detection on the header).\\n•Connectionless protocol\\n๏Each datagram is handled independently\\n๏Datagrams sent by the source to the same destination could\\n-Arrive out of order\\n-be lost or corrupted during transmission.\\n๏IPv4 relies on a high-level protocol to take of all these problem.\\n35\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv4 Datagrams\\n•Packets in the IPv4 layer are called Datagrams.\\n36\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nver\\nlength\\n32 bits\\ndata \\n(variable  length,\\ntypically a TCP \\nor UDP segment)\\n16-bit identifier\\nInternet\\nchecksum\\ntime to\\nlive\\n32 bit source IP address\\nIP protocol version number\\nheader length (bytes)\\nmax number\\nremaining hops\\n(decremented at \\neach router)\\nfor\\nfragmentation/\\nreassembly\\ntotal datagram\\nlength (bytes)\\nupper layer protocol\\nto deliver payload to\\nhead.\\nlen\\ntype of\\nservice\\n“type” of data \\nflgs\\nfragment\\noffset\\nupper\\nlayer\\n32 bit destination IP address\\nOptions (if any)\\nE.g. timestamp,\\nrecord route\\ntaken, specify\\nlist of routers \\nto visit.\\nhow much overhead \\nwith TCP?\\n20 bytes of TCP\\n20 bytes of IP\\n= 40 bytes + app \\nlayer overhead\\nIP datagram format\\n37\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv4 Datagram (cont’d)\\n•A datagram is a variable-length packet consisting of a \\nheaderand data.\\n•Header\\n๏Length : 20 –60 bytes\\n๏Contains information essential to routing and delivery.\\n•Version (VER) : It defines the Version of IPv4. it is 4.\\n•Header Length (HLEN) : Defining the total length of \\nthe datagram header in 4-byte words.\\n38\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv4 Datagram (cont’d)\\n•Protocol \\n๏Defining the higher level protocol that uses the \\nservices of the IP layer\\n-TCP, UDP, ICMP, and IGMP\\n-Multiplexing data from different higher level protocols\\nValueProtocol\\n1ICMP\\n2IGMP\\n6TCP\\n8EGP\\n17UDP\\n89OSPF\\n39\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv6 Datagram\\n40\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv6 Datagram\\n41\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSubnet with VLSM\\n192.168.10.0/24\\n42\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nRegular Subnet\\n7subnets; The largest subnet needs 60hosts \\nIf 3bits for subnet (8 subnets) 5bits for host (32 hosts)\\nIf 6bits for host (64 hosts) 2bits for subnet (4 subnets)\\n192.168.10.0/24\\n43\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nExercise\\n•A multinational  company  wishes to have an IPv4 addressing  plan for the new \\nbranch it has created  in Beirut. The Beirut branch has 5 departments  as follows:\\n๏Human Resources  Management  (HRM) with 12 staff;\\n๏Engineering  (ENG) with 23 staff ;\\n๏Information  system (IS) with 8 staff;\\n๏Marketing  and sales (MS) with 50 staff;\\n๏Accounting and auditing  (AA) with 15 staff.\\n•In total,  the Beirut branch has 108 staff. The network  allocated  for the branch is \\n192.168.100.0/24. While taking into account the evolution  of the branch, divide  the \\nnetwork  into several  sub-networks  according  to the departments.\\n•You should fill the below  table  for each department/  sub-network.  Briefly explain \\nthe different  choices.\\n44\\nDept. \\nName\\nNetwork \\naddress\\nPrefix \\nlength\\nUsableIP address  range\\n(First –Last)\\nBroadcast address\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nForwarding -Routing\\n223.1.1.1\\n223.1.1.3\\n223.1.1.4\\n223.1.2.2\\n223.1.2.1\\n223.1.2.6\\n223.1.3.2\\n223.1.3.1\\n223.1.3.27\\n223.1.1.2\\n223.1.7.0\\n223.1.7.1\\n223.1.8.0223.1.8.1\\n223.1.9.1\\n223.1.9.2\\nDestination \\nNetwork\\nNext hopInterface\\n0.0.0.0223.1.1.3FastEthernet\\nFastEthernet\\nDestination \\nNetwork\\nNext hopInterface\\n223.1.3.0/24223.1.7.1FastEthernet0/0\\n223.1.2.0/24223.1.9.1FastEthernet0/1\\n45\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIntroduction to Routing\\nStatic Routing\\n•Static Route Characteristics:\\n๏Must be configured manually\\n๏Must be adjusted manually by \\nthe administrator when there \\nis a change in the topology\\n๏Good for small non-redundant \\nnetworks\\n๏Often used in conjunction \\nwith a dynamic routing \\nprotocolfor configuring a \\ndefault route\\n46\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIntroduction to Routing\\nDynamic Routing\\n•Dynamic Routes Automatically:\\n๏Discover remote networks\\n๏Maintain up-to-date \\ninformation\\n๏Choose the best path to the \\ndestination\\n๏Find new best paths when \\nthere is a topology change\\n๏Dynamic routing can also \\nshare static default routes \\nwith the other routers.\\n47\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nAddress Resolution -ARP\\n48\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nMAC addresses and ARP\\n•IP address: \\n๏“Low” Network-layer address for interface\\n๏Used for layer 3 (network layer) forwarding\\n•MAC (or LAN or physical or Ethernet) address: \\n๏Function: used “locally” to get frame from one interface to \\nanother physically-connected interface (same network, in \\nIP-addressing sense)\\n๏48 bit MAC address (for most LANs) burned in NIC ROM, \\nalso sometimes software settable\\n๏e.g.: 1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD\\nhexadecimal (base 16) notation\\n(each “numeral” represents 4 bits)\\n49\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nLAN addresses and ARP\\neach adapter on LAN has unique LANaddress\\nadapter\\n1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD\\n58-23-D7-FA-20-B0\\n0C-C4-11-6F-E3-98\\n71-65-F7-2B-08-53\\nLAN\\n(wired or\\nwireless)\\n50\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nLAN addresses (more)\\n•MAC address allocation administered by IEEE\\n•Manufacturer buys portion of MAC address space (to \\nassure uniqueness)\\n•Analogy:\\n๏MAC address: like Social Security Number\\n๏IP address: like postal address\\n•MAC flat address  ➜portability \\n๏can move LAN card from one LAN to another\\n•IP hierarchical address not portable\\n๏address depends on IP subnet to which node is attached\\n51\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nARP: Address Resolution Protocol\\n•ARP table: each IP node (host, \\nrouter) on LAN has a ARP table\\n–IP/MAC address mappings for some \\nLAN nodes:\\n•< IP address; MAC address; TTL>\\n–TTL (Time To Live): time after which \\naddress mapping will be forgotten \\n(typically 20 min)\\nQuestion:how to determine\\ninterface’s MAC address, \\nknowing its IP address?\\n1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD\\n58-23-D7-FA-20-B0\\n0C-C4-11-6F-E3-98\\n71-65-F7-2B-08-53\\nLAN\\n137.196.7.23\\n137.196.7.78\\n137.196.7.14\\n137.196.7.88\\nIP addressMAC addressTTL\\n137.196.7.1458-23-D7-FA-20-B0\\n20\\n52\\nUse arpcommand to display ARP table on Windows or Linux\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nARP protocol: same LAN\\n1.A wants to send datagram to B\\n๏B’s MAC address not in A’s ARP table.\\n2.A broadcasts ARP query packet, containing B's IP address \\n๏Destination MAC address = FF-FF-FF-FF-FF-FF\\n๏All nodes on LAN receive ARP query \\n3.B receives ARP packet, replies to A with its (B's) MAC address\\n๏frame sent to A’s MAC address (unicast)\\n4.A caches (saves) IP-to-MAC address pair in its ARP table until \\ninformation becomes old (times out) \\n๏soft state: information that times out (goes away) unless refreshed\\n•ARP is “plug-and-play”:\\n๏Nodes create their ARP tables without intervention from net \\nadministrator\\n53\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nARP operation\\n54\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nHardware Type –\\nEthernet is type 1\\nProtocol Type-\\nIPv4=x0800\\nHardware Length: \\nlength of Ethernet \\nAddress (6)\\nProtocol Length: \\nlength of IPv4 \\naddress (4)\\nARP packet\\n55\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nThe ARP packet is encapsulated within an Ethernet packet.\\nNote: Type field for Ethernet is x0806\\nEncapsulation of ARP packet\\n56\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nFour cases using ARP\\n57\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nARP Example \\n58\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nARP –A each step\\nARP: Who has this IP?\\nARP: Who has this IP?\\nARP: Who has this IP?\\n59\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nDefault Gateways\\n•Devices need the following information \\nfor network access: IP address, subnet \\nmask, and default gateway.\\n•When a host sends a packet to a device \\nthat is on the same IP network, the packet \\nis forwarded out the host interface to the \\ndestination device. The router does not \\nneed to get involved.\\n•When a host sends a packet to a device on \\na different IP network, the packet is \\nforwarded to the default gateway because \\nthe host device cannot communicate with \\ndevices outside of the local network.\\n•The default gateway is the device that \\nroutes traffic from the local network to \\ndevices on remote networks, such as \\ndevices on the Internet.\\nRouters are also usually configured with their own default gateway.\\n60\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•walkthrough: send datagram from A to B via R\\n–Focus on addressing –at IP (datagram) and MAC layer \\n(frame)\\n–Assume A knows B’s IP address\\n–Assume A knows IP address of first hop router, R (how?)\\n–Assume A knows R’s MAC address (how?)\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\n61\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•A creates IP datagram with IP source A, destination B \\n•A creates link-layer frame with R's MAC address as \\ndestination address, frame contains A-to-B IP datagram\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\nMAC src: 74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nMAC dest: E6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\n62\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•Frame sent from A to R\\n•Frame received at R, datagram removed, passed \\nup to IP\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\nMAC src: 74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nMAC dest: E6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\n63\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•R forwards datagram with IP source A, destination B \\n•R creates link-layer frame with B's MAC address as \\ndestination address, frame contains A-to-B IP \\ndatagram\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\nMAC src: 1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\nMAC dest: 49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\n64\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•R forwards datagram with IP source A, destination B \\n•R creates link-layer frame with B's MAC address as \\ndestination address, frame contains A-to-B IP \\ndatagram\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\nMAC src: 1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\nMAC dest: 49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\n65\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•R forwards datagram with IP source A, destination B \\n•R creates link-layer frame with B's MAC address as dest, frame \\ncontains A-to-B IP datagram\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\nMAC src: 1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\nMAC dest: 49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\n* Check out the online interactive exercises for more \\nexamples:  http://gaia.cs.umass.edu/kurose_ross/interactive/\\n66\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIntroduction to Routing\\nRouter Packet Forwarding Decision\\n•What happens when the router receives the frame \\nfrom the host device?\\n67\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nSend a Packet\\n•PC1 must determine if the destination IPv4 address is on the same network. \\n•If it is on the same network, PC1 will obtain the destination MAC address from its ARP cache or use an \\nARP request.\\n•Because the destination network is on a different network, PC1 forwards the packet to its default \\ngateway.\\n68\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nSend a Packet\\n•To determine the MAC address of the default gateway, PC1 checks its ARP table for \\nthe IPv4 address of the default gateway and its corresponding MAC address. \\n๏An ARP request is sent if it is not found.\\n•When PC1 has the MAC address of Router R1, it can forward the packet. \\n69\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nForward to the Next Hop\\n•R1 examines the destination MAC address which matches the MAC address \\nof the receiving interface and copies the frame into its buffer.\\n•R1 identifies the Ethernet Type field as 0x800 which indicates that the \\nEthernet frame contains an IPv4 packet in the data portion of the frame.\\n70\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nForward to the Next Hop\\n•R1 de-encapsulates the Ethernet frame.\\n•Because the destination IPv4 address of the packet, 192.168.4.10,   does not match \\nany of the directly connected networks on R1, R1 searches the routing table for a \\ncorresponding route.\\n๏R1’s Routing Table has a route for the 192.168.4.0/24 network.\\n71\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nForward to the Next Hop\\n•The routethat R1 finds to the 192.168.4.0/24 network has a next-hopaddressof \\n192.168.2.2 and an exit interface of FastEthernet0/1.\\n•This will require that the IPv4 packet be encapsulated in a new Ethernet frame with \\nthe destination MAC address of the IPv4 address of the next-hop router, 192.168.2.2\\n72\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nForward to the Next Hop\\n•Because the exit interface is on an Ethernet network, R1 must resolve the \\nnext-hop IPv4 address with a destination MAC address using ARP, assuming \\nit is not in its ARP cache.\\n•When R1 has the MAC address for the next-hop, the Ethernet frame is \\nforwarded out of the FastEthernet0/1 interface of R1.\\n73\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nPacket Routing\\n•R2 examines the destination MAC address\\n๏Because it matches the MAC address of its receiving interface, R2 copies the \\nframe into its buffer.\\n•R2 determines that that frame contains an IPv4 packet in the data portion \\nof the frame.\\n74\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nPacket Routing\\n•R2 de-encapsulates the Ethernet frame.\\n•Because the destination IP address is on a different network, \\nthe routing table is searched to find a corresponding route for \\nthe destination IPv4 address. \\n75\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nPacket Routing\\n•The routing table of R2 has a routeto the 192.168.4.0/24 network \\nwith a next-hop IPv4 address of 192.168.3.2 and an exit interface of \\nSerial 0/0/0.   \\n•Because the exit interface is not Ethernet, R2 does not have to \\nresolve the next-hop IP-v4 address with a destination MAC address.\\n76\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nPacket Routing\\n•The IPv4 packet is encapsulatedinto a new data link frame used by \\nthe exit interface and sent out the Serial 0/0/0 exit interface.\\n•Because there are no MAC addresses on serial interfaces, R2 sets the \\ndata link destination address to an equivalent of a broadcast.\\n77\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nReach the Destination\\n•R3 copies the data link PPP frame into its buffer.\\n•R3 de-encapsulatesthe data link PPP frame.\\n•R3 searches the routing table for the destination IPv4 address of the \\npacket.\\n78\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nReach the Destination\\n•Because the destination network is on R3’s directly connected network, the \\npacket can be sent directly and does not need to be sent to another router.\\n•Because the exit interface is a directly connected Ethernet network, R3 \\nmust resolve the destination IPv4 address of the packet with a destination \\nMAC address by either finding it in its ARP cache or send out an ARP \\nrequest.\\n79\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nInternet Control Message Protocol \\n•The Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) \\n•Specified in [RFC 792], \\n•Used by hosts and routers to communicate network-\\nlayer information to each other. \\n•Most typical use of ICMP is for error reporting\\n•Often considered part of IP, but architecturally it lies \\njust above IP, as ICMP messages are carried inside IP \\ndatagrams. \\n๏ICMP messages are carried as IP payload\\n80\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nICMP Type and Code \\nTypeCode Description\\n00echo reply (ping)\\n30destination network unreachable\\n31destination host unreachable\\n32destination protocol unreachable\\n33destination port unreachable\\n36destination network unknown\\n37destination host unknown\\n80echo request (ping)\\n90route advertisement\\n100router discovery\\n110TTL expired\\n120bad IP header\\n81\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTrace Route –ICMP\\n•Source sends series of UDP segments (or ICMP Echo request) to destination host\\n๏First has TTL =1\\n๏Second has TTL=2, etc.\\n๏Unlikely port number\\n•When n\\nth\\ndatagram arrives to n\\nth\\nrouter:\\n๏Router discards datagram\\n๏Sends to source an ICMP message (type 11, code 0)\\n๏Datagram includes router IP address. Traceroute does DNS lookup to find name of router \\n(if any)\\n•When ICMP message arrives, source calculates RTT\\n•Traceroute repeat the process 3 times (To get average RTT)\\n•Stopping criterion\\n๏UDP segment eventually arrives at destination host\\n๏Destination returns ICMP “port unreachable” packet (type 3, code 3)\\n82\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTrace Route –ICMP\\n83\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTransport layer\\nThe transport layer is responsible for delivering segments from a source process to a \\nfinal destination process.\\n84\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTransport layer\\n•Transport Layer Responsibilities\\n๏Process-to-process delivery of entire message \\n๏Port addressing \\n๏Segmentation and reassembly \\n๏Connection control: connectionless or connection-oriented \\n๏End-to-end flow control \\n๏End-to-end error control \\n85\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nApplication Layer\\n•The application layer is responsible for providing \\nservices to the user.\\n86\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nThanks !\\n87\",\"summary\":\"Here's a detailed summary of the provided text, organized into bullet points:\\n\\n## I3304: Network Administration and Security\\n\\n*   **Instructors**: Ahmad Fadlallah, Ali RAAD\\n*   **Academic Year**: 2023-2024\\n*   **Reference**: Textbooks are used for the course.\\n\\n### Course Outline\\n\\nThe course covers fundamental concepts in network administration and security, structured as follows:\\n\\n*   **Introduction**\\n    *   Introduction to the course.\\n    *   Recall Network Basics (from I2208).\\n*   **Network Layer**\\n    *   IP packet structure (recall).\\n    *   Static Routing.\\n    *   Dynamic Routing Algorithms.\\n    *   Dynamic Routing Protocols.\\n    *   NAT (Network Address Translation).\\n*   **Transport Layer**\\n    *   Function of the transport layer.\\n    *   UDP Protocol.\\n    *   TCP Protocol:\\n        *   Connection management.\\n        *   Flow control.\\n        *   Congestion control.\\n*   **Application Layer**\\n    *   HTTP protocol.\\n    *   FTP protocol.\\n    *   Mail protocols.\\n    *   DNS.\\n*   **Introduction to Security**\\n    *   Security services.\\n    *   Cryptography.\\n    *   Digital Signature.\\n    *   Principle of network security protocols.\\n\\n### What is the Internet?\\n\\n*   **\\\"Nuts and Bolts\\\" View**:\\n    *   Billions of connected computing devices:\\n        *   **Hosts (End Systems)**: Run network applications.\\n        *   **Communication Links**: Fiber, copper, radio, satellite, characterized by **transmission rate (bandwidth)**.\\n        *   **Packet Switches**: Forward packets (chunks of data); includes routers and switches.\\n    *   The Internet is a \\\"network of networks,\\\" comprised of interconnected ISPs (Internet Service Providers).\\n    *   **Protocols**: Control sending and receiving of messages (e.g., TCP, IP, HTTP, Skype, 802.11).\\n    *   **Internet Standards**: Defined by RFCs (Request for Comments) and managed by the IETF (Internet Engineering Task Force).\\n    *   **\\\"Fun\\\" Internet-connected devices**: Examples like IP picture frames, web-enabled toasters, smart refrigerators, and sensorized mattresses highlight the pervasive nature of connectivity.\\n\\n*   **\\\"Service\\\" View**:\\n    *   An infrastructure that provides services to applications (e.g., Web, VoIP, email, games, e-commerce, social networks).\\n    *   Provides a **programming interface** to applications, allowing them to \\\"connect\\\" and offering service options similar to postal services.\\n\\n### Protocols\\n\\n*   **Definition**: Protocols define the format, order of messages sent and received among network entities, and actions taken upon message transmission or receipt.\\n*   **Analogy (Human vs. Network)**:\\n    *   Human protocols (e.g., \\\"what's the time?\\\", introductions) involve specific messages and actions.\\n    *   Network protocols govern all communication activity in the Internet, but for machines.\\n\\n### Why Layering?\\n\\n*   **Purpose**: Dealing with complex systems.\\n*   **Benefits**:\\n    *   **Explicit structure**: Allows identification and understanding of relationships between system pieces.\\n    *   **Modularization**: Eases maintenance and updating.\\n    *   **Transparency**: Changes in a layer's service implementation are transparent to the rest of the system.\\n\\n### Reference Models\\n\\n*   **Two Competing Models**:\\n    *   **OSI (Open Systems Interconnection)**:\\n        *   Developed by ISO (International Standards Organization).\\n        *   Comprises 7 layers.\\n    *   **TCP (Transfer Control Protocol)**:\\n        *   Used in ARPANET and the Internet.\\n        *   Comprises 5 layers.\\n        *   The common mechanism that is surpassing the OSI Model in practical use.\\n\\n*   **Internet Protocol Stack (TCP/IP - 5 Layers)**:\\n    *   **Application Layer**: Supports network applications (e.g., FTP, SMTP, HTTP).\\n    *   **Transport Layer**: Process-to-process data transfer (e.g., TCP, UDP).\\n    *   **Network Layer**: Routing of datagrams from source to destination (e.g., IP, routing protocols).\\n    *   **Link Layer**: Data transfer between neighboring network elements (e.g., Ethernet, 802.11 (WiFi), PPP).\\n    *   **Physical Layer**: Bits \\\"on the wire.\\\"\\n\\n*   **ISO/OSI Reference Model (Additional Layers)**:\\n    *   **Presentation Layer**: Allows applications to interpret data meaning (e.g., encryption, compression, machine-specific conventions).\\n    *   **Session Layer**: Handles synchronization, checkpointing, and recovery of data exchange.\\n    *   **Note**: The Internet stack \\\"missing\\\" these layers; their services, if needed, must be implemented within the application itself.\\n\\n### Encapsulation\\n\\n*   **Process**: As data moves down the protocol stack, each layer adds its own header (and sometimes a trailer for the link layer) to the data received from the layer above.\\n*   **Terminology**:\\n    *   **Message (M)**: Application layer data.\\n    *   **Segment (H_t M)**: Transport layer data with its header.\\n    *   **Datagram (H_n H_t M)**: Network layer data with its header.\\n    *   **Frame (H_l H_n H_t M T_l)**: Link layer data with its header and trailer.\\n\\n### Internet Layers: Detailed Breakdown\\n\\n#### Physical Layer\\n\\n*   **Responsibilities**:\\n    *   Physical characteristics of interfaces and transmission media.\\n    *   Representation of bits (without interpretation).\\n    *   Data rate (number of bits per second).\\n    *   Synchronization of bits.\\n*   **Note**: Responsible for transmitting individual bits from one node to the next.\\n\\n#### Data Link Layer\\n\\n*   **Responsibilities**:\\n    *   Defines **frames** as manageable data units.\\n    *   Physical addressing (MAC addresses).\\n    *   Flow control.\\n    *   Error control.\\n    *   Access control.\\n*   **Note**: Responsible for transmitting frames from one node to the next.\\n\\n*   **802.3 MAC Frame Structure (Ethernet)**:\\n    *   **Preamble** (7 bytes): Alternating 0s and 1s to alert the receiver and allow synchronization.\\n    *   **Start Frame Delimiter (SFD)** (1 byte): 10101011, signals frame start, last chance for synchronization (last 2 bits are 11).\\n    *   **Destination Address (DA)** (6 bytes): Physical address of the destination station(s).\\n    *   **Source Address (SA)** (6 bytes): Physical address of the sender.\\n    *   **Length/Type**: If < 1518, defines data field length; if > 1536, defines type of encapsulated PDU packet.\\n    *   **Data** (46 ~ 1500 bytes): Data encapsulated from upper-layer protocols.\\n    *   **CRC** (CRC-32): Error detection.\\n\\n#### Network Layer\\n\\n*   **Responsibilities**:\\n    *   Source-to-destination delivery, possibly across multiple networks.\\n    *   Logical addressing (IP addresses).\\n    *   Routing (determining the best path).\\n*   **Note**: Responsible for the delivery of packets from the original source to the final destination.\\n\\n*   **IPv4 (Internet Protocol version 4)**:\\n    *   **Position**: Lies just above the Link Layer in the TCP/IP suite.\\n    *   **Nature**: An unreliable and connectionless datagram protocol.\\n    *   **Best-effort delivery**: Provides no error control or flow control (except for header error detection).\\n    *   **Connectionless protocol**: Each datagram is handled independently; datagrams from the same source to destination can arrive out of order, be lost, or corrupted. Relies on higher-level protocols (e.g., TCP) to handle these issues.\\n    *   **IPv4 Datagrams**: Packets at the IPv4 layer. Variable-length, consisting of a header and data.\\n    *   **Header Fields (20-60 bytes)**:\\n        *   **Version (VER)**: Defines the IP version (e.g., 4 for IPv4).\\n        *   **Header Length (HLEN)**: Total length of the datagram header in 4-byte words.\\n        *   **Type of Service (ToS)**: Specifies quality of service parameters.\\n        *   **Total Length**: Total length of the datagram, including header and data.\\n        *   **Identification (ID)**: Used for fragmentation and reassembly.\\n        *   **Flags (FLGS)**: Used for fragmentation.\\n        *   **Fragment Offset**: Indicates where in the original datagram this fragment belongs.\\n        *   **Time To Live (TTL)**: Maximum number of remaining hops (decremented at each router); prevents loops.\\n        *   **Protocol**: Defines the higher-level protocol using IP services.\\n            *   1: ICMP\\n            *   2: IGMP\\n            *   6: TCP\\n            *   17: UDP\\n            *   89: OSPF\\n        *   **Header Checksum**: Error detection for the header only.\\n        *   **Source IP Address** (32 bits).\\n        *   **Destination IP Address** (32 bits).\\n        *   **Options** (if any): E.g., timestamp, record route, specify routers to visit.\\n\\n*   **IPv6 Datagram**: A newer version with a different header structure (briefly shown, not detailed).\\n\\n*   **Subnetting with VLSM**:\\n    *   **VLSM (Variable Length Subnet Mask)** allows for efficient use of IP addresses by creating subnets of different sizes.\\n    *   An exercise is provided to create an IPv4 addressing plan for a company branch using subnetting based on departmental staff counts.\\n\\n*   **Routing**:\\n    *   **Static Routing**:\\n        *   **Characteristics**: Configured manually; adjusted manually by an administrator upon topology changes.\\n        *   **Use Cases**: Good for small, non-redundant networks. Often used with dynamic routing for configuring a default route.\\n    *   **Dynamic Routing**:\\n        *   **Characteristics**: Automatically discovers remote networks; maintains up-to-date information; chooses the best path; finds new best paths upon topology changes.\\n        *   Can share static default routes with other routers.\\n\\n*   **Address Resolution Protocol (ARP)**:\\n    *   **Purpose**: Resolves an IP address to a corresponding MAC (physical) address.\\n    *   **MAC (LAN/Physical/Ethernet) Address**:\\n        *   Function: Used \\\"locally\\\" to get a frame from one physically connected interface to another within the same network.\\n        *   Format: 48-bit address (e.g., 1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD), typically burned into the NIC ROM, sometimes software settable.\\n        *   Management: Administered by IEEE, manufacturers buy portions of MAC address space.\\n        *   Nature: Flat address, allowing LAN cards to be portable between LANs.\\n    *   **IP Address vs. MAC Address**:\\n        *   MAC address: Like a Social Security Number (flat, portable).\\n        *   IP address: Like a postal address (hierarchical, depends on the IP subnet, not portable if the host moves to a different subnet).\\n    *   **ARP Table**:\\n        *   Each IP node (host, router) on a LAN maintains an ARP table.\\n        *   Stores IP/MAC address mappings for some LAN nodes (e.g., `<IP address; MAC address; TTL>`).\\n        *   **TTL (Time To Live)**: Time after which an address mapping is forgotten (typically 20 min).\\n    *   **ARP Protocol (Same LAN Scenario)**:\\n        1.  A wants to send a datagram to B, but B's MAC is not in A's ARP table.\\n        2.  A broadcasts an ARP query packet containing B's IP address (Destination MAC address = FF-FF-FF-FF-FF-FF). All nodes on the LAN receive it.\\n        3.  B receives the ARP query and replies to A with its MAC address (unicast frame).\\n        4.  A caches the IP-to-MAC address pair in its ARP table until it times out (**soft state**).\\n        *   **\\\"Plug-and-play\\\"**: Nodes create ARP tables without manual intervention.\\n    *   **ARP Packet Structure**: Contains fields like Hardware Type (Ethernet = 1), Protocol Type (IPv4 = x0800), Hardware Length (6 for Ethernet MAC), Protocol Length (4 for IPv4).\\n    *   **Encapsulation**: An ARP packet is encapsulated within an Ethernet packet (Ethernet Type field is x0806 for ARP).\\n\\n*   **Default Gateways**:\\n    *   **Essential Information**: Devices need an IP address, subnet mask, and default gateway for network access.\\n    *   **Function**:\\n        *   If the destination is on the *same IP network*, the packet is forwarded directly to the destination device (router not involved).\\n        *   If the destination is on a *different IP network*, the packet is forwarded to the default gateway.\\n    *   The default gateway is the device (usually a router) that routes traffic from the local network to devices on remote networks (e.g., the Internet). Routers typically also have their own default gateways.\\n\\n*   **Packet Forwarding / Routing to another LAN (Detailed Walkthrough)**:\\n    1.  **Host A to Router R**:\\n        *   A creates an IP datagram (IP source A, IP destination B).\\n        *   A creates a link-layer frame with R's MAC address as the destination, encapsulating the IP datagram.\\n        *   Frame is sent from A to R.\\n    2.  **Router R**:\\n        *   R receives the frame, removes the link-layer header/trailer, and passes the IP datagram up to the IP layer.\\n        *   R looks up the destination IP (B) in its routing table to determine the next hop and outgoing interface.\\n        *   R creates a *new* link-layer frame (with its own MAC as source and B's MAC as destination) and encapsulates the *original* IP datagram (IP source A, IP destination B remain unchanged).\\n        *   Frame is sent from R to B.\\n    3.  **Host B**:\\n        *   B receives the frame, removes the link-layer header/trailer, and passes the IP datagram up to the IP layer.\\n        *   B processes the IP datagram.\\n    *   **Key Principle**: IP source and destination addresses remain constant throughout the journey, while MAC source and destination addresses change at each hop (between directly connected devices).\\n\\n*   **Router Packet Forwarding Decision (Step-by-step example)**:\\n    1.  **PC1 to R1 (Default Gateway)**:\\n        *   PC1 determines destination is on a different network, so it forwards to its default gateway (R1).\\n        *   PC1 resolves R1's IP address to its MAC address via ARP (if not in cache).\\n        *   PC1 encapsulates the IPv4 packet in an Ethernet frame (dest MAC = R1's interface MAC) and sends it.\\n    2.  **R1 to R2**:\\n        *   R1 receives the frame, checks dest MAC (matches its interface), de-encapsulates.\\n        *   R1 examines the IPv4 packet's destination IP (192.168.4.10) and searches its routing table.\\n        *   R1 finds a route with a next-hop IP (192.168.2.2) and exit interface (FastEthernet0/1).\\n        *   R1 resolves the next-hop IP (R2's interface IP) to its MAC address via ARP (if not in cache).\\n        *   R1 encapsulates the IPv4 packet in a *new* Ethernet frame (dest MAC = R2's interface MAC) and forwards it.\\n    3.  **R2 to R3**:\\n        *   R2 receives the frame, de-encapsulates.\\n        *   R2 searches its routing table for the destination IP.\\n        *   R2 finds a route with a next-hop IP (192.168.3.2) and exit interface (Serial 0/0/0).\\n        *   Since it's a serial interface (not Ethernet), R2 doesn't use MAC addresses but sets the data link destination to a broadcast equivalent.\\n        *   R2 encapsulates the IPv4 packet in a *new* data link frame (e.g., PPP) and sends it out the serial interface.\\n    4.  **R3 to Final Destination**:\\n        *   R3 receives the PPP frame, de-encapsulates.\\n        *   R3 searches its routing table for the destination IP.\\n        *   R3 finds the destination network is *directly connected* to its Ethernet interface.\\n        *   R3 resolves the destination host's IPv4 address to its MAC address via ARP.\\n        *   R3 encapsulates the IPv4 packet in a *new* Ethernet frame (dest MAC = destination host's MAC) and delivers it directly.\\n\\n*   **Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP)**:\\n    *   **Specification**: Specified in [RFC 792].\\n    *   **Purpose**: Used by hosts and routers to communicate network-layer information to each other. Most typically for error reporting.\\n    *   **Architecture**: Often considered part of IP, but architecturally lies *just above* IP, as ICMP messages are carried inside IP datagrams (as IP payload).\\n    *   **Common ICMP Types and Codes**:\\n        *   0, 0: Echo reply (ping)\\n        *   3, 0-7: Destination network/host/protocol/port unreachable, fragmentation needed, etc.\\n        *   8, 0: Echo request (ping)\\n        *   11, 0: TTL expired\\n        *   12, 0: Bad IP header\\n\\n*   **Traceroute (using ICMP)**:\\n    *   **Process**:\\n        1.  Source sends a series of UDP segments (or ICMP Echo requests) to the destination.\\n        2.  Each segment/request has an incrementing **Time To Live (TTL)** value, starting from 1.\\n        3.  When the *n*-th datagram arrives at the *n*-th router (meaning its TTL reaches 0), the router discards it.\\n        4.  The router sends an ICMP \\\"Time Exceeded\\\" message (Type 11, Code 0) back to the source, including the router's IP address.\\n        5.  The source calculates the Round Trip Time (RTT) based on the ICMP reply. Traceroute typically repeats this process 3 times to get an average RTT.\\n        6.  The destination's IP address in the ICMP message allows for a DNS lookup to find the router's name.\\n    *   **Stopping Criterion**: When the UDP segment eventually reaches the destination host, the host returns an ICMP \\\"Port Unreachable\\\" packet (Type 3, Code 3) because the chosen port number is typically unused.\\n\\n#### Transport Layer\\n\\n*   **Responsibilities**:\\n    *   Process-to-process delivery of the entire message.\\n    *   Port addressing (to identify specific applications).\\n    *   Segmentation and reassembly of data.\\n    *   Connection control (connectionless for UDP, connection-oriented for TCP).\\n    *   End-to-end flow control.\\n    *   End-to-end error control.\\n*   **Note**: Responsible for delivering segments from a source process to a final destination process.\\n\\n#### Application Layer\\n\\n*   **Responsibility**: Providing services to the user (e.g., web browsing, file transfer, email).\"}","timestamp":"2026-03-20 21:36:37"}
