{"file_size":4689970,"filename":"I3304-2024-2025-Part-1 (1).pdf","level":"info","message":"Input object for PDFDocument:","mime_type":"application/pdf","original_text":"\n\nI3304\nNetwork administration and \nsecurity\nAhmad Fadlallah\nAli RAAD\n1\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nReferenceTextbooks\n2\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nOutline\n•Introduction \n๏Introduction to the course\n๏Recall Network Basics (I2208)\n•Network Layer\n๏IP packet structure (Recall)\n๏Static Routing\n๏Dynamic Routing Algorithm\n๏Dynamic Routing Protocols\n๏NAT (Network Address Translation)\n•Transport Layer\n๏Function of the transport layer\n๏UDP Protocol\n๏TCP Protocol\n-Connection management\n-Flow control\n-Congestion control\n•Application Layer\nHTTP protocol\nFTP protocol\nMail protocols\nDNS\n•Introduction to Security\nSecurity services\nCryptography\nDigital Signature\nPrinciple of network security \nprotocols\n3\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nWhat’s the Internet: “nuts and bolts”view\n•Billions of connected computing \ndevices: \n๏hosts = end systems \n๏running network apps\n•Communication links\n๏fiber, copper, radio, satellite\n๏transmission rate: bandwidth\n•Packet switches: forward packets \n(chunks of data)\n๏Routers and switches\nWired links\nwireless\nlinks\nrouter\nsmartphone\nPC\nserver\nWireless laptop\nmobile network\nglobal ISP\nregional ISP\nhome \nnetwork\ninstitutional\nnetwork\n4\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\n“Fun” Internet-connected devices\nIP picture frame\nhttp://www.ceiva.com/\nWeb-enabled  toaster +\nweather forecaster\nInternet phones\nInternet \nrefrigerator\nSlingbox:  watch,\ncontrol cable TV remotely\nTweet-a-watt: \nmonitor energy  use\nsensorized,\nbed\nmattress\n5\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nWhat’s the Internet: “nuts and bolts” view\n•Internet: “network of networks”\n๏Interconnected ISPs\n6\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nWhat’s the Internet: “nuts and bolts” view\n•Protocolscontrol sending, \nreceiving of messages\n๏e.g., TCP, IP, HTTP, Skype,  \n802.11\n•Internet  standards\n๏RFC: Request for comments\n๏IETF: Internet Engineering Task \nForce\nmobile network\nglobal ISP\nregional ISP\nhome \nnetwork\ninstitutional\nnetwork\n7\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nWhat’s the Internet: a service view\n•Infrastructure that provides \nservices to applications:\n๏Web, VoIP, email, games, e-\ncommerce, social nets, ...\n•Provides programming \ninterface to apps\n๏hooks that allow sending \nand receiving  app programs \nto “connect”to Internet\n๏Provides service options, \nanalogous to postal service\nmobile network\nglobal ISP\nregional ISP\nhome \nnetwork\ninstitutional\nnetwork\n8\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nWhat’s a protocol?\n•“what’s the time?”\n•“I have a question”\n•introductions\n•Machines rather than \nhumans\n•All communication activity \nin Internet governed by \nprotocols\nHuman protocols\nNetwork protocols\n... specific messages sent\n... specific actions taken when messages \nreceived, or other events\nprotocolsdefine format, orderof \nmessages sent and received\namong network entities, and \nactions takenon message \ntransmission, receipt\n9\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nWhat’s a protocol?\nQ:other human protocols? \n10\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nWhy layering?\nDealing with complex systems:\n•Explicit structure allows identification, relationship of \ncomplex system’s pieces\n•Modularizationeases maintenance, updating of \nsystem\n๏Change of implementation of layer’s service \ntransparent to rest of system\n11\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nAnalogy\nIk vind \nkonijnen \nleuk\nL: Ducth\nFax:#\nIk vind \nkonijnen \nleuk\nL: Dutch\nI like \nrabbits\nMessage\nInformation \nfor the \nremote \ntranslator\nInformation \nfor the \nremote \nsecretary\nIk vind \nkonijnen \nleuk\nL: Ducth\nFax:#\nIk vind \nkonijnen \nleuk\nL: Ducth\nJ’aime \nbien les \nlapins\nArabic & English\nChinese & French\nProfessor B\nTranslator\nSecretary\nuse fax\nuse Dutch\nSecretary\nTranslator\nProfessor A\n12\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nReference Models\n•There are two competing models for how the \nsoftware is layered: the OSIand the TCPmodels.  \n•OSI (Open Systems Interconnection)\n๏Developed by ISO (International Standards \nOrganization)\n๏7 layers\n•TCP (Transfer Control Protocol)\n๏Used in the ARPANET and in the Internet.  \n๏Common mechanism that is surpassing the OSI Model.  \n๏5 layers\n13\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nReference Models\n14\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nInternet Protocol Stack\n•Application: supporting network applications\n๏FTP, SMTP, HTTP\n•Transport: process-process data transfer\n๏TCP, UDP\n•Network: routing of datagrams from source \nto destination\n๏IP, routing protocols\n•Link: data transfer between neighboring  \nnetwork elements\n๏Ethernet, 802.111 (WiFi), PPP\n•Physical: bits “on the wire”\n15\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nISO/OSI reference model\n•Presentation: allow applications to \ninterpret meaning of data, e.g., \nencryption, compression, machine-\nspecific conventions\n•Session: synchronization, check-\npointing, recovery of data exchange\n•Internet stack “missing”these \nlayers!\n๏these services, if needed, must be \nimplemented in application\n๏needed?\n16\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nsource\napplication\ntransport\nnetwork\nlink\nphysical\nH\nt\nH\nn\nM\nsegment\nH\nt\ndatagram\ndestination\napplication\ntransport\nnetwork\nlink\nphysical\nH\nt\nH\nn\nH\nl\nM\nH\nt\nH\nn\nM\nH\nt\nM\nM\nnetwork\nlink\nphysical\nlink\nphysical\nH\nt\nH\nn\nH\nl\nM\nH\nt\nH\nn\nM\nH\nt\nH\nn\nM\nH\nt\nH\nn\nH\nl\nM\nrouter\nswitch\nEncapsulation\nmessage\nM\nH\nt\nM\nH\nn\nframe\n17\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nReference Models\n•Headers, Data, and Trailers\n•Encapsulation\n18\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nTCP/IP MODEL\n19\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nInternet Layers\n•Internet Model\n๏Dominant model in data communications and networking \n๏5 ordered layers; often referred to as TCP/IP protocol suite \n20\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nInternet Layers\n21\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nPeer-to-Peer Processes\n22\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nAn exchange using the Internet model\n23\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nPhysical Layer\n•Physical characteristics of interfaces and media \n๏Representation of bits without interpretation \n๏Data rate: number of bits per second \n๏Synchronization of bits \n24\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nThe physical layer is responsible  for \ntransmitting  individual bits from one \nnode to the next.\nNote:\n25\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nTransmission Media\n26\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nData link Layer\nData Link Layer Responsibilities\n•Defines framesinto manageable data units \n๏Physical addressing \n๏Flow control \n๏Error control \n๏Access control \n27\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nThe data link layer is responsible for \ntransmitting  frames from \none node to the next.\nNote:\n28\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nNode-to-Node delivery\n29\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\n802.3 MAC frame\n•Preamble–7 bytesof alternating 0s and 1s to alert the receiver and allow it to \nsynchronize\n•Start Frame Delimiter (SFD) –1 byte –10101011 signals the beginning of a frame, \nlast chance for synchronization –last 2 bits are 11\n•Destination address (DA) –6 bytes –contains the physical address of the destination \nstation or stations\n•Source address (SA) –6 bytes –contains the physical address of the sender\n•Length/type–if less than 1518 then it defines the length of the data field –if more \nthan 1536 then it defines the type of the PDU packet that is encapsulated\n•Data–data encapsulated from upper-layer protocols : 46 ~ 1500 bytes\n•CRC–CRC-32\n30\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nNetwork layer\n•Network Layer Responsibilities\n๏Source-to-destination delivery, possibly across multiple \nnetworks \n๏Logical addressing \n๏Routing\n31\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nThe network layer is responsible  for \nthe delivery of packets from  the \noriginal source to the \nfinal destination.\nNote:\n32\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSource-to-Destination delivery\n33\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nPosition of IPv4 in TCP/IP protocol suite\nIPv4\n34\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIPv4\n•Best-effort delivery\n๏IPv4 is an unreliableand connectionlessdatagram protocol\n๏Abest-effort delivery service.\n๏best-effort IPv4 provides no error control or flow control(except for \nerror detection on the header).\n•Connectionless protocol\n๏Each datagram is handled independently\n๏Datagrams sent by the source to the same destination could\n-Arrive out of order\n-be lost or corrupted during transmission.\n๏IPv4 relies on a high-level protocol to take of all these problem.\n35\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIPv4 Datagrams\n•Packets in the IPv4 layer are called Datagrams.\n36\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nver\nlength\n32 bits\ndata \n(variable  length,\ntypically a TCP \nor UDP segment)\n16-bit identifier\nInternet\nchecksum\ntime to\nlive\n32 bit source IP address\nIP protocol version number\nheader length (bytes)\nmax number\nremaining hops\n(decremented at \neach router)\nfor\nfragmentation/\nreassembly\ntotal datagram\nlength (bytes)\nupper layer protocol\nto deliver payload to\nhead.\nlen\ntype of\nservice\n“type” of data \nflgs\nfragment\noffset\nupper\nlayer\n32 bit destination IP address\nOptions (if any)\nE.g. timestamp,\nrecord route\ntaken, specify\nlist of routers \nto visit.\nhow much overhead \nwith TCP?\n20 bytes of TCP\n20 bytes of IP\n= 40 bytes + app \nlayer overhead\nIP datagram format\n37\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIPv4 Datagram (cont’d)\n•A datagram is a variable-length packet consisting of a \nheaderand data.\n•Header\n๏Length : 20 –60 bytes\n๏Contains information essential to routing and delivery.\n•Version (VER) : It defines the Version of IPv4. it is 4.\n•Header Length (HLEN) : Defining the total length of \nthe datagram header in 4-byte words.\n38\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIPv4 Datagram (cont’d)\n•Protocol \n๏Defining the higher level protocol that uses the \nservices of the IP layer\n-TCP, UDP, ICMP, and IGMP\n-Multiplexing data from different higher level protocols\nValueProtocol\n1ICMP\n2IGMP\n6TCP\n8EGP\n17UDP\n89OSPF\n39\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIPv6 Datagram\n40\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIPv6 Datagram\n41\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSubnet with VLSM\n192.168.10.0/24\n42\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nRegular Subnet\n7subnets; The largest subnet needs 60hosts \nIf 3bits for subnet (8 subnets) 5bits for host (32 hosts)\nIf 6bits for host (64 hosts) 2bits for subnet (4 subnets)\n192.168.10.0/24\n43\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nExercise\n•A multinational  company  wishes to have an IPv4 addressing  plan for the new \nbranch it has created  in Beirut. The Beirut branch has 5 departments  as follows:\n๏Human Resources  Management  (HRM) with 12 staff;\n๏Engineering  (ENG) with 23 staff ;\n๏Information  system (IS) with 8 staff;\n๏Marketing  and sales (MS) with 50 staff;\n๏Accounting and auditing  (AA) with 15 staff.\n•In total,  the Beirut branch has 108 staff. The network  allocated  for the branch is \n192.168.100.0/24. While taking into account the evolution  of the branch, divide  the \nnetwork  into several  sub-networks  according  to the departments.\n•You should fill the below  table  for each department/  sub-network.  Briefly explain \nthe different  choices.\n44\nDept. \nName\nNetwork \naddress\nPrefix \nlength\nUsableIP address  range\n(First –Last)\nBroadcast address\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nForwarding -Routing\n223.1.1.1\n223.1.1.3\n223.1.1.4\n223.1.2.2\n223.1.2.1\n223.1.2.6\n223.1.3.2\n223.1.3.1\n223.1.3.27\n223.1.1.2\n223.1.7.0\n223.1.7.1\n223.1.8.0223.1.8.1\n223.1.9.1\n223.1.9.2\nDestination \nNetwork\nNext hopInterface\n0.0.0.0223.1.1.3FastEthernet\nFastEthernet\nDestination \nNetwork\nNext hopInterface\n223.1.3.0/24223.1.7.1FastEthernet0/0\n223.1.2.0/24223.1.9.1FastEthernet0/1\n45\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIntroduction to Routing\nStatic Routing\n•Static Route Characteristics:\n๏Must be configured manually\n๏Must be adjusted manually by \nthe administrator when there \nis a change in the topology\n๏Good for small non-redundant \nnetworks\n๏Often used in conjunction \nwith a dynamic routing \nprotocolfor configuring a \ndefault route\n46\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIntroduction to Routing\nDynamic Routing\n•Dynamic Routes Automatically:\n๏Discover remote networks\n๏Maintain up-to-date \ninformation\n๏Choose the best path to the \ndestination\n๏Find new best paths when \nthere is a topology change\n๏Dynamic routing can also \nshare static default routes \nwith the other routers.\n47\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nAddress Resolution -ARP\n48\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nMAC addresses and ARP\n•IP address: \n๏“Low” Network-layer address for interface\n๏Used for layer 3 (network layer) forwarding\n•MAC (or LAN or physical or Ethernet) address: \n๏Function: used “locally” to get frame from one interface to \nanother physically-connected interface (same network, in \nIP-addressing sense)\n๏48 bit MAC address (for most LANs) burned in NIC ROM, \nalso sometimes software settable\n๏e.g.: 1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD\nhexadecimal (base 16) notation\n(each “numeral” represents 4 bits)\n49\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nLAN addresses and ARP\neach adapter on LAN has unique LANaddress\nadapter\n1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD\n58-23-D7-FA-20-B0\n0C-C4-11-6F-E3-98\n71-65-F7-2B-08-53\nLAN\n(wired or\nwireless)\n50\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nLAN addresses (more)\n•MAC address allocation administered by IEEE\n•Manufacturer buys portion of MAC address space (to \nassure uniqueness)\n•Analogy:\n๏MAC address: like Social Security Number\n๏IP address: like postal address\n•MAC flat address  ➜portability \n๏can move LAN card from one LAN to another\n•IP hierarchical address not portable\n๏address depends on IP subnet to which node is attached\n51\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nARP: Address Resolution Protocol\n•ARP table: each IP node (host, \nrouter) on LAN has a ARP table\n–IP/MAC address mappings for some \nLAN nodes:\n•< IP address; MAC address; TTL>\n–TTL (Time To Live): time after which \naddress mapping will be forgotten \n(typically 20 min)\nQuestion:how to determine\ninterface’s MAC address, \nknowing its IP address?\n1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD\n58-23-D7-FA-20-B0\n0C-C4-11-6F-E3-98\n71-65-F7-2B-08-53\nLAN\n137.196.7.23\n137.196.7.78\n137.196.7.14\n137.196.7.88\nIP addressMAC addressTTL\n137.196.7.1458-23-D7-FA-20-B0\n20\n52\nUse arpcommand to display ARP table on Windows or Linux\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nARP protocol: same LAN\n1.A wants to send datagram to B\n๏B’s MAC address not in A’s ARP table.\n2.A broadcasts ARP query packet, containing B's IP address \n๏Destination MAC address = FF-FF-FF-FF-FF-FF\n๏All nodes on LAN receive ARP query \n3.B receives ARP packet, replies to A with its (B's) MAC address\n๏frame sent to A’s MAC address (unicast)\n4.A caches (saves) IP-to-MAC address pair in its ARP table until \ninformation becomes old (times out) \n๏soft state: information that times out (goes away) unless refreshed\n•ARP is “plug-and-play”:\n๏Nodes create their ARP tables without intervention from net \nadministrator\n53\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nARP operation\n54\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nHardware Type –\nEthernet is type 1\nProtocol Type-\nIPv4=x0800\nHardware Length: \nlength of Ethernet \nAddress (6)\nProtocol Length: \nlength of IPv4 \naddress (4)\nARP packet\n55\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nThe ARP packet is encapsulated within an Ethernet packet.\nNote: Type field for Ethernet is x0806\nEncapsulation of ARP packet\n56\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nFour cases using ARP\n57\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nARP Example \n58\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nARP –A each step\nARP: Who has this IP?\nARP: Who has this IP?\nARP: Who has this IP?\n59\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nDefault Gateways\n•Devices need the following information \nfor network access: IP address, subnet \nmask, and default gateway.\n•When a host sends a packet to a device \nthat is on the same IP network, the packet \nis forwarded out the host interface to the \ndestination device. The router does not \nneed to get involved.\n•When a host sends a packet to a device on \na different IP network, the packet is \nforwarded to the default gateway because \nthe host device cannot communicate with \ndevices outside of the local network.\n•The default gateway is the device that \nroutes traffic from the local network to \ndevices on remote networks, such as \ndevices on the Internet.\nRouters are also usually configured with their own default gateway.\n60\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\n•walkthrough: send datagram from A to B via R\n–Focus on addressing –at IP (datagram) and MAC layer \n(frame)\n–Assume A knows B’s IP address\n–Assume A knows IP address of first hop router, R (how?)\n–Assume A knows R’s MAC address (how?)\nR\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\n222.222.222.220\n111.111.111.110\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\n111.111.111.112\n111.111.111.111\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nA\n222.222.222.222\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\n222.222.222.221\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\nB\n61\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\n•A creates IP datagram with IP source A, destination B \n•A creates link-layer frame with R's MAC address as \ndestination address, frame contains A-to-B IP datagram\nR\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\n222.222.222.220\n111.111.111.110\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\n111.111.111.112\n111.111.111.111\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nA\n222.222.222.222\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\n222.222.222.221\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\nB\nIP\nEth\nPhy\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\nMAC src: 74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nMAC dest: E6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\n62\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nR\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\n222.222.222.220\n111.111.111.110\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\n111.111.111.112\n111.111.111.111\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nA\n222.222.222.222\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\n222.222.222.221\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\nB\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\n•Frame sent from A to R\n•Frame received at R, datagram removed, passed \nup to IP\nIP\nEth\nPhy\nIP\nEth\nPhy\nMAC src: 74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nMAC dest: E6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\n63\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nR\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\n222.222.222.220\n111.111.111.110\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\n111.111.111.112\n111.111.111.111\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nA\n222.222.222.222\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\n222.222.222.221\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\nB\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\n•R forwards datagram with IP source A, destination B \n•R creates link-layer frame with B's MAC address as \ndestination address, frame contains A-to-B IP \ndatagram\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\nMAC src: 1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\nMAC dest: 49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\nIP\nEth\nPhy\nIP\nEth\nPhy\n64\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nR\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\n222.222.222.220\n111.111.111.110\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\n111.111.111.112\n111.111.111.111\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nA\n222.222.222.222\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\n222.222.222.221\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\nB\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\n•R forwards datagram with IP source A, destination B \n•R creates link-layer frame with B's MAC address as \ndestination address, frame contains A-to-B IP \ndatagram\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\nMAC src: 1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\nMAC dest: 49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\nIP\nEth\nPhy\nIP\nEth\nPhy\n65\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nR\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\n222.222.222.220\n111.111.111.110\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\n111.111.111.112\n111.111.111.111\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nA\n222.222.222.222\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\n222.222.222.221\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\nB\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\n•R forwards datagram with IP source A, destination B \n•R creates link-layer frame with B's MAC address as dest, frame \ncontains A-to-B IP datagram\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\nMAC src: 1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\nMAC dest: 49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\nIP\nEth\nPhy\n* Check out the online interactive exercises for more \nexamples:  http://gaia.cs.umass.edu/kurose_ross/interactive/\n66\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIntroduction to Routing\nRouter Packet Forwarding Decision\n•What happens when the router receives the frame \nfrom the host device?\n67\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \nSend a Packet\n•PC1 must determine if the destination IPv4 address is on the same network. \n•If it is on the same network, PC1 will obtain the destination MAC address from its ARP cache or use an \nARP request.\n•Because the destination network is on a different network, PC1 forwards the packet to its default \ngateway.\n68\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \nSend a Packet\n•To determine the MAC address of the default gateway, PC1 checks its ARP table for \nthe IPv4 address of the default gateway and its corresponding MAC address. \n๏An ARP request is sent if it is not found.\n•When PC1 has the MAC address of Router R1, it can forward the packet. \n69\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \nForward to the Next Hop\n•R1 examines the destination MAC address which matches the MAC address \nof the receiving interface and copies the frame into its buffer.\n•R1 identifies the Ethernet Type field as 0x800 which indicates that the \nEthernet frame contains an IPv4 packet in the data portion of the frame.\n70\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \nForward to the Next Hop\n•R1 de-encapsulates the Ethernet frame.\n•Because the destination IPv4 address of the packet, 192.168.4.10,   does not match \nany of the directly connected networks on R1, R1 searches the routing table for a \ncorresponding route.\n๏R1’s Routing Table has a route for the 192.168.4.0/24 network.\n71\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \nForward to the Next Hop\n•The routethat R1 finds to the 192.168.4.0/24 network has a next-hopaddressof \n192.168.2.2 and an exit interface of FastEthernet0/1.\n•This will require that the IPv4 packet be encapsulated in a new Ethernet frame with \nthe destination MAC address of the IPv4 address of the next-hop router, 192.168.2.2\n72\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \nForward to the Next Hop\n•Because the exit interface is on an Ethernet network, R1 must resolve the \nnext-hop IPv4 address with a destination MAC address using ARP, assuming \nit is not in its ARP cache.\n•When R1 has the MAC address for the next-hop, the Ethernet frame is \nforwarded out of the FastEthernet0/1 interface of R1.\n73\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\nPacket Routing\n•R2 examines the destination MAC address\n๏Because it matches the MAC address of its receiving interface, R2 copies the \nframe into its buffer.\n•R2 determines that that frame contains an IPv4 packet in the data portion \nof the frame.\n74\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\nPacket Routing\n•R2 de-encapsulates the Ethernet frame.\n•Because the destination IP address is on a different network, \nthe routing table is searched to find a corresponding route for \nthe destination IPv4 address. \n75\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\nPacket Routing\n•The routing table of R2 has a routeto the 192.168.4.0/24 network \nwith a next-hop IPv4 address of 192.168.3.2 and an exit interface of \nSerial 0/0/0.   \n•Because the exit interface is not Ethernet, R2 does not have to \nresolve the next-hop IP-v4 address with a destination MAC address.\n76\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\nPacket Routing\n•The IPv4 packet is encapsulatedinto a new data link frame used by \nthe exit interface and sent out the Serial 0/0/0 exit interface.\n•Because there are no MAC addresses on serial interfaces, R2 sets the \ndata link destination address to an equivalent of a broadcast.\n77\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\nReach the Destination\n•R3 copies the data link PPP frame into its buffer.\n•R3 de-encapsulatesthe data link PPP frame.\n•R3 searches the routing table for the destination IPv4 address of the \npacket.\n78\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\nReach the Destination\n•Because the destination network is on R3’s directly connected network, the \npacket can be sent directly and does not need to be sent to another router.\n•Because the exit interface is a directly connected Ethernet network, R3 \nmust resolve the destination IPv4 address of the packet with a destination \nMAC address by either finding it in its ARP cache or send out an ARP \nrequest.\n79\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nInternet Control Message Protocol \n•The Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) \n•Specified in [RFC 792], \n•Used by hosts and routers to communicate network-\nlayer information to each other. \n•Most typical use of ICMP is for error reporting\n•Often considered part of IP, but architecturally it lies \njust above IP, as ICMP messages are carried inside IP \ndatagrams. \n๏ICMP messages are carried as IP payload\n80\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nICMP Type and Code \nTypeCode Description\n00echo reply (ping)\n30destination network unreachable\n31destination host unreachable\n32destination protocol unreachable\n33destination port unreachable\n36destination network unknown\n37destination host unknown\n80echo request (ping)\n90route advertisement\n100router discovery\n110TTL expired\n120bad IP header\n81\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nTrace Route –ICMP\n•Source sends series of UDP segments (or ICMP Echo request) to destination host\n๏First has TTL =1\n๏Second has TTL=2, etc.\n๏Unlikely port number\n•When n\nth\ndatagram arrives to n\nth\nrouter:\n๏Router discards datagram\n๏Sends to source an ICMP message (type 11, code 0)\n๏Datagram includes router IP address. Traceroute does DNS lookup to find name of router \n(if any)\n•When ICMP message arrives, source calculates RTT\n•Traceroute repeat the process 3 times (To get average RTT)\n•Stopping criterion\n๏UDP segment eventually arrives at destination host\n๏Destination returns ICMP “port unreachable” packet (type 3, code 3)\n82\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nTrace Route –ICMP\n83\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nTransport layer\nThe transport layer is responsible for delivering segments from a source process to a \nfinal destination process.\n84\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nTransport layer\n•Transport Layer Responsibilities\n๏Process-to-process delivery of entire message \n๏Port addressing \n๏Segmentation and reassembly \n๏Connection control: connectionless or connection-oriented \n๏End-to-end flow control \n๏End-to-end error control \n85\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nApplication Layer\n•The application layer is responsible for providing \nservices to the user.\n86\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nThanks !\n87","storage_path":"uploads\\1774035781647_I3304_2024_2025_Part_1__1_.pdf","summary":"Here is a detailed summary of the provided text in bullet points, covering main ideas, key concepts, important details, and definitions:\n\n**I3304 - Network Administration and Security (2023-2024)**\n\n*   **Course Overview:**\n    *   **Title:** Network Administration and Security (I3304).\n    *   **Instructors:** Ahmad Fadlallah, Ali RAAD.\n    *   **Outline Covered:** Introduction, Network Layer, Transport Layer, Application Layer, Introduction to Security.\n\n**1. Introduction to Networking Fundamentals**\n\n*   **What's the Internet? (\"Nuts and Bolts\" View):**\n    *   Comprises billions of connected computing devices (hosts/end systems) running network applications.\n    *   Uses communication links (fiber, copper, radio, satellite) with a specific transmission rate (bandwidth).\n    *   Packet switches (routers and switches) forward data chunks (packets).\n    *   It is a \"network of networks,\" interconnected through Internet Service Providers (ISPs).\n    *   Communication is controlled by protocols (e.g., TCP, IP, HTTP, 802.11).\n    *   Internet standards are defined by RFCs (Request For Comments) from the IETF (Internet Engineering Task Force).\n*   **What's the Internet? (A \"Service\" View):**\n    *   An infrastructure providing services to applications (Web, VoIP, email, games, e-commerce, social networks).\n    *   Offers a programming interface allowing application programs to \"connect\" and exchange data.\n*   **What's a Protocol?:**\n    *   Analogous to human protocols (e.g., introductions, asking time).\n    *   For machines, protocols define the format, order of messages sent and received among network entities, and actions taken upon message transmission or receipt. All Internet communication is governed by protocols.\n*   **Why Layering?:**\n    *   **Purpose:** To manage the complexity of network systems.\n    *   **Benefits:**\n        *   Explicit structure helps identify and understand relationships between system pieces.\n        *   Modularization eases system maintenance and updates.\n        *   Changes in a layer's implementation are transparent to other layers.\n    *   **Analogy:** A language translation service involving secretaries and translators, where each step adds/removes information specific to its function without altering the core message.\n\n**2. Network Reference Models**\n\n*   **Two Competing Models:** OSI and TCP/IP.\n*   **OSI (Open Systems Interconnection) Model:**\n    *   Developed by ISO (International Standards Organization).\n    *   Composed of 7 layers.\n    *   **Presentation Layer:** Allows applications to interpret data meaning (e.g., encryption, compression, machine-specific conventions).\n    *   **Session Layer:** Handles synchronization, checkpointing, and recovery of data exchange.\n    *   *(Note: The Internet stack often integrates these services directly into the application layer if needed, rather than having distinct layers.)*\n*   **TCP/IP (Transfer Control Protocol) Model:**\n    *   Used in ARPANET and the Internet, now the dominant model.\n    *   Composed of 5 layers.\n*   **Internet Protocol Stack (5-Layer Model - Dominant):**\n    *   **Application Layer:** Supports network applications (e.g., FTP, SMTP, HTTP).\n    *   **Transport Layer:** Manages process-to-process data transfer (e.g., TCP, UDP).\n    *   **Network Layer:** Responsible for routing datagrams from source to destination (e.g., IP, routing protocols).\n    *   **Link Layer:** Handles data transfer between neighboring network elements (e.g., Ethernet, 802.11 Wi-Fi, PPP).\n    *   **Physical Layer:** Deals with the transmission of bits \"on the wire.\"\n*   **Encapsulation:**\n    *   The process where data (a message 'M') moves down the layers, and each layer adds its own header (and sometimes a trailer) to the data unit.\n    *   `Message (M)` -> `Segment (Ht M)` -> `Datagram (Hn Ht M)` -> `Frame (Hl Hn Ht M)`.\n    *   This includes Headers, Data, and Trailers.\n*   **Peer-to-Peer Processes:** Each layer logically communicates with its corresponding layer on the destination system, even though actual data flow is vertical through the stack.\n\n**3. Physical Layer**\n\n*   **Responsibility:** Transmitting individual bits from one node to the next.\n*   **Key Characteristics:**\n    *   Defines physical characteristics of interfaces and transmission media.\n    *   Handles the representation of bits (e.g., electrical signals, light pulses) without interpreting their meaning.\n    *   Determines data rate (number of bits per second).\n    *   Manages synchronization of bits.\n*   **Transmission Media:** Mentioned as a component.\n\n**4. Data Link Layer**\n\n*   **Responsibility:** Transmitting frames from one node to the next.\n*   **Key Responsibilities:**\n    *   **Framing:** Defines data units called frames.\n    *   **Physical Addressing:** Uses MAC addresses for local delivery.\n    *   **Flow Control:** Manages data transmission rate between nodes.\n    *   **Error Control:** Detects and/or corrects errors in frames.\n    *   **Access Control:** Determines which device has control over the link at any given time.\n*   **802.3 MAC Frame Structure (Ethernet):**\n    *   **Preamble (7 bytes):** Alternating 0s and 1s for receiver synchronization.\n    *   **Start Frame Delimiter (SFD) (1 byte):** `10101011` sequence, signals frame start, final sync opportunity.\n    *   **Destination Address (DA) (6 bytes):** Physical address of the destination station(s).\n    *   **Source Address (SA) (6 bytes):** Physical address of the sender.\n    *   **Length/Type (2 bytes):**\n        *   If < 1518, defines the length of the data field.\n        *   If > 1536, defines the type of the encapsulated PDU (e.g., IPv4).\n    *   **Data (46-1500 bytes):** Encapsulated data from upper-layer protocols.\n    *   **CRC (Cyclic Redundancy Check) (4 bytes):** `CRC-32` for error detection.\n\n**5. Network Layer**\n\n*   **Responsibility:** Delivering packets from the original source to the final destination, potentially across multiple networks.\n*   **Key Responsibilities:**\n    *   **Logical Addressing:** Uses IP addresses for global identification.\n    *   **Routing:** Determining the best path for packets to travel.\n*   **IPv4 (Internet Protocol version 4):**\n    *   **Best-Effort Delivery:** An unreliable and connectionless datagram protocol.\n        *   Provides no error control or flow control (except for header error detection).\n        *   Relies on higher-level protocols (e.g., TCP) to manage these issues.\n    *   **Connectionless Protocol:** Each datagram is handled independently.\n        *   Datagrams can arrive out of order, be lost, or be corrupted during transmission.\n    *   **IPv4 Datagrams:** Packets at the IPv4 layer. Variable-length, consisting of a header and data.\n    *   **IPv4 Header Fields (Key ones highlighted):**\n        *   **Version (VER):** `4` for IPv4.\n        *   **Header Length (HLEN):** Length of the header in 4-byte words (typically 20-60 bytes).\n        *   Type of Service (ToS)\n        *   Total Length\n        *   Identifier\n        *   Flags\n        *   Fragment Offset\n        *   **Time to Live (TTL):** Maximum number of hops before discard (decremented at each router).\n        *   **Protocol:** Identifies the higher-level protocol in the payload (e.g., `1` for ICMP, `6` for TCP, `17` for UDP).\n        *   Header Checksum\n        *   **Source IP Address:** 32-bit.\n        *   **Destination IP Address:** 32-bit.\n        *   Options (if any).\n    *   **Overhead:** Minimal IP + TCP header overhead is 40 bytes (20 IP + 20 TCP).\n*   **IPv6 Datagram:** Mentioned with diagrams as a successor to IPv4, but specific field details are not provided in the text.\n*   **Subnetting with VLSM (Variable Length Subnet Mask):**\n    *   A method for dividing an IP network into smaller sub-networks, allowing for efficient use of IP addresses by assigning subnet masks of different lengths based on host requirements. An exercise demonstrates this concept for department allocation.\n\n**6. Routing Concepts**\n\n*   **Forwarding vs. Routing:**\n    *   **Forwarding:** The router's action of moving a packet from an input interface to an appropriate output interface.\n    *   **Routing:** The process of determining the end-to-end path that packets will take.\n*   **Static Routing:**\n    *   Characteristics: Must be manually configured and adjusted by an administrator.\n    *   Use Case: Good for small, non-redundant networks. Often used with dynamic routing to configure a default route.\n*   **Dynamic Routing:**\n    *   Characteristics: Automatically discovers remote networks, maintains up-to-date routing information, chooses the best path, and finds new paths upon topology changes.\n    *   Can also share static default routes with other routers.\n*   **Address Resolution Protocol (ARP):**\n    *   **MAC (LAN/Physical/Ethernet) Addresses:**\n        *   Function: Used \"locally\" to get a frame from one interface to another physically connected interface within the same IP network/LAN.\n        *   Format: 48-bit hexadecimal address (e.g., `1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD`), burned into NIC ROM, sometimes software-settable.\n        *   Administration: MAC address space allocated by IEEE to manufacturers, ensuring uniqueness.\n        *   Analogy: MAC address is like a Social Security Number (flat, portable across LANs); IP address is like a postal address (hierarchical, depends on subnet).\n    *   **ARP Table:** Each IP node (host, router) maintains a table mapping IP addresses to MAC addresses for some LAN nodes. Includes a Time To Live (TTL) (e.g., 20 min) after which mappings are forgotten (soft state).\n    *   **ARP Protocol (Same LAN Communication):**\n        1.  Host A wants to send a datagram to Host B, but B's MAC address is unknown.\n        2.  A broadcasts an ARP query packet (destination MAC `FF-FF-FF-FF-FF-FF`) containing B's IP address.\n        3.  B receives the ARP query and replies directly to A with its MAC address (unicast).\n        4.  A caches the IP-to-MAC mapping in its ARP table.\n        *   **Plug-and-play:** ARP tables are built automatically without administrative intervention.\n    *   **ARP Packet Structure:** Includes Hardware Type (Ethernet=1), Protocol Type (IPv4=0x0800), Hardware Length (6 for Ethernet MAC), Protocol Length (4 for IPv4), Operation Code (request/reply), Sender/Target MAC and IP addresses.\n    *   **Encapsulation of ARP:** An ARP packet is encapsulated within an Ethernet frame (Ethernet Type field = `0x0806`).\n*   **Default Gateways:**\n    *   Devices require an IP address, subnet mask, and default gateway to access a network.\n    *   For destinations on the same IP network, packets are forwarded directly to the destination MAC.\n    *   For destinations on a *different* IP network, packets are forwarded to the default gateway (a router).\n    *   The default gateway routes traffic between the local network and remote networks (e.g., the Internet). Routers themselves typically also have default gateways.\n*   **Addressing: Routing to Another LAN (Detailed Process):**\n    *   **A to R (Router):**\n        *   Host A creates an IP datagram (Source IP = A, Dest IP = B).\n        *   Host A encapsulates this IP datagram in a link-layer frame (Source MAC = A, Dest MAC = R's interface MAC).\n        *   Frame is sent to Router R.\n    *   **R Processing:**\n        *   Router R receives the frame, removes the link-layer header, and passes the IP datagram to its IP layer.\n        *   Router R determines the next hop for Dest IP B (which is B itself if directly connected, or another router).\n        *   Router R encapsulates the *original* IP datagram (Source IP = A, Dest IP = B) into a *new* link-layer frame (Source MAC = R's outgoing interface MAC, Dest MAC = B's MAC).\n        *   Frame is sent to Host B.\n    *   **B Processing:** Host B receives the frame, removes the link-layer header, and processes the IP datagram.\n*   **Switching Packets Between Networks (Multi-hop Routing Example):**\n    *   **PC1 to R1:** PC1 identifies destination as remote, sends packet to its default gateway (R1). PC1 uses ARP to find R1's MAC address, then encapsulates the IP packet in an Ethernet frame with R1's MAC as destination.\n    *   **R1 to R2:** R1 receives frame, de-encapsulates IPv4 packet. Consults routing table to find next hop (R2). R1 uses ARP (if Ethernet link) to find R2's MAC address, then re-encapsulates the IP packet in a new Ethernet frame with R2's MAC as destination.\n    *   **R2 to R3 (Serial Link):** R2 receives frame, de-encapsulates IPv4 packet. Consults routing table to find next hop (R3) via a serial interface. Since serial links don't use MAC addresses, R2 encapsulates the IP packet into a new PPP (or similar) data link frame, setting the destination address to a broadcast equivalent.\n    *   **R3 to Destination PC:** R3 receives PPP frame, de-encapsulates IPv4 packet. Destination network is directly connected to R3. R3 uses ARP to find the final destination PC's MAC address, then encapsulates the IP packet in a new Ethernet frame with the PC's MAC as destination.\n\n**7. Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP)**\n\n*   **Purpose:** Used by hosts and routers to communicate network-layer information, primarily for error reporting.\n*   **Architectural Placement:** Logically above IP; ICMP messages are carried as IP payload within IP datagrams.\n*   **Common ICMP Type and Code Values:**\n    *   `0 0`: Echo reply (Ping response).\n    *   `3 0`: Destination network unreachable.\n    *   `3 3`: Destination port unreachable.\n    *   `8 0`: Echo request (Ping request).\n    *   `11 0`: TTL (Time to Live) expired.\n*   **Traceroute (using ICMP or UDP):**\n    *   **Mechanism:**\n        1.  Source sends a series of UDP segments (or ICMP Echo requests) to the destination, starting with a TTL of 1, then 2, and so on. Unlikely port numbers are used for UDP segments.\n        2.  When the `n`-th datagram reaches the `n`-th router, the router discards it (because TTL expires) and sends an ICMP \"TTL expired\" message (Type 11, Code 0) back to the source. This message includes the router's IP address.\n        3.  Upon receiving the ICMP message, the source calculates the Round Trip Time (RTT) to that router. Traceroute typically repeats this process 3 times.\n        4.  **Stopping Criterion:** When the UDP segment eventually reaches the destination host, the host returns an ICMP \"Port Unreachable\" packet (Type 3, Code 3) because the specified port is not listening.\n\n**8. Transport Layer**\n\n*   **Responsibility:** Delivering segments from a source *process* to a final destination *process*.\n*   **Key Responsibilities:**\n    *   Process-to-process delivery of the entire message.\n    *   **Port Addressing:** Uses port numbers to distinguish between different applications/processes on a host.\n    *   **Segmentation and Reassembly:** Breaking application messages into smaller segments for transmission and reassembling them at the destination.\n    *   **Connection Control:** Can be connectionless (UDP) or connection-oriented (TCP).\n    *   End-to-end flow control.\n    *   End-to-end error control.\n*   **Protocols Mentioned in Outline:** UDP Protocol, TCP Protocol (with Connection management, Flow control, Congestion control). *(Details not provided in text)*\n\n**9. Application Layer**\n\n*   **Responsibility:** Providing services directly to the user.\n*   **Protocols Mentioned in Outline:** HTTP, FTP, Mail protocols, DNS. *(Details not provided in text)*\n\n**10. Introduction to Security**\n\n*   *(This section was listed in the outline but had no corresponding content in the provided text.)*\n*   **Topics to Cover:** Security services, Cryptography, Digital Signature, Principle of network security protocols.","timestamp":"2026-03-20 21:43:38"}
{"level":"info","message":"Mapping JSON to PDFDocument: {\"filename\":\"I3304-2024-2025-Part-1 (1).pdf\",\"file_size\":4689970,\"mime_type\":\"application/pdf\",\"storage_path\":\"uploads\\\\1774035781647_I3304_2024_2025_Part_1__1_.pdf\",\"original_text\":\"\\n\\nI3304\\nNetwork administration and \\nsecurity\\nAhmad Fadlallah\\nAli RAAD\\n1\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nReferenceTextbooks\\n2\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nOutline\\n•Introduction \\n๏Introduction to the course\\n๏Recall Network Basics (I2208)\\n•Network Layer\\n๏IP packet structure (Recall)\\n๏Static Routing\\n๏Dynamic Routing Algorithm\\n๏Dynamic Routing Protocols\\n๏NAT (Network Address Translation)\\n•Transport Layer\\n๏Function of the transport layer\\n๏UDP Protocol\\n๏TCP Protocol\\n-Connection management\\n-Flow control\\n-Congestion control\\n•Application Layer\\nHTTP protocol\\nFTP protocol\\nMail protocols\\nDNS\\n•Introduction to Security\\nSecurity services\\nCryptography\\nDigital Signature\\nPrinciple of network security \\nprotocols\\n3\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s the Internet: “nuts and bolts”view\\n•Billions of connected computing \\ndevices: \\n๏hosts = end systems \\n๏running network apps\\n•Communication links\\n๏fiber, copper, radio, satellite\\n๏transmission rate: bandwidth\\n•Packet switches: forward packets \\n(chunks of data)\\n๏Routers and switches\\nWired links\\nwireless\\nlinks\\nrouter\\nsmartphone\\nPC\\nserver\\nWireless laptop\\nmobile network\\nglobal ISP\\nregional ISP\\nhome \\nnetwork\\ninstitutional\\nnetwork\\n4\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\n“Fun” Internet-connected devices\\nIP picture frame\\nhttp://www.ceiva.com/\\nWeb-enabled  toaster +\\nweather forecaster\\nInternet phones\\nInternet \\nrefrigerator\\nSlingbox:  watch,\\ncontrol cable TV remotely\\nTweet-a-watt: \\nmonitor energy  use\\nsensorized,\\nbed\\nmattress\\n5\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s the Internet: “nuts and bolts” view\\n•Internet: “network of networks”\\n๏Interconnected ISPs\\n6\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s the Internet: “nuts and bolts” view\\n•Protocolscontrol sending, \\nreceiving of messages\\n๏e.g., TCP, IP, HTTP, Skype,  \\n802.11\\n•Internet  standards\\n๏RFC: Request for comments\\n๏IETF: Internet Engineering Task \\nForce\\nmobile network\\nglobal ISP\\nregional ISP\\nhome \\nnetwork\\ninstitutional\\nnetwork\\n7\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s the Internet: a service view\\n•Infrastructure that provides \\nservices to applications:\\n๏Web, VoIP, email, games, e-\\ncommerce, social nets, ...\\n•Provides programming \\ninterface to apps\\n๏hooks that allow sending \\nand receiving  app programs \\nto “connect”to Internet\\n๏Provides service options, \\nanalogous to postal service\\nmobile network\\nglobal ISP\\nregional ISP\\nhome \\nnetwork\\ninstitutional\\nnetwork\\n8\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s a protocol?\\n•“what’s the time?”\\n•“I have a question”\\n•introductions\\n•Machines rather than \\nhumans\\n•All communication activity \\nin Internet governed by \\nprotocols\\nHuman protocols\\nNetwork protocols\\n... specific messages sent\\n... specific actions taken when messages \\nreceived, or other events\\nprotocolsdefine format, orderof \\nmessages sent and received\\namong network entities, and \\nactions takenon message \\ntransmission, receipt\\n9\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s a protocol?\\nQ:other human protocols? \\n10\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhy layering?\\nDealing with complex systems:\\n•Explicit structure allows identification, relationship of \\ncomplex system’s pieces\\n•Modularizationeases maintenance, updating of \\nsystem\\n๏Change of implementation of layer’s service \\ntransparent to rest of system\\n11\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nAnalogy\\nIk vind \\nkonijnen \\nleuk\\nL: Ducth\\nFax:#\\nIk vind \\nkonijnen \\nleuk\\nL: Dutch\\nI like \\nrabbits\\nMessage\\nInformation \\nfor the \\nremote \\ntranslator\\nInformation \\nfor the \\nremote \\nsecretary\\nIk vind \\nkonijnen \\nleuk\\nL: Ducth\\nFax:#\\nIk vind \\nkonijnen \\nleuk\\nL: Ducth\\nJ’aime \\nbien les \\nlapins\\nArabic & English\\nChinese & French\\nProfessor B\\nTranslator\\nSecretary\\nuse fax\\nuse Dutch\\nSecretary\\nTranslator\\nProfessor A\\n12\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nReference Models\\n•There are two competing models for how the \\nsoftware is layered: the OSIand the TCPmodels.  \\n•OSI (Open Systems Interconnection)\\n๏Developed by ISO (International Standards \\nOrganization)\\n๏7 layers\\n•TCP (Transfer Control Protocol)\\n๏Used in the ARPANET and in the Internet.  \\n๏Common mechanism that is surpassing the OSI Model.  \\n๏5 layers\\n13\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nReference Models\\n14\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nInternet Protocol Stack\\n•Application: supporting network applications\\n๏FTP, SMTP, HTTP\\n•Transport: process-process data transfer\\n๏TCP, UDP\\n•Network: routing of datagrams from source \\nto destination\\n๏IP, routing protocols\\n•Link: data transfer between neighboring  \\nnetwork elements\\n๏Ethernet, 802.111 (WiFi), PPP\\n•Physical: bits “on the wire”\\n15\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nISO/OSI reference model\\n•Presentation: allow applications to \\ninterpret meaning of data, e.g., \\nencryption, compression, machine-\\nspecific conventions\\n•Session: synchronization, check-\\npointing, recovery of data exchange\\n•Internet stack “missing”these \\nlayers!\\n๏these services, if needed, must be \\nimplemented in application\\n๏needed?\\n16\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nsource\\napplication\\ntransport\\nnetwork\\nlink\\nphysical\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nM\\nsegment\\nH\\nt\\ndatagram\\ndestination\\napplication\\ntransport\\nnetwork\\nlink\\nphysical\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nH\\nl\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nM\\nM\\nnetwork\\nlink\\nphysical\\nlink\\nphysical\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nH\\nl\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nH\\nl\\nM\\nrouter\\nswitch\\nEncapsulation\\nmessage\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nM\\nH\\nn\\nframe\\n17\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nReference Models\\n•Headers, Data, and Trailers\\n•Encapsulation\\n18\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTCP/IP MODEL\\n19\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nInternet Layers\\n•Internet Model\\n๏Dominant model in data communications and networking \\n๏5 ordered layers; often referred to as TCP/IP protocol suite \\n20\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nInternet Layers\\n21\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nPeer-to-Peer Processes\\n22\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nAn exchange using the Internet model\\n23\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nPhysical Layer\\n•Physical characteristics of interfaces and media \\n๏Representation of bits without interpretation \\n๏Data rate: number of bits per second \\n๏Synchronization of bits \\n24\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nThe physical layer is responsible  for \\ntransmitting  individual bits from one \\nnode to the next.\\nNote:\\n25\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTransmission Media\\n26\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nData link Layer\\nData Link Layer Responsibilities\\n•Defines framesinto manageable data units \\n๏Physical addressing \\n๏Flow control \\n๏Error control \\n๏Access control \\n27\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nThe data link layer is responsible for \\ntransmitting  frames from \\none node to the next.\\nNote:\\n28\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nNode-to-Node delivery\\n29\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\n802.3 MAC frame\\n•Preamble–7 bytesof alternating 0s and 1s to alert the receiver and allow it to \\nsynchronize\\n•Start Frame Delimiter (SFD) –1 byte –10101011 signals the beginning of a frame, \\nlast chance for synchronization –last 2 bits are 11\\n•Destination address (DA) –6 bytes –contains the physical address of the destination \\nstation or stations\\n•Source address (SA) –6 bytes –contains the physical address of the sender\\n•Length/type–if less than 1518 then it defines the length of the data field –if more \\nthan 1536 then it defines the type of the PDU packet that is encapsulated\\n•Data–data encapsulated from upper-layer protocols : 46 ~ 1500 bytes\\n•CRC–CRC-32\\n30\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nNetwork layer\\n•Network Layer Responsibilities\\n๏Source-to-destination delivery, possibly across multiple \\nnetworks \\n๏Logical addressing \\n๏Routing\\n31\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nThe network layer is responsible  for \\nthe delivery of packets from  the \\noriginal source to the \\nfinal destination.\\nNote:\\n32\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSource-to-Destination delivery\\n33\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nPosition of IPv4 in TCP/IP protocol suite\\nIPv4\\n34\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv4\\n•Best-effort delivery\\n๏IPv4 is an unreliableand connectionlessdatagram protocol\\n๏Abest-effort delivery service.\\n๏best-effort IPv4 provides no error control or flow control(except for \\nerror detection on the header).\\n•Connectionless protocol\\n๏Each datagram is handled independently\\n๏Datagrams sent by the source to the same destination could\\n-Arrive out of order\\n-be lost or corrupted during transmission.\\n๏IPv4 relies on a high-level protocol to take of all these problem.\\n35\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv4 Datagrams\\n•Packets in the IPv4 layer are called Datagrams.\\n36\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nver\\nlength\\n32 bits\\ndata \\n(variable  length,\\ntypically a TCP \\nor UDP segment)\\n16-bit identifier\\nInternet\\nchecksum\\ntime to\\nlive\\n32 bit source IP address\\nIP protocol version number\\nheader length (bytes)\\nmax number\\nremaining hops\\n(decremented at \\neach router)\\nfor\\nfragmentation/\\nreassembly\\ntotal datagram\\nlength (bytes)\\nupper layer protocol\\nto deliver payload to\\nhead.\\nlen\\ntype of\\nservice\\n“type” of data \\nflgs\\nfragment\\noffset\\nupper\\nlayer\\n32 bit destination IP address\\nOptions (if any)\\nE.g. timestamp,\\nrecord route\\ntaken, specify\\nlist of routers \\nto visit.\\nhow much overhead \\nwith TCP?\\n20 bytes of TCP\\n20 bytes of IP\\n= 40 bytes + app \\nlayer overhead\\nIP datagram format\\n37\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv4 Datagram (cont’d)\\n•A datagram is a variable-length packet consisting of a \\nheaderand data.\\n•Header\\n๏Length : 20 –60 bytes\\n๏Contains information essential to routing and delivery.\\n•Version (VER) : It defines the Version of IPv4. it is 4.\\n•Header Length (HLEN) : Defining the total length of \\nthe datagram header in 4-byte words.\\n38\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv4 Datagram (cont’d)\\n•Protocol \\n๏Defining the higher level protocol that uses the \\nservices of the IP layer\\n-TCP, UDP, ICMP, and IGMP\\n-Multiplexing data from different higher level protocols\\nValueProtocol\\n1ICMP\\n2IGMP\\n6TCP\\n8EGP\\n17UDP\\n89OSPF\\n39\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv6 Datagram\\n40\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv6 Datagram\\n41\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSubnet with VLSM\\n192.168.10.0/24\\n42\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nRegular Subnet\\n7subnets; The largest subnet needs 60hosts \\nIf 3bits for subnet (8 subnets) 5bits for host (32 hosts)\\nIf 6bits for host (64 hosts) 2bits for subnet (4 subnets)\\n192.168.10.0/24\\n43\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nExercise\\n•A multinational  company  wishes to have an IPv4 addressing  plan for the new \\nbranch it has created  in Beirut. The Beirut branch has 5 departments  as follows:\\n๏Human Resources  Management  (HRM) with 12 staff;\\n๏Engineering  (ENG) with 23 staff ;\\n๏Information  system (IS) with 8 staff;\\n๏Marketing  and sales (MS) with 50 staff;\\n๏Accounting and auditing  (AA) with 15 staff.\\n•In total,  the Beirut branch has 108 staff. The network  allocated  for the branch is \\n192.168.100.0/24. While taking into account the evolution  of the branch, divide  the \\nnetwork  into several  sub-networks  according  to the departments.\\n•You should fill the below  table  for each department/  sub-network.  Briefly explain \\nthe different  choices.\\n44\\nDept. \\nName\\nNetwork \\naddress\\nPrefix \\nlength\\nUsableIP address  range\\n(First –Last)\\nBroadcast address\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nForwarding -Routing\\n223.1.1.1\\n223.1.1.3\\n223.1.1.4\\n223.1.2.2\\n223.1.2.1\\n223.1.2.6\\n223.1.3.2\\n223.1.3.1\\n223.1.3.27\\n223.1.1.2\\n223.1.7.0\\n223.1.7.1\\n223.1.8.0223.1.8.1\\n223.1.9.1\\n223.1.9.2\\nDestination \\nNetwork\\nNext hopInterface\\n0.0.0.0223.1.1.3FastEthernet\\nFastEthernet\\nDestination \\nNetwork\\nNext hopInterface\\n223.1.3.0/24223.1.7.1FastEthernet0/0\\n223.1.2.0/24223.1.9.1FastEthernet0/1\\n45\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIntroduction to Routing\\nStatic Routing\\n•Static Route Characteristics:\\n๏Must be configured manually\\n๏Must be adjusted manually by \\nthe administrator when there \\nis a change in the topology\\n๏Good for small non-redundant \\nnetworks\\n๏Often used in conjunction \\nwith a dynamic routing \\nprotocolfor configuring a \\ndefault route\\n46\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIntroduction to Routing\\nDynamic Routing\\n•Dynamic Routes Automatically:\\n๏Discover remote networks\\n๏Maintain up-to-date \\ninformation\\n๏Choose the best path to the \\ndestination\\n๏Find new best paths when \\nthere is a topology change\\n๏Dynamic routing can also \\nshare static default routes \\nwith the other routers.\\n47\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nAddress Resolution -ARP\\n48\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nMAC addresses and ARP\\n•IP address: \\n๏“Low” Network-layer address for interface\\n๏Used for layer 3 (network layer) forwarding\\n•MAC (or LAN or physical or Ethernet) address: \\n๏Function: used “locally” to get frame from one interface to \\nanother physically-connected interface (same network, in \\nIP-addressing sense)\\n๏48 bit MAC address (for most LANs) burned in NIC ROM, \\nalso sometimes software settable\\n๏e.g.: 1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD\\nhexadecimal (base 16) notation\\n(each “numeral” represents 4 bits)\\n49\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nLAN addresses and ARP\\neach adapter on LAN has unique LANaddress\\nadapter\\n1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD\\n58-23-D7-FA-20-B0\\n0C-C4-11-6F-E3-98\\n71-65-F7-2B-08-53\\nLAN\\n(wired or\\nwireless)\\n50\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nLAN addresses (more)\\n•MAC address allocation administered by IEEE\\n•Manufacturer buys portion of MAC address space (to \\nassure uniqueness)\\n•Analogy:\\n๏MAC address: like Social Security Number\\n๏IP address: like postal address\\n•MAC flat address  ➜portability \\n๏can move LAN card from one LAN to another\\n•IP hierarchical address not portable\\n๏address depends on IP subnet to which node is attached\\n51\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nARP: Address Resolution Protocol\\n•ARP table: each IP node (host, \\nrouter) on LAN has a ARP table\\n–IP/MAC address mappings for some \\nLAN nodes:\\n•< IP address; MAC address; TTL>\\n–TTL (Time To Live): time after which \\naddress mapping will be forgotten \\n(typically 20 min)\\nQuestion:how to determine\\ninterface’s MAC address, \\nknowing its IP address?\\n1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD\\n58-23-D7-FA-20-B0\\n0C-C4-11-6F-E3-98\\n71-65-F7-2B-08-53\\nLAN\\n137.196.7.23\\n137.196.7.78\\n137.196.7.14\\n137.196.7.88\\nIP addressMAC addressTTL\\n137.196.7.1458-23-D7-FA-20-B0\\n20\\n52\\nUse arpcommand to display ARP table on Windows or Linux\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nARP protocol: same LAN\\n1.A wants to send datagram to B\\n๏B’s MAC address not in A’s ARP table.\\n2.A broadcasts ARP query packet, containing B's IP address \\n๏Destination MAC address = FF-FF-FF-FF-FF-FF\\n๏All nodes on LAN receive ARP query \\n3.B receives ARP packet, replies to A with its (B's) MAC address\\n๏frame sent to A’s MAC address (unicast)\\n4.A caches (saves) IP-to-MAC address pair in its ARP table until \\ninformation becomes old (times out) \\n๏soft state: information that times out (goes away) unless refreshed\\n•ARP is “plug-and-play”:\\n๏Nodes create their ARP tables without intervention from net \\nadministrator\\n53\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nARP operation\\n54\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nHardware Type –\\nEthernet is type 1\\nProtocol Type-\\nIPv4=x0800\\nHardware Length: \\nlength of Ethernet \\nAddress (6)\\nProtocol Length: \\nlength of IPv4 \\naddress (4)\\nARP packet\\n55\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nThe ARP packet is encapsulated within an Ethernet packet.\\nNote: Type field for Ethernet is x0806\\nEncapsulation of ARP packet\\n56\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nFour cases using ARP\\n57\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nARP Example \\n58\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nARP –A each step\\nARP: Who has this IP?\\nARP: Who has this IP?\\nARP: Who has this IP?\\n59\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nDefault Gateways\\n•Devices need the following information \\nfor network access: IP address, subnet \\nmask, and default gateway.\\n•When a host sends a packet to a device \\nthat is on the same IP network, the packet \\nis forwarded out the host interface to the \\ndestination device. The router does not \\nneed to get involved.\\n•When a host sends a packet to a device on \\na different IP network, the packet is \\nforwarded to the default gateway because \\nthe host device cannot communicate with \\ndevices outside of the local network.\\n•The default gateway is the device that \\nroutes traffic from the local network to \\ndevices on remote networks, such as \\ndevices on the Internet.\\nRouters are also usually configured with their own default gateway.\\n60\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•walkthrough: send datagram from A to B via R\\n–Focus on addressing –at IP (datagram) and MAC layer \\n(frame)\\n–Assume A knows B’s IP address\\n–Assume A knows IP address of first hop router, R (how?)\\n–Assume A knows R’s MAC address (how?)\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\n61\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•A creates IP datagram with IP source A, destination B \\n•A creates link-layer frame with R's MAC address as \\ndestination address, frame contains A-to-B IP datagram\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\nMAC src: 74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nMAC dest: E6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\n62\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•Frame sent from A to R\\n•Frame received at R, datagram removed, passed \\nup to IP\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\nMAC src: 74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nMAC dest: E6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\n63\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•R forwards datagram with IP source A, destination B \\n•R creates link-layer frame with B's MAC address as \\ndestination address, frame contains A-to-B IP \\ndatagram\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\nMAC src: 1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\nMAC dest: 49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\n64\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•R forwards datagram with IP source A, destination B \\n•R creates link-layer frame with B's MAC address as \\ndestination address, frame contains A-to-B IP \\ndatagram\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\nMAC src: 1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\nMAC dest: 49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\n65\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•R forwards datagram with IP source A, destination B \\n•R creates link-layer frame with B's MAC address as dest, frame \\ncontains A-to-B IP datagram\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\nMAC src: 1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\nMAC dest: 49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\n* Check out the online interactive exercises for more \\nexamples:  http://gaia.cs.umass.edu/kurose_ross/interactive/\\n66\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIntroduction to Routing\\nRouter Packet Forwarding Decision\\n•What happens when the router receives the frame \\nfrom the host device?\\n67\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nSend a Packet\\n•PC1 must determine if the destination IPv4 address is on the same network. \\n•If it is on the same network, PC1 will obtain the destination MAC address from its ARP cache or use an \\nARP request.\\n•Because the destination network is on a different network, PC1 forwards the packet to its default \\ngateway.\\n68\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nSend a Packet\\n•To determine the MAC address of the default gateway, PC1 checks its ARP table for \\nthe IPv4 address of the default gateway and its corresponding MAC address. \\n๏An ARP request is sent if it is not found.\\n•When PC1 has the MAC address of Router R1, it can forward the packet. \\n69\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nForward to the Next Hop\\n•R1 examines the destination MAC address which matches the MAC address \\nof the receiving interface and copies the frame into its buffer.\\n•R1 identifies the Ethernet Type field as 0x800 which indicates that the \\nEthernet frame contains an IPv4 packet in the data portion of the frame.\\n70\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nForward to the Next Hop\\n•R1 de-encapsulates the Ethernet frame.\\n•Because the destination IPv4 address of the packet, 192.168.4.10,   does not match \\nany of the directly connected networks on R1, R1 searches the routing table for a \\ncorresponding route.\\n๏R1’s Routing Table has a route for the 192.168.4.0/24 network.\\n71\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nForward to the Next Hop\\n•The routethat R1 finds to the 192.168.4.0/24 network has a next-hopaddressof \\n192.168.2.2 and an exit interface of FastEthernet0/1.\\n•This will require that the IPv4 packet be encapsulated in a new Ethernet frame with \\nthe destination MAC address of the IPv4 address of the next-hop router, 192.168.2.2\\n72\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nForward to the Next Hop\\n•Because the exit interface is on an Ethernet network, R1 must resolve the \\nnext-hop IPv4 address with a destination MAC address using ARP, assuming \\nit is not in its ARP cache.\\n•When R1 has the MAC address for the next-hop, the Ethernet frame is \\nforwarded out of the FastEthernet0/1 interface of R1.\\n73\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nPacket Routing\\n•R2 examines the destination MAC address\\n๏Because it matches the MAC address of its receiving interface, R2 copies the \\nframe into its buffer.\\n•R2 determines that that frame contains an IPv4 packet in the data portion \\nof the frame.\\n74\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nPacket Routing\\n•R2 de-encapsulates the Ethernet frame.\\n•Because the destination IP address is on a different network, \\nthe routing table is searched to find a corresponding route for \\nthe destination IPv4 address. \\n75\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nPacket Routing\\n•The routing table of R2 has a routeto the 192.168.4.0/24 network \\nwith a next-hop IPv4 address of 192.168.3.2 and an exit interface of \\nSerial 0/0/0.   \\n•Because the exit interface is not Ethernet, R2 does not have to \\nresolve the next-hop IP-v4 address with a destination MAC address.\\n76\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nPacket Routing\\n•The IPv4 packet is encapsulatedinto a new data link frame used by \\nthe exit interface and sent out the Serial 0/0/0 exit interface.\\n•Because there are no MAC addresses on serial interfaces, R2 sets the \\ndata link destination address to an equivalent of a broadcast.\\n77\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nReach the Destination\\n•R3 copies the data link PPP frame into its buffer.\\n•R3 de-encapsulatesthe data link PPP frame.\\n•R3 searches the routing table for the destination IPv4 address of the \\npacket.\\n78\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nReach the Destination\\n•Because the destination network is on R3’s directly connected network, the \\npacket can be sent directly and does not need to be sent to another router.\\n•Because the exit interface is a directly connected Ethernet network, R3 \\nmust resolve the destination IPv4 address of the packet with a destination \\nMAC address by either finding it in its ARP cache or send out an ARP \\nrequest.\\n79\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nInternet Control Message Protocol \\n•The Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) \\n•Specified in [RFC 792], \\n•Used by hosts and routers to communicate network-\\nlayer information to each other. \\n•Most typical use of ICMP is for error reporting\\n•Often considered part of IP, but architecturally it lies \\njust above IP, as ICMP messages are carried inside IP \\ndatagrams. \\n๏ICMP messages are carried as IP payload\\n80\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nICMP Type and Code \\nTypeCode Description\\n00echo reply (ping)\\n30destination network unreachable\\n31destination host unreachable\\n32destination protocol unreachable\\n33destination port unreachable\\n36destination network unknown\\n37destination host unknown\\n80echo request (ping)\\n90route advertisement\\n100router discovery\\n110TTL expired\\n120bad IP header\\n81\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTrace Route –ICMP\\n•Source sends series of UDP segments (or ICMP Echo request) to destination host\\n๏First has TTL =1\\n๏Second has TTL=2, etc.\\n๏Unlikely port number\\n•When n\\nth\\ndatagram arrives to n\\nth\\nrouter:\\n๏Router discards datagram\\n๏Sends to source an ICMP message (type 11, code 0)\\n๏Datagram includes router IP address. Traceroute does DNS lookup to find name of router \\n(if any)\\n•When ICMP message arrives, source calculates RTT\\n•Traceroute repeat the process 3 times (To get average RTT)\\n•Stopping criterion\\n๏UDP segment eventually arrives at destination host\\n๏Destination returns ICMP “port unreachable” packet (type 3, code 3)\\n82\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTrace Route –ICMP\\n83\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTransport layer\\nThe transport layer is responsible for delivering segments from a source process to a \\nfinal destination process.\\n84\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTransport layer\\n•Transport Layer Responsibilities\\n๏Process-to-process delivery of entire message \\n๏Port addressing \\n๏Segmentation and reassembly \\n๏Connection control: connectionless or connection-oriented \\n๏End-to-end flow control \\n๏End-to-end error control \\n85\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nApplication Layer\\n•The application layer is responsible for providing \\nservices to the user.\\n86\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nThanks !\\n87\",\"summary\":\"Here is a detailed summary of the provided text in bullet points, covering main ideas, key concepts, important details, and definitions:\\n\\n**I3304 - Network Administration and Security (2023-2024)**\\n\\n*   **Course Overview:**\\n    *   **Title:** Network Administration and Security (I3304).\\n    *   **Instructors:** Ahmad Fadlallah, Ali RAAD.\\n    *   **Outline Covered:** Introduction, Network Layer, Transport Layer, Application Layer, Introduction to Security.\\n\\n**1. Introduction to Networking Fundamentals**\\n\\n*   **What's the Internet? (\\\"Nuts and Bolts\\\" View):**\\n    *   Comprises billions of connected computing devices (hosts/end systems) running network applications.\\n    *   Uses communication links (fiber, copper, radio, satellite) with a specific transmission rate (bandwidth).\\n    *   Packet switches (routers and switches) forward data chunks (packets).\\n    *   It is a \\\"network of networks,\\\" interconnected through Internet Service Providers (ISPs).\\n    *   Communication is controlled by protocols (e.g., TCP, IP, HTTP, 802.11).\\n    *   Internet standards are defined by RFCs (Request For Comments) from the IETF (Internet Engineering Task Force).\\n*   **What's the Internet? (A \\\"Service\\\" View):**\\n    *   An infrastructure providing services to applications (Web, VoIP, email, games, e-commerce, social networks).\\n    *   Offers a programming interface allowing application programs to \\\"connect\\\" and exchange data.\\n*   **What's a Protocol?:**\\n    *   Analogous to human protocols (e.g., introductions, asking time).\\n    *   For machines, protocols define the format, order of messages sent and received among network entities, and actions taken upon message transmission or receipt. All Internet communication is governed by protocols.\\n*   **Why Layering?:**\\n    *   **Purpose:** To manage the complexity of network systems.\\n    *   **Benefits:**\\n        *   Explicit structure helps identify and understand relationships between system pieces.\\n        *   Modularization eases system maintenance and updates.\\n        *   Changes in a layer's implementation are transparent to other layers.\\n    *   **Analogy:** A language translation service involving secretaries and translators, where each step adds/removes information specific to its function without altering the core message.\\n\\n**2. Network Reference Models**\\n\\n*   **Two Competing Models:** OSI and TCP/IP.\\n*   **OSI (Open Systems Interconnection) Model:**\\n    *   Developed by ISO (International Standards Organization).\\n    *   Composed of 7 layers.\\n    *   **Presentation Layer:** Allows applications to interpret data meaning (e.g., encryption, compression, machine-specific conventions).\\n    *   **Session Layer:** Handles synchronization, checkpointing, and recovery of data exchange.\\n    *   *(Note: The Internet stack often integrates these services directly into the application layer if needed, rather than having distinct layers.)*\\n*   **TCP/IP (Transfer Control Protocol) Model:**\\n    *   Used in ARPANET and the Internet, now the dominant model.\\n    *   Composed of 5 layers.\\n*   **Internet Protocol Stack (5-Layer Model - Dominant):**\\n    *   **Application Layer:** Supports network applications (e.g., FTP, SMTP, HTTP).\\n    *   **Transport Layer:** Manages process-to-process data transfer (e.g., TCP, UDP).\\n    *   **Network Layer:** Responsible for routing datagrams from source to destination (e.g., IP, routing protocols).\\n    *   **Link Layer:** Handles data transfer between neighboring network elements (e.g., Ethernet, 802.11 Wi-Fi, PPP).\\n    *   **Physical Layer:** Deals with the transmission of bits \\\"on the wire.\\\"\\n*   **Encapsulation:**\\n    *   The process where data (a message 'M') moves down the layers, and each layer adds its own header (and sometimes a trailer) to the data unit.\\n    *   `Message (M)` -> `Segment (Ht M)` -> `Datagram (Hn Ht M)` -> `Frame (Hl Hn Ht M)`.\\n    *   This includes Headers, Data, and Trailers.\\n*   **Peer-to-Peer Processes:** Each layer logically communicates with its corresponding layer on the destination system, even though actual data flow is vertical through the stack.\\n\\n**3. Physical Layer**\\n\\n*   **Responsibility:** Transmitting individual bits from one node to the next.\\n*   **Key Characteristics:**\\n    *   Defines physical characteristics of interfaces and transmission media.\\n    *   Handles the representation of bits (e.g., electrical signals, light pulses) without interpreting their meaning.\\n    *   Determines data rate (number of bits per second).\\n    *   Manages synchronization of bits.\\n*   **Transmission Media:** Mentioned as a component.\\n\\n**4. Data Link Layer**\\n\\n*   **Responsibility:** Transmitting frames from one node to the next.\\n*   **Key Responsibilities:**\\n    *   **Framing:** Defines data units called frames.\\n    *   **Physical Addressing:** Uses MAC addresses for local delivery.\\n    *   **Flow Control:** Manages data transmission rate between nodes.\\n    *   **Error Control:** Detects and/or corrects errors in frames.\\n    *   **Access Control:** Determines which device has control over the link at any given time.\\n*   **802.3 MAC Frame Structure (Ethernet):**\\n    *   **Preamble (7 bytes):** Alternating 0s and 1s for receiver synchronization.\\n    *   **Start Frame Delimiter (SFD) (1 byte):** `10101011` sequence, signals frame start, final sync opportunity.\\n    *   **Destination Address (DA) (6 bytes):** Physical address of the destination station(s).\\n    *   **Source Address (SA) (6 bytes):** Physical address of the sender.\\n    *   **Length/Type (2 bytes):**\\n        *   If < 1518, defines the length of the data field.\\n        *   If > 1536, defines the type of the encapsulated PDU (e.g., IPv4).\\n    *   **Data (46-1500 bytes):** Encapsulated data from upper-layer protocols.\\n    *   **CRC (Cyclic Redundancy Check) (4 bytes):** `CRC-32` for error detection.\\n\\n**5. Network Layer**\\n\\n*   **Responsibility:** Delivering packets from the original source to the final destination, potentially across multiple networks.\\n*   **Key Responsibilities:**\\n    *   **Logical Addressing:** Uses IP addresses for global identification.\\n    *   **Routing:** Determining the best path for packets to travel.\\n*   **IPv4 (Internet Protocol version 4):**\\n    *   **Best-Effort Delivery:** An unreliable and connectionless datagram protocol.\\n        *   Provides no error control or flow control (except for header error detection).\\n        *   Relies on higher-level protocols (e.g., TCP) to manage these issues.\\n    *   **Connectionless Protocol:** Each datagram is handled independently.\\n        *   Datagrams can arrive out of order, be lost, or be corrupted during transmission.\\n    *   **IPv4 Datagrams:** Packets at the IPv4 layer. Variable-length, consisting of a header and data.\\n    *   **IPv4 Header Fields (Key ones highlighted):**\\n        *   **Version (VER):** `4` for IPv4.\\n        *   **Header Length (HLEN):** Length of the header in 4-byte words (typically 20-60 bytes).\\n        *   Type of Service (ToS)\\n        *   Total Length\\n        *   Identifier\\n        *   Flags\\n        *   Fragment Offset\\n        *   **Time to Live (TTL):** Maximum number of hops before discard (decremented at each router).\\n        *   **Protocol:** Identifies the higher-level protocol in the payload (e.g., `1` for ICMP, `6` for TCP, `17` for UDP).\\n        *   Header Checksum\\n        *   **Source IP Address:** 32-bit.\\n        *   **Destination IP Address:** 32-bit.\\n        *   Options (if any).\\n    *   **Overhead:** Minimal IP + TCP header overhead is 40 bytes (20 IP + 20 TCP).\\n*   **IPv6 Datagram:** Mentioned with diagrams as a successor to IPv4, but specific field details are not provided in the text.\\n*   **Subnetting with VLSM (Variable Length Subnet Mask):**\\n    *   A method for dividing an IP network into smaller sub-networks, allowing for efficient use of IP addresses by assigning subnet masks of different lengths based on host requirements. An exercise demonstrates this concept for department allocation.\\n\\n**6. Routing Concepts**\\n\\n*   **Forwarding vs. Routing:**\\n    *   **Forwarding:** The router's action of moving a packet from an input interface to an appropriate output interface.\\n    *   **Routing:** The process of determining the end-to-end path that packets will take.\\n*   **Static Routing:**\\n    *   Characteristics: Must be manually configured and adjusted by an administrator.\\n    *   Use Case: Good for small, non-redundant networks. Often used with dynamic routing to configure a default route.\\n*   **Dynamic Routing:**\\n    *   Characteristics: Automatically discovers remote networks, maintains up-to-date routing information, chooses the best path, and finds new paths upon topology changes.\\n    *   Can also share static default routes with other routers.\\n*   **Address Resolution Protocol (ARP):**\\n    *   **MAC (LAN/Physical/Ethernet) Addresses:**\\n        *   Function: Used \\\"locally\\\" to get a frame from one interface to another physically connected interface within the same IP network/LAN.\\n        *   Format: 48-bit hexadecimal address (e.g., `1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD`), burned into NIC ROM, sometimes software-settable.\\n        *   Administration: MAC address space allocated by IEEE to manufacturers, ensuring uniqueness.\\n        *   Analogy: MAC address is like a Social Security Number (flat, portable across LANs); IP address is like a postal address (hierarchical, depends on subnet).\\n    *   **ARP Table:** Each IP node (host, router) maintains a table mapping IP addresses to MAC addresses for some LAN nodes. Includes a Time To Live (TTL) (e.g., 20 min) after which mappings are forgotten (soft state).\\n    *   **ARP Protocol (Same LAN Communication):**\\n        1.  Host A wants to send a datagram to Host B, but B's MAC address is unknown.\\n        2.  A broadcasts an ARP query packet (destination MAC `FF-FF-FF-FF-FF-FF`) containing B's IP address.\\n        3.  B receives the ARP query and replies directly to A with its MAC address (unicast).\\n        4.  A caches the IP-to-MAC mapping in its ARP table.\\n        *   **Plug-and-play:** ARP tables are built automatically without administrative intervention.\\n    *   **ARP Packet Structure:** Includes Hardware Type (Ethernet=1), Protocol Type (IPv4=0x0800), Hardware Length (6 for Ethernet MAC), Protocol Length (4 for IPv4), Operation Code (request/reply), Sender/Target MAC and IP addresses.\\n    *   **Encapsulation of ARP:** An ARP packet is encapsulated within an Ethernet frame (Ethernet Type field = `0x0806`).\\n*   **Default Gateways:**\\n    *   Devices require an IP address, subnet mask, and default gateway to access a network.\\n    *   For destinations on the same IP network, packets are forwarded directly to the destination MAC.\\n    *   For destinations on a *different* IP network, packets are forwarded to the default gateway (a router).\\n    *   The default gateway routes traffic between the local network and remote networks (e.g., the Internet). Routers themselves typically also have default gateways.\\n*   **Addressing: Routing to Another LAN (Detailed Process):**\\n    *   **A to R (Router):**\\n        *   Host A creates an IP datagram (Source IP = A, Dest IP = B).\\n        *   Host A encapsulates this IP datagram in a link-layer frame (Source MAC = A, Dest MAC = R's interface MAC).\\n        *   Frame is sent to Router R.\\n    *   **R Processing:**\\n        *   Router R receives the frame, removes the link-layer header, and passes the IP datagram to its IP layer.\\n        *   Router R determines the next hop for Dest IP B (which is B itself if directly connected, or another router).\\n        *   Router R encapsulates the *original* IP datagram (Source IP = A, Dest IP = B) into a *new* link-layer frame (Source MAC = R's outgoing interface MAC, Dest MAC = B's MAC).\\n        *   Frame is sent to Host B.\\n    *   **B Processing:** Host B receives the frame, removes the link-layer header, and processes the IP datagram.\\n*   **Switching Packets Between Networks (Multi-hop Routing Example):**\\n    *   **PC1 to R1:** PC1 identifies destination as remote, sends packet to its default gateway (R1). PC1 uses ARP to find R1's MAC address, then encapsulates the IP packet in an Ethernet frame with R1's MAC as destination.\\n    *   **R1 to R2:** R1 receives frame, de-encapsulates IPv4 packet. Consults routing table to find next hop (R2). R1 uses ARP (if Ethernet link) to find R2's MAC address, then re-encapsulates the IP packet in a new Ethernet frame with R2's MAC as destination.\\n    *   **R2 to R3 (Serial Link):** R2 receives frame, de-encapsulates IPv4 packet. Consults routing table to find next hop (R3) via a serial interface. Since serial links don't use MAC addresses, R2 encapsulates the IP packet into a new PPP (or similar) data link frame, setting the destination address to a broadcast equivalent.\\n    *   **R3 to Destination PC:** R3 receives PPP frame, de-encapsulates IPv4 packet. Destination network is directly connected to R3. R3 uses ARP to find the final destination PC's MAC address, then encapsulates the IP packet in a new Ethernet frame with the PC's MAC as destination.\\n\\n**7. Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP)**\\n\\n*   **Purpose:** Used by hosts and routers to communicate network-layer information, primarily for error reporting.\\n*   **Architectural Placement:** Logically above IP; ICMP messages are carried as IP payload within IP datagrams.\\n*   **Common ICMP Type and Code Values:**\\n    *   `0 0`: Echo reply (Ping response).\\n    *   `3 0`: Destination network unreachable.\\n    *   `3 3`: Destination port unreachable.\\n    *   `8 0`: Echo request (Ping request).\\n    *   `11 0`: TTL (Time to Live) expired.\\n*   **Traceroute (using ICMP or UDP):**\\n    *   **Mechanism:**\\n        1.  Source sends a series of UDP segments (or ICMP Echo requests) to the destination, starting with a TTL of 1, then 2, and so on. Unlikely port numbers are used for UDP segments.\\n        2.  When the `n`-th datagram reaches the `n`-th router, the router discards it (because TTL expires) and sends an ICMP \\\"TTL expired\\\" message (Type 11, Code 0) back to the source. This message includes the router's IP address.\\n        3.  Upon receiving the ICMP message, the source calculates the Round Trip Time (RTT) to that router. Traceroute typically repeats this process 3 times.\\n        4.  **Stopping Criterion:** When the UDP segment eventually reaches the destination host, the host returns an ICMP \\\"Port Unreachable\\\" packet (Type 3, Code 3) because the specified port is not listening.\\n\\n**8. Transport Layer**\\n\\n*   **Responsibility:** Delivering segments from a source *process* to a final destination *process*.\\n*   **Key Responsibilities:**\\n    *   Process-to-process delivery of the entire message.\\n    *   **Port Addressing:** Uses port numbers to distinguish between different applications/processes on a host.\\n    *   **Segmentation and Reassembly:** Breaking application messages into smaller segments for transmission and reassembling them at the destination.\\n    *   **Connection Control:** Can be connectionless (UDP) or connection-oriented (TCP).\\n    *   End-to-end flow control.\\n    *   End-to-end error control.\\n*   **Protocols Mentioned in Outline:** UDP Protocol, TCP Protocol (with Connection management, Flow control, Congestion control). *(Details not provided in text)*\\n\\n**9. Application Layer**\\n\\n*   **Responsibility:** Providing services directly to the user.\\n*   **Protocols Mentioned in Outline:** HTTP, FTP, Mail protocols, DNS. *(Details not provided in text)*\\n\\n**10. Introduction to Security**\\n\\n*   *(This section was listed in the outline but had no corresponding content in the provided text.)*\\n*   **Topics to Cover:** Security services, Cryptography, Digital Signature, Principle of network security protocols.\"}","timestamp":"2026-03-20 21:43:38"}
