timization\nOptimization\n\nDigital Simulation & ModelingInterpolation & Extrapolation\nIntroduction (cont’d)\n•Multimodalcases: Both localand globaloptimacan \noccur for a single function \n7\n\nDigital Simulation & ModelingInterpolation & Extrapolation\nIntroduction (cont’d)\n•How to distinguish global optimum from local one?\n๏By graphingto gain insight into the behavior of the \nfunction.\n๏Using randomly generated starting guessesand picking \nthe largest of the optimaas global.\n๏Perturbing the starting point associated to a local \noptima to see if the routine returns a better point or the \nsame local optima.\n8\n\nDigital Simulation & ModelingInterpolation & Extrapolation\nGolden-Section Search\n•A unimodalfunction has a singlemaximum (resp. \nminimum) in the a given interval. For a unimodal \nfunction:\n๏Pick two pointsthat will bracket your extremum [x\nl\n, x\nu\n].\n๏Pick an additional third pointwithin this intervalto \ndetermine whether a maximum occurred.\n๏Pick a fourth pointto determine whether the maximum \nhas occurred within the first three or last three points\n๏The key is making this approach efficient by choosing \nintermediate points wiselythus minimizing the function \nevaluationsby replacing the old values with new values.\n9\n\nDigital Simulation & ModelingInterpolation & Extrapolation\nGolden-Section Search (cont’d)\n•The sum of the two sub lengths 푙\n1\nand 푙\n2\nmust equal the original interval length.\n•The ratio of the length must be equal\n10\nGolden Ratio\n\nDigital Simulation & ModelingInterpolation & Extrapolation\nGolden Ratio (History)\n11\n\nDigital Simulation & ModelingInterpolation & Extrapolation\nGolden-Section Search (cont’d)\n•The method starts with two initial \nguesses, 푥\n푙\nand 푥\n푢\n, that bracket \none local extremum of f(x)\n•two interior points 푥\n1\nand 푥\n2\nare \nchosen according to the golden \nratio\n•The function is evaluated at these \ntwo interior points.\n12\n\nDigital Simulation & ModelingInterpolation & Extrapolation\nGolden-Section Search (cont’d)\n•If f(x\n1\n)>f(x\n2\n) \n=> the domain of x to the left of x\n2\nfrom x\nl\nto x\n2 \ndoes not contain the maximum \n=> can be eliminated => new x\nl\n= x\n2\n•If f(x\n2\n)>f(x\n1\n)\n=> the domain of x to the right of x\n1\nfrom x\nl\nto x\n2\n, \nwould have been eliminated => new x\nu\n= x\n1\n•New x\n1\nis determined as before\n13\n•Stop condition: |x\nu\n-x\nl\n| < Ɛ, max = (x\nl\n+ x\nu\n)/2\n\nDigital Simulation & ModelingInterpolation & Extrapolation\nExercise\n•Use the golden-section search to find the maximum of the \nfollowing function  within the interval x\nl\n=0 and x\nu\n=4.\n•Note\n14\n\nDigital Simulation & ModelingInterpolation & Extrapolation\nExercise -Solution\n15\n•Because f(x\n2\n) > f(x\n1\n), the maximum is in the interval defined by x\nl\n, x\n2\n, and x\n1\n. \n•For the new interval\n•LB remains x\nl\n= 0, x\n1\nbecomes the UB => x\nu\n= 2.472. \n•Former x\n2\nvalue becomes the new x\n1\n, that is, x\n1\n= 1.528.\n\nDigital Simulation & ModelingInterpolation & Extrapolation\nExercise -Solution (cont’d)\n16\n\nDigital Simulation & ModelingInterpolation & Extrapolation\nQuadratic Interpolation\n•Parabolic interpolation takes advantage of the fact that a \nsecond-order polynomialoften provides a good \napproximationto the shape of f(x) near an optimum\n17\n\nDigital Simulation & ModelingInterpolation & Extrapolation\nQuadratic Interpolation (cont’d)\n•There is only onequadratic polynomial or parabola\nconnecting three points. \n•if we have three points that jointly bracket an optimum, we \ncan fit a parabola to the points. \n•Then we can differentiate it, set the result equal to zero, and \nsolve for an estimate of the optimal x. \n•It can be shown through some algebraic manipulations that the \nresult is\n•x\n0\n, x\n1\n, and x\n2\nare the initial guesses, and x\n3\nis the value of xthat \ncorresponds to the maximum value of the parabolic fitto the \nguesses\n•and so on (same as golden section search)\n18\n\nDigital Simulation & ModelingInterpolation & Extrapolation\nExercise\n•Use parabolic interpolation to approximate the maximum \nof the following function  with initial guesses of x\n0\n=0, x\n1=\n1, \nand x\n2 = \n4.\n•Note:\n19\n\nDigital Simulation & ModelingInterpolation & Extrapolation\nExercise -Solution\n20\nBecause the function value for the new point is higher than for the intermediate \npoint (x\n1\n) and the new x value is to the right of the intermediate point, the lower \nguess (x\n0\n) is discarded. Therefore, for the next iteration\n\nDigital Simulation & ModelingInterpolation & Extrapolation\nExercise -Solution\n21\nGolden Section Search\nQuadratic\n\nDigital Simulation & ModelingInterpolation & Extrapolation\nNewton’s Method\n•Based on the Newton-Raphson \nmethod to find the root of an \nequation\n•The Newton-Raphson method is \nbased on the principle that if the \ninitial guess of the root of f(x) = \n0 is at x\ni\n, then if one draws the \ntangent to the curve at f(x\ni\n),the \npoint x\ni+1\nwhere the tangent \ncrosses the x-axis is an \nimproved estimate of the root \n22\n\nDigital Simulation & ModelingInterpolation & Extrapolation\nNewton’s Method (cont’d)\n•Consider a new function g(x)=f'(x). \n•The optimal value x* satisfies: f'(x*)=g(x*)=0\n•We can use the following as a technique to the extremum \nof f(x).\n•Start with an initial guess x\n0\nand repeat the iterations until \nfinding f’(x\nk\n) = 0 (or less than some value)\n23\n\nDigital Simulation & ModelingInterpolation & Extrapolation\nExercise\n•Use Newton’s method to approximate the maximum of the \nfollowing function  with initial guesses of x\n0\n=2.5\n•Note:\n24\n\nDigital Simulation & ModelingInterpolation & Extrapolation\nExercise -Solution\n25\n\nDigital Simulation & ModelingInterpolation & Extrapolation\nExercise\nEmploy the following methods to find the maximum of\nf (x) = 4x-1.8x\n2\n+ 1.2x\n3\n-0.3x\n4\n(a) Golden-section search (x\nl\n= -2, x\nu\n= 4, Ɛ\ns\n= 1%).\n(b) Parabolic interpolation (x\n0\n=1.75, x\n1\n=2, x\n2\n=2.5, iter. = 4).\n(c)  Newton’s method (x\n0\n= 3, Ɛ\ns\n=1%).\n26","storage_path":"uploads\\1774036099588_I3344_2021_2022_Part_6.pdf","summary":"Here's a detailed summary of the provided text, organized into bullet points:\n\n**I3344: Numerical Simulation & Modeling (Ahmad Fadlallah)**\n\n**I. Tentative Syllabus Overview**\n\n*   **Interpolation and Extrapolation:**\n    *   Linear methods: Linear regression ($y = ax + b$), correlation, standard deviation.\n    *   Non-linear methods: K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN).\n    *   Validation: K-fold cross-validation method.\n*   **Solving Linear Equations:**\n    *   Direct methods: Gauss elimination, LU decomposition.\n    *   Iterative methods: Jacobi, Gauss-Seidel.\n*   **Derivation:**\n    *   Finite Difference Method (FDM): Euler, Runge-Kutta.\n*   **Integration:**\n    *   Surface estimation.\n    *   Finite Element Method (FEM).\n    *   Monte Carlo method.\n    *   Comparison of two methods.\n*   **Non-linear Problems:**\n    *   Bisection method.\n*   **Optimization.**\n*   **Introduction to Parallel Computing:**\n    *   Notion and underlying algorithms.\n\n**II. Outline of Current Section**\n\n*   Introduction to Optimization.\n*   Golden Section Search.\n*   Newton Method.\n\n**III. Introduction to Optimization**\n\n*   **Relationship between Root Location and Optimization:** Both involve guessing and searching for a point on a function.\n    *   **Root Location:** Searching for zeros of a function ($f(x) = 0$).\n    *   **Optimization:** Searching for the minimum or the maximum of a function.\n*   **Mathematical Background / General Optimization Problem Statement:**\n    *   **Goal:** Find **x** that minimizes or maximizes $f(\\mathbf{x})$.\n    *   **Subject to:**\n        *   $d_i(\\mathbf{x}) \\le a_i$ (inequality constraints)\n        *   $e_i(\\mathbf{x}) = b_i$ (equality constraints)\n    *   **Definitions:**\n        *   **x:** An n-dimensional design vector (the variables to be optimized).\n        *   **f(x):** The objective function (the function to be minimized or maximized).\n        *   **d_i(x), e_i(x):** Constraint functions.\n        *   **a_i, b_i:** Constants.\n*   **Types of Optimization Problems:**\n    *   One-Dimensional Unconstrained Optimization.\n    *   Multidimensional Unconstrained Optimization.\n    *   Constrained Optimization.\n*   **Multimodal Cases:** A single function can have both local and global optima.\n*   **Distinguishing Global Optimum from Local Optima:**\n    *   Graphing the function to gain insight into its behavior.\n    *   Using randomly generated starting guesses and picking the largest (for maximization) or smallest (for minimization) of the found optima as the global one.\n    *   Perturbing the starting point associated with a local optimum to check if the routine returns a better point or the same local optimum.\n\n**IV. Golden-Section Search**\n\n*   **Applicability:** For a **unimodal function**, which has a single maximum (or minimum) within a given interval.\n*   **Core Idea:**\n    *   Bracket the extremum within an interval $[x_l, x_u]$.\n    *   Select additional interior points to efficiently reduce the search interval.\n    *   Minimize function evaluations by reusing old values and choosing new points based on the Golden Ratio.\n*   **The Golden Ratio (Φ):** A special ratio that guides the selection of interior points for efficient interval reduction.\n    *   The ratio of lengths of sub-intervals must be equal.\n*   **Method Steps:**\n    1.  Start with two initial guesses, $x_l$ and $x_u$, that bracket one local extremum.\n    2.  Choose two interior points, $x_1$ and $x_2$, according to the golden ratio.\n    3.  Evaluate the function at these two interior points: $f(x_1)$ and $f(x_2)$.\n    4.  **For Maximization:**\n        *   If $f(x_1) > f(x_2)$, the maximum is not to the left of $x_2$. The new lower bound becomes $x_l = x_2$.\n        *   If $f(x_2) > f(x_1)$, the maximum is not to the right of $x_1$. The new upper bound becomes $x_u = x_1$.\n    5.  A new interior point is determined based on the updated interval, and the process repeats.\n*   **Stop Condition:** When the interval length $|x_u - x_l|$ is less than a specified tolerance $\\epsilon$.\n*   **Optimal Point Estimate:** The maximum (or minimum) is approximated as $(x_l + x_u) / 2$.\n*   **Example:** Demonstrates finding the maximum of a function within an interval by iteratively narrowing the search using the golden-section search rules.\n\n**V. Quadratic (Parabolic) Interpolation**\n\n*   **Core Idea:** A second-order polynomial (parabola) often provides a good approximation to the shape of $f(x)$ near an optimum.\n*   **Requirement:** Uses three points ($x_0, x_1, x_2$) that jointly bracket an optimum.\n*   **Method:**\n    1.  Fit a unique parabola through the three given points.\n    2.  Differentiate the parabolic equation, set the result to zero, and solve for an estimate of the optimal $x$.\n*   **Formula for Optimal x ($x_3$):**\n    $x_3 = \\frac{f(x_0)(x_1^2 - x_2^2) + f(x_1)(x_2^2 - x_0^2) + f(x_2)(x_0^2 - x_1^2)}{2f(x_0)(x_1 - x_2) + 2f(x_1)(x_2 - x_0) + 2f(x_2)(x_0 - x_1)}$\n    *   This formula estimates the optimal x-value ($x_3$) corresponding to the maximum of the parabolic fit.\n*   **Iteration:** Similar to the golden section search, one of the original points is discarded and replaced with $x_3$ to continue refining the estimate.\n*   **Example:** Demonstrates finding the maximum using three initial guesses and iteratively applying the formula.\n\n**VI. Newton's Method**\n\n*   **Basis:** Adapted from the Newton-Raphson method for finding roots of an equation.\n*   **Application to Optimization:** To find the extremum of $f(x)$, we search for the root of its first derivative, $f'(x)=0$. Let $g(x) = f'(x)$, then we are finding the root of $g(x)=0$.\n*   **Iterative Formula:**\n    $x_{i+1} = x_i - \\frac{f'(x_i)}{f''(x_i)}$\n    *   Where $x_i$ is the current guess, $f'(x_i)$ is the first derivative, and $f''(x_i)$ is the second derivative of the objective function $f(x)$ evaluated at $x_i$.\n*   **Stop Condition:** Iterate until $f'(x_k)$ is approximately zero (or less than a specified tolerance).\n*   **Example:** Demonstrates finding the maximum using an initial guess and iteratively applying Newton's method.\n\n**VII. General Exercise**\n\n*   An exercise is provided to compare the three methods (Golden-section search, Parabolic interpolation, Newton's method) for finding the maximum of a given function:\n    $f(x) = 4x - 1.8x^2 + 1.2x^3 - 0.3x^4$\n    *   Specific initial conditions and stopping criteria are given for each method.","timestamp":"2026-03-20 21:48:31"}
