{"file_size":3407719,"filename":"Chapter 5_ Structural Design Patterns (3).pdf","level":"info","message":"Input object for PDFDocument:","mime_type":"application/pdf","original_text":"\n\nChapter5 :\nStructural Design Patterns\nInstructor: Abed Safadi, Ph.D.\n\nReferences \n2\n\nRichard N. Taylor, Nenad Medvidovie, Eric M. Dashofy: Software \nArchitecture Foundations, Theory, and Practice.\n\nMarckRichards:  Software Architecture Patterns.\n\nErich Gamma, Richard Helm, Ralph Johnson & John Vlissides: \nDesign Patterns : Elements of Reusable Object-Oriented \nSoftware.\n\nRobert C. Martin : Clean Architecture : A Craftsman’s Guide to \nSoftware Structure and Design\n\nWebsites notes\n\nStructural patterns\n\nStructuralpatternsfocusonthecompositionofobjects\nand classes into larger structures while keeping these\nstructuresflexibleandefficient.\n\nThis composition refers to how these classes and\nobjects are put together to achieve specific\nfunctionalitiesorbehaviors.\n\nStructural patterns related to the problems of\norganization of objects in software. The essence of\nstructural patterns is to organize the compositional\nstructureofobjectsinastandardandefficientway.\n3\n\nPlan\n•\n•\n•\n•\n•\n4\n\nFlyweightpattern\n5\nIntent\n\nThe “Flyweightpattern\" is used to optimize the number of\nobjectsstoredinyourapplication'smemory.\n\nFlyweightis a structural design pattern that allows you to\nefficientlyutilizeavailablememorybysharingcommonpartsof\nstate among multiple objects instead of keeping all of the data\nineachobject.\n\nUsedwhenyouneedtocreatealargenumberofsimilarobjects\n\nTo reduce memory usage you share Objects that are similar in\nsomewayratherthancreatingnewones\n\nExample before Flyweight pattern\n6\nCreating 20 circles of different locations\n\nFlyweight -Problem\n7\npublic interfaceShape{\nvoiddraw();\n}\npublic classCircleimplementsShape{\nprivateStringcolor;\nprivate intx;\nprivate inty;\nprivate intradius;\npublicCircle(Stringcolor){\nthis.color=color;\n}\npublic voidsetX(intx) {\nthis.x=x;\n}\npublic voidsetY(inty) {\nthis.y=y;\n}\npublic voidsetRadius(intradius) {\nthis.radius=radius;\n}\n@Override\npublic voiddraw() {\nSystem.out.println(\"Circle: Draw() [Color : \"+color +\", x : \"+x +\", y :\"+y +\", radius :\"+radius);\n}\n}\nCircle.java\nShape.java\nImplementation : We are going to create aShapeinterface and concrete classCircle \nimplementing theShapeinterface.\n\nFlyweight -Problem\n8\nImplementation : We are going to create aShapeinterface and concrete classCircle \nimplementing theShapeinterface.\npublic classDemo{\nprivate static final Stringcolors[] = { \"Red\", \"Green\", \"Blue\", “Black”,   \n”White”, };\npublic static voidmain(String[]args) {\nfor(inti=0;i <20; ++i) { \nCirclecircle=newCircle(color [(int)(Math.random()*colors.length)]);\ncircle.setX(Math.random()*100); \ncircle.setY(Math.random()*100);\ncircle.setRadius(Math.random()*100); \ncircle.draw();\n}\n}\n}\nBefore  Flyweight Design Patterns we must create 20 objects \nin order to draw 20 circles .\nDemo.java\n\nFlyweight -Solution\n9\nFlyweight pattern tries toreuse already existing similar kind objects by storing \nthem and creates new object when no matching object is found.\nA flyweight is an object through which we try to minimize memory usage by \nsharing data as much as possible. \nTwo common terms are used here:\n—intrinsic state : color\n—extrinsic state: size.  \nThe first category (intrinsic) can be stored in the flyweight and is shareable. The \nother one depends on the flyweight’s context and is non-shareable.\nWe will demonstrate this pattern by drawing 20 circles of different locations \nbut we will create only 5 objects\n\nFlyweight -Solution\n10\nOnly 5 colors are available so color property (intrinsic state) is \nused to check already existingCircleobjects\n\nFlyweight -Solution\n11\nFor example, in each group all circles have the same color. Other parts of a circle s \nstate, such as radius is  unique to each circle. After all, the values of this field \nchange over time.\nThis data represents the always changing context in which the circle exists, while \nthe color remain constant for each circle.\nThis constant data of an object is usually called theintrinsic state. It lives within \nthe object; other objects can only read it, not change it. The rest of the object’s \nstate, often altered “from the outside” by other objects, is called theextrinsic \nstate.\n\nFlyweight -Solution\n12\n\nShapeFactoryhas aHashMapofCirclehaving \nkey as color (intrinsic state) of \ntheCircleobject. Whenever a request comes \nto create a circle of particular color \ntoShapeFactory, it checks the circle object in \nitsHashMap, if object ofCircle found, that \nobject is returned otherwise a new object is \ncreated, stored in hashmapfor future use, \nand returned to client.\n\nFlyWeightPatternDemo, our demo class, will \nuseShapeFactoryto get aShapeobject. It will \npass information (red / green / blue/ white/ \nblack/) toShapeFactoryto get the circle of \ndesired color it needs.\n\nJava translation\n13\nCreate a factory to generate object of concrete class based on \ngiven information.\nShapeFactory.java\n\nJava translation\n14\nUse the factory to get object of concrete class by passing an \ninformation such as color.\nFlyweightPatternDemo.java\n\nJava translation\n15\n\nVerify the output\n\nFlyweightClass diagram\n16\nTheFlyweightFactory\nmanages a pool of\nexisting  flyweights.\nWiththefactory,clients\ndon’t create flyweights\ndirectly. Instead, they\ncall the factory, passing\nit bits of the intrinsic\nstate of the desired\nflyweight. The factory\nlooks over previously\ncreated flyweights and\neither  returns  an\nexisting  one  that\nmatches search criteria\nor creates a new one if\nnothingisfound.\nTheFlyweightclass contains the portion of the original object’s\nstate that can be shared between multiple objects. The same\nflyweightobjectcanbeusedinmanydifferentcontexts.Thestate\nstoredinsideaflyweightiscalledintrinsic.Thestatepassedtothe\nflyweight’smethodsiscalledextrinsic.\n\nPlan\n•\n•\n•\n•\n•\n17\n\nBridge pattern\nIntent\n\nDecouple anabstractionfrom itsimplementationso that the\ntwocanvaryindependently\n\nIn this pattern, the abstract class is separated from the\nimplementation class and we provide a bridge interface\nbetween them. This interface helps us to make concrete class\nfunctionalities independent from the interface implementer\nclass.Wecanmodifythesedifferentkindofclassesstructurally\nwithoutaffectingeachother.\n18\n\nExample : Before Bridge Design Pattern\n19\n•Remote is an abstract class. It contains:\n•an instance variable sound\n•two methods soundUpand soundDown\n•two abstract methods onPressMiddleand onPressNine\n•If it is remote for TV: onPressNinego to the channel nine.\n•If it is remote forDVD: onPressNinepause.\n•If it is Sonyremote: onPressMiddleopen menu.\n•If it is Toshibaremote: onPressMiddleturn off.\n\nBridge pattern problem\n20\n•Problems\n•Create a remote for LCD  creation of three new data types (RemoteLCD,\nRemoteLCDSony, RemoteLCDToshiba).\n•Code redundancy(duplication of methods)!\n\nJava Translation\n21\n\nJava Translation\n22\n\nJava Translation\n23\n\nBridge-Solution \nThe Bridge pattern attempts to solve this problem by switching from inheritance to \nthe object composition. What this means is that you extract one of the dimensions into \na separate class hierarchy, so that the original classes will reference an object of the new \nhierarchy, instead of having all of its state and behaviors within one class.\n24\nAbstract class Remote has an Interface type\n\nJava Translation\n25\n\nJava Translation\n26\n\nJava Translation\n27\n\nJava Translation\n28\n\nBridge Pattern UML diagram\n29\n\nPlan\n•\n•\n•\n•\n•\n30\n\nComposite design pattern\nIntent\n\nCompositeisastructuraldesignpatternthatletsyoucompose\nobjectsintotreestructuresandthenworkwiththesestructures\nasiftheywereindividualobjects.\no\nIn other words, when we need to create a structure in a way\nthattheobjectsinthestructurehastobetreatedthesameway,\nwecanapplycompositedesignpattern\no\nIn object-oriented programming, we make a composite object\nwhen we have many objects withcommon functionalities.This\nrelationship is also termed a “has-a” relationship among\nobjects.\n31\n\nExample\n32\nLet's imagine asimple graphic applicationwhere users can draw\nshapessuchascircles,squares,andgroupsofshapes.Eachshape\ncanbemanipulatedindividually(moved,resized,colored)orasa\ngroup.\n•\nLeaf:Individualshapeslikeacircleorasquare.\n•\nComposite:Agroupofshapesthatcancontaincircles,squares,\norothergroups.\n•\nComponent:Thecommoninterfacethatdefinesoperationslike\nmove,resize,andcolor.\nUsers of the application can select a single shape or a group of\nshapes and apply the same operations. This approach simplifies\nthe management of the application's graphic objects, making\noperationsoncomplexshapesaseasyasonsimpleshapes.\n\nComposite-Example\n33\nWe can think of any organization that has many \ndepartments, and in turn each department has \nmany employees to serve. \nPlease note that actually all are employees of the \norganization. \nGroupings of employees create a department, and \nthose departments ultimately can be grouped \ntogether to build the whole organization.\n•You have a set of employees\n•An employee could be a manager(of a set of employees), a \ndeveloper, or a designer\nExample(Employees)\n\nUML Diagram\n34\n\nJava Translation\n35\n\nJava Translation\n36\n\nJava Translation\n37\n\nJava Translation\n38\n\nComposite pattern-Solution\n39\nTheComponentinterface describes\noperations that are common to both simple\nandcomplexelementsofthetree.\nTheLeafis a basic element of a tree that\ndoesn’thavesub-elements.\nTheContainer(akacomposite)isanelement\nthat has sub-elements: leaves or other\ncontainers. A container doesn’t know the\nconcreteclassesofitschildren.Itworkswith\nall sub-elements only via the component\ninterface.\nUpon receiving a request, a container\ndelegates the work to its sub-elements,\nprocesses intermediate results and then\nreturnsthefinalresulttotheclient.\n\nPlan\n•\n•\n•\n•\n•\n40\n\nProxy design pattern\n41\nIntent\n\nProxyis a structural design pattern that lets you provide a\nsubstitute or placeholder for another object. A proxy controls\naccesstotheoriginalobject,allowingyoutoperformsomething\neither before or after the request gets through to the\noriginalobject.\nTypesofproxies:\n\nProtectionproxy:controlsaccesstotheoriginalobject\n\nVirtualproxy:createanexpensiveobjectifneededonly\n\n.....\n\nProtection Proxy Problem\n42\nExample:\nA very simple real life scenario is our University internet, which\nrestricts few site access. The proxy first checks the host you are\nconnectingto,ifitisnotpartofrestrictedsitelist,thenitconnects\ntotherealinternet.ThisexampleisbasedonProtectionproxies.\n\nJava Translation-Solution\n43\n\nJava Translation-Solution\n44\n\nJava Translation-Solution\n45\nResult\n\nPoxy design pattern Structure\n46\nTheProxypatternsuggeststhatyoucreateanewproxyclasswith\nthe same interface as an original service object. Then you update\nyour app so that it passes the proxy object to all of the original\nobject’s clients. Upon receiving a request from a client, the proxy\ncreatesarealserviceobjectanddelegatesalltheworktoit.\nTheService Interfacedeclares the interface of the\nService.Theproxymustfollowthisinterfacetobeableto\nmaskitselfasaserviceobject.\nTheProxyclass has a reference field that points to a\nservice object. After the proxy finishes its processing\n(e.g., lazy initialization, logging, access control,\ncaching,etc.),itpassestherequesttotheserviceobject.\nTheServiceisaclassthatprovidessomeusefulbusiness\nlogic.\n\nPlan\n•\n•\n•\n•\n•\n47\n\nAdapter Pattern\n48\nAdapteris a structural design pattern that allows objects with \nincompatible interfaces tocollaborate.\nAreallifeexamplecouldbeacaseofcardreaderwhichactsasan\nadapter between memory card and a laptop. You plugin the\nmemory card into card reader and card reader into the laptop so\nthatmemorycardcanbereadvialaptop.\n\nProblem\n49\nImagine that you’re creating a stock market monitoring app. The\napp downloads the stock data from multiple sources in XML\nformatandthendisplaysnice-lookingchartsanddiagramsforthe\nuser.\n\nAt some point, you decide to improve the app by integrating a\nsmart 3rd-party analytics library. But there’s a catch: the\nanalyticslibraryonlyworkswithdatainJSONformat.\n\nBad Solution\n50\nYou could change the library to work with XML. However, this \nmight break some existing code that relies on the library. And \nworse, you might not have access to the library’s source code in \nthe first place, making this approach impossible.\n\nGood Solution\n51\nYou can create anadapter. This is a special object that converts \nthe interface of one object so that another object can understand \nit.\nHere’s how it works:\n\nThe adapter gets an interface, compatible with one of the existing \nobjects.\n\nUsing this interface, the existing object can safely call the adapter’s \nmethods.\n\nUpon receiving a call, the adapter passes the request to the second \nobject, but in a format and order that the second object expects.\n\nGood Solution\n52\nTo solve the dilemma of incompatible formats, you can create XML-to-\nJSON adapters for every class of the analytics library that your code\nworkswithdirectly.Thenyouadjustyourcodetocommunicatewiththe\nlibrary only via these adapters. When an adapter receives a call, it\ntranslates the incoming XML data into a JSON structure and passes the\ncalltotheappropriatemethodsofawrappedanalyticsobject.\n\nStructure\n53\n\nExample\n54\nWe have aMediaPlayerinterface and a concrete  classAudioPlayer\nimplementing theMediaPlayerinterface.AudioPlayercan play mp3 \nformat audio files by default\n\nExample\n55\nWe are having another interfaceAdvancedMediaPlayerand concrete \nclasses implementing theAdvancedMediaPlayerinterface. These classes \ncan play Vlcand Mp4 format files.\n\nExample\n56\nWe want to makeAudioPlayerto play other formats as well. To achieve \nthis, we have created an adapter classMediaAdapterwhich implements \ntheMediaPlayerinterface and usesAdvancedMediaPlayerobjects to play \nthe required format.\nAudioPlayeruses the adapter classMediaAdapterpassing it the desired audio type \nwithout knowing the actual class which can play the desired format.\nAdapterPatternDemo, our demo class will useAudioPlayerclass to play various\nformats.\n\nStep 1\n57\n\nCreate interfaces for Media Player and Advanced Media Player.\n\nStep 2\n58\n\nCreate concrete classes implementing theAdvancedMediaPlayerinterface.\n\nStep 3\n59\n\nCreate adapter class implementing theMediaPlayerinterface.\n\nStep 4\n60\n\nCreate concrete class implementing theMediaPlayerinterface.\n\nStep 5\n61\n\nUse the AudioPlayerto play different types of audio formats.\n\nStep 6\n62\n\nVerify the output.\n\nQuestions? \n63","storage_path":"uploads\\1774036365413_Chapter_5__Structural_Design_Patterns__3_.pdf","summary":"Here's a detailed summary of the provided text on Structural Design Patterns:\n\n## Chapter 5: Structural Design Patterns\n\n**Instructor:** Abed Safadi, Ph.D.\n\n**References:**\n*   Richard N. Taylor, Nenad Medvidovie, Eric M. Dashofy: *Software Architecture Foundations, Theory, and Practice.*\n*   Marck Richards: *Software Architecture Patterns.*\n*   Erich Gamma, Richard Helm, Ralph Johnson & John Vlissides: *Design Patterns : Elements of Reusable Object-Oriented Software.*\n*   Robert C. Martin: *Clean Architecture : A Craftsman’s Guide to Software Structure and Design.*\n*   Websites notes\n\n---\n\n### Introduction to Structural Patterns\n\n*   **Focus:** Composition of objects and classes into larger structures.\n*   **Goal:** Keep these structures flexible and efficient.\n*   **Definition:** These patterns address problems related to the organization of objects in software.\n*   **Essence:** To organize the compositional structure of objects in a standard and efficient way.\n*   **Composition:** Refers to how classes and objects are put together to achieve specific functionalities or behaviors.\n\n---\n\n### Flyweight Pattern\n\n*   **Intent:**\n    *   Optimize the number of objects stored in an application's memory.\n    *   Efficiently utilize available memory by sharing common parts of state among multiple objects, instead of keeping all data in each object.\n    *   Used when a large number of similar objects need to be created.\n    *   Reduces memory usage by sharing objects that are similar in some way, rather than creating new ones.\n*   **Problem (Example before Flyweight):**\n    *   Creating 20 `Circle` objects, each with its own `color`, `x`, `y`, `radius`.\n    *   If each `Circle` instance holds all this data, creating many circles (even if some share colors) results in 20 distinct objects, consuming significant memory.\n*   **Solution:**\n    *   The Flyweight pattern reuses already existing similar objects by storing them.\n    *   It creates a new object only when no matching object is found.\n    *   Minimizes memory usage by sharing data as much as possible.\n*   **Key Concepts (State Categories):**\n    *   **Intrinsic State:**\n        *   Shareable among multiple objects.\n        *   Stored within the flyweight object (e.g., `color` of a circle).\n        *   Remains constant for the object; other objects can only read it, not change it.\n    *   **Extrinsic State:**\n        *   Non-shareable; depends on the flyweight's context.\n        *   Passed to the flyweight's methods (e.g., `x`, `y`, `radius` of a circle).\n        *   Often altered \"from the outside\" by other objects.\n*   **How it Works (ShapeFactory Example):**\n    *   A `ShapeFactory` manages a `HashMap` of `Circle` objects, using the circle's `color` (intrinsic state) as the key.\n    *   When a client requests a `Circle` of a particular color:\n        1.  The `ShapeFactory` checks its `HashMap` for an existing `Circle` object with that `color`.\n        2.  If found, the existing object is returned.\n        3.  If not found, a new `Circle` object is created (with the specified `color`), stored in the `HashMap` for future use, and then returned to the client.\n    *   The client then sets the `x`, `y`, and `radius` (extrinsic state) on the returned `Circle` object.\n    *   This way, only a few `Circle` objects (one for each unique color) are created, while many circles with different locations and radii can be drawn.\n*   **UML Diagram Elements:**\n    *   **`Flyweight` class:** Contains the intrinsic (shareable) portion of the object's state. Extrinsic state is passed to its methods.\n    *   **`FlyweightFactory`:** Manages a pool of existing flyweights. Clients request flyweights from the factory, passing intrinsic state. The factory either returns an existing matching flyweight or creates a new one.\n\n---\n\n### Bridge Pattern\n\n*   **Intent:** Decouple an abstraction from its implementation so that the two can vary independently.\n*   **Key Idea:**\n    *   The abstract class is separated from the implementation class.\n    *   A \"bridge interface\" is provided between them.\n    *   This interface allows concrete class functionalities to be independent of the interface implementer class.\n    *   Different kinds of classes (abstraction and implementation) can be modified structurally without affecting each other.\n*   **Problem (Example before Bridge - Remote Control):**\n    *   An `abstract Remote` class has general methods (`soundUp`, `soundDown`) and abstract methods (`onPressMiddle`, `onPressNine`) whose behavior depends on the device (TV, DVD) and brand (Sony, Toshiba).\n    *   Direct inheritance leads to a complex hierarchy (e.g., `RemoteTV`, `RemoteDVD`, then `RemoteTVSony`, `RemoteTVToshiba`, etc.).\n    *   Adding a new device type (e.g., `LCD`) or brand quickly multiplies the number of classes (`RemoteLCD`, `RemoteLCDSony`, `RemoteLCDToshiba`), causing significant code redundancy and a \"cartesian product\" issue.\n*   **Solution:**\n    *   Switches from inheritance to **object composition**.\n    *   One of the dimensions (e.g., device type or brand) is extracted into a separate class hierarchy, defined by an interface.\n    *   The original abstract class (`Remote`) holds a reference to an object of this new hierarchy (via its interface).\n    *   **Example:**\n        *   An `IDevice` interface is created with methods like `turnOn`, `turnOff`, `setChannel`, `pause`, etc.\n        *   Concrete device classes (`TV`, `DVD`) implement `IDevice`.\n        *   The `Remote` abstract class holds an `IDevice` instance.\n        *   Specific `Remote` types (e.g., `SonyRemote`, `ToshibaRemote`) become refined abstractions that interact with the `IDevice` instance through its interface, independent of the concrete device type.\n        *   This allows new remotes (abstractions) and new devices (implementations) to be added without affecting each other.\n*   **UML Diagram Elements:**\n    *   **`Abstraction`:** Defines the abstraction's interface and maintains a reference to an `Implementor` object.\n    *   **`RefinedAbstraction`:** Extends `Abstraction` to provide concrete implementations.\n    *   **`Implementor`:** Defines the interface for implementation classes. This is the \"bridge\" interface.\n    *   **`ConcreteImplementorA`, `ConcreteImplementorB`:** Implement the `Implementor` interface.\n\n---\n\n### Composite Design Pattern\n\n*   **Intent:**\n    *   Lets you compose objects into tree structures.\n    *   Allows working with these structures as if they were individual objects.\n    *   Applies when objects in a structure need to be treated the same way.\n*   **Key Concept:** Establishes a \"has-a\" relationship among objects where a composite object contains many other objects with common functionalities.\n*   **Example (Graphic Application):**\n    *   Users can draw shapes (circles, squares) and groups of shapes.\n    *   Operations (move, resize, color) should apply to both individual shapes and entire groups uniformly.\n    *   **Roles:**\n        *   **Component:** The common interface (e.g., `Graphic`) that defines operations applicable to both simple and complex elements (e.g., `move`, `resize`, `color`).\n        *   **Leaf:** Basic elements of the tree that don't have sub-elements (e.g., `Circle`, `Square`). They implement the `Component` interface.\n        *   **Composite (Container):** Elements that have sub-elements (either `Leaf`s or other `Container`s). They also implement the `Component` interface.\n        *   A `Container` works with all its sub-elements only via the `Component` interface. Upon receiving a request, it delegates the work to its sub-elements and aggregates results.\n*   **Example (Employees):**\n    *   An organization has employees. An employee can be a manager (who manages a set of employees), a developer, or a designer.\n    *   All are essentially \"employees.\" Groupings of employees form departments, which form the organization.\n    *   The pattern allows treating individual employees and departments (groups of employees) uniformly.\n*   **UML Diagram Elements:**\n    *   **`Component`:** Declares the interface for objects in the composition and for accessing and managing its child components.\n    *   **`Leaf`:** Represents leaf objects in the composition. A leaf has no children.\n    *   **`Composite`:** Defines behavior for components having children, and stores child components. It implements the `Component` interface and manages its children (add, remove, getChild).\n\n---\n\n### Proxy Design Pattern\n\n*   **Intent:** Provide a substitute or placeholder for another object.\n*   **Function:** Controls access to the original object, allowing operations to be performed either before or after the request gets through to the original object.\n*   **Types of Proxies:**\n    *   **Protection Proxy:** Controls access to the original object based on permissions or restrictions (e.g., blocking access to certain websites).\n    *   **Virtual Proxy:** Creates an expensive object only when it is actually needed (lazy initialization).\n    *   *(Other types exist but are not detailed in the text.)*\n*   **Problem (Protection Proxy Example):**\n    *   Direct access to the `Internet` might allow users to connect to any host.\n    *   Scenario: A university internet system needs to restrict access to certain websites.\n*   **Solution (Protection Proxy):**\n    *   Create a `ProxyInternet` class that acts as an intermediary.\n    *   This `ProxyInternet` implements the same interface as the `RealInternet` (e.g., `Internet`).\n    *   When a client requests to `connectTo(host)`:\n        1.  The `ProxyInternet` first checks if the `host` is part of a restricted access list.\n        2.  If the host is allowed, the proxy then delegates the request to the actual `RealInternet` object.\n        3.  If the host is restricted, the proxy denies access without ever involving the `RealInternet`.\n*   **UML Diagram Elements:**\n    *   **`Service Interface`:** Declares the common interface that both the `Service` (real object) and `Proxy` must follow, allowing the proxy to mask itself as the service.\n    *   **`Proxy` class:**\n        *   Has a reference field that points to a `Service` object.\n        *   Upon receiving a client request, it performs its own processing (e.g., access control, logging, caching, lazy initialization).\n        *   After its processing, it passes the request to the `Service` object.\n    *   **`Service` class:** The real object that provides the useful business logic.\n\n---\n\n### Adapter Pattern\n\n*   **Intent:** Allows objects with incompatible interfaces to collaborate.\n*   **Real-life Analogy:** A card reader acts as an adapter between a memory card (incompatible interface) and a laptop (expects a different interface).\n*   **Problem (Stock Market Monitoring App):**\n    *   An app downloads stock data in XML format.\n    *   It needs to integrate a 3rd-party analytics library that *only* works with data in JSON format.\n    *   **Bad Solution:** Modifying the library to accept XML is problematic (breaks existing code, source code might not be available).\n*   **Good Solution:** Create an **Adapter**.\n    *   **How it works:**\n        1.  The adapter is a special object that converts the interface of one object so that another object can understand it.\n        2.  The adapter gets an interface compatible with the *existing object* (the app that produces XML).\n        3.  The existing object calls the adapter's methods.\n        4.  Upon receiving a call, the adapter translates the incoming data (e.g., XML) into the format expected by the *second object* (the analytics library, expecting JSON).\n        5.  Then, it passes the translated request to the appropriate methods of the wrapped analytics object.\n*   **Example (Media Player):**\n    *   `MediaPlayer` interface (default plays MP3). `AudioPlayer` implements `MediaPlayer`.\n    *   `AdvancedMediaPlayer` interface (plays VLC, MP4). `VlcPlayer`, `Mp4Player` implement `AdvancedMediaPlayer`.\n    *   **Goal:** Enable `AudioPlayer` to play other formats (VLC, MP4).\n    *   **Solution:**\n        1.  Create a `MediaAdapter` class that implements the `MediaPlayer` interface.\n        2.  `MediaAdapter` internally holds a reference to an `AdvancedMediaPlayer` object.\n        3.  When `AudioPlayer` (client) requests to play a format like \"vlc\" or \"mp4\" via `MediaAdapter`:\n            *   The `MediaAdapter` determines which `AdvancedMediaPlayer` (e.g., `VlcPlayer` or `Mp4Player`) is needed.\n            *   It then delegates the play request to the appropriate method of that `AdvancedMediaPlayer` object (`playVlc` or `playMp4`).\n        4.  The `AudioPlayer` uses the `MediaAdapter` without needing to know the actual class that plays the desired format.\n*   **UML Diagram Elements:**\n    *   **`Target`:** The interface that the client expects to use (e.g., `MediaPlayer`).\n    *   **`Client`:** Interacts with objects conforming to the `Target` interface (e.g., `AudioPlayer`).\n    *   **`Adaptee`:** The existing class with an incompatible interface that needs to be adapted (e.g., `AdvancedMediaPlayer`).\n    *   **`Adapter`:** Implements the `Target` interface and contains an instance of the `Adaptee`. It translates requests from the `Client` into a format understood by the `Adaptee`.","timestamp":"2026-03-20 21:53:10"}
{"level":"info","message":"Mapping JSON to PDFDocument: {\"filename\":\"Chapter 5_ Structural Design Patterns (3).pdf\",\"file_size\":3407719,\"mime_type\":\"application/pdf\",\"storage_path\":\"uploads\\\\1774036365413_Chapter_5__Structural_Design_Patterns__3_.pdf\",\"original_text\":\"\\n\\nChapter5 :\\nStructural Design Patterns\\nInstructor: Abed Safadi, Ph.D.\\n\\nReferences \\n2\\n\\nRichard N. Taylor, Nenad Medvidovie, Eric M. Dashofy: Software \\nArchitecture Foundations, Theory, and Practice.\\n\\nMarckRichards:  Software Architecture Patterns.\\n\\nErich Gamma, Richard Helm, Ralph Johnson & John Vlissides: \\nDesign Patterns : Elements of Reusable Object-Oriented \\nSoftware.\\n\\nRobert C. Martin : Clean Architecture : A Craftsman’s Guide to \\nSoftware Structure and Design\\n\\nWebsites notes\\n\\nStructural patterns\\n\\nStructuralpatternsfocusonthecompositionofobjects\\nand classes into larger structures while keeping these\\nstructuresflexibleandefficient.\\n\\nThis composition refers to how these classes and\\nobjects are put together to achieve specific\\nfunctionalitiesorbehaviors.\\n\\nStructural patterns related to the problems of\\norganization of objects in software. The essence of\\nstructural patterns is to organize the compositional\\nstructureofobjectsinastandardandefficientway.\\n3\\n\\nPlan\\n•\\n•\\n•\\n•\\n•\\n4\\n\\nFlyweightpattern\\n5\\nIntent\\n\\nThe “Flyweightpattern\\\" is used to optimize the number of\\nobjectsstoredinyourapplication'smemory.\\n\\nFlyweightis a structural design pattern that allows you to\\nefficientlyutilizeavailablememorybysharingcommonpartsof\\nstate among multiple objects instead of keeping all of the data\\nineachobject.\\n\\nUsedwhenyouneedtocreatealargenumberofsimilarobjects\\n\\nTo reduce memory usage you share Objects that are similar in\\nsomewayratherthancreatingnewones\\n\\nExample before Flyweight pattern\\n6\\nCreating 20 circles of different locations\\n\\nFlyweight -Problem\\n7\\npublic interfaceShape{\\nvoiddraw();\\n}\\npublic classCircleimplementsShape{\\nprivateStringcolor;\\nprivate intx;\\nprivate inty;\\nprivate intradius;\\npublicCircle(Stringcolor){\\nthis.color=color;\\n}\\npublic voidsetX(intx) {\\nthis.x=x;\\n}\\npublic voidsetY(inty) {\\nthis.y=y;\\n}\\npublic voidsetRadius(intradius) {\\nthis.radius=radius;\\n}\\n@Override\\npublic voiddraw() {\\nSystem.out.println(\\\"Circle: Draw() [Color : \\\"+color +\\\", x : \\\"+x +\\\", y :\\\"+y +\\\", radius :\\\"+radius);\\n}\\n}\\nCircle.java\\nShape.java\\nImplementation : We are going to create aShapeinterface and concrete classCircle \\nimplementing theShapeinterface.\\n\\nFlyweight -Problem\\n8\\nImplementation : We are going to create aShapeinterface and concrete classCircle \\nimplementing theShapeinterface.\\npublic classDemo{\\nprivate static final Stringcolors[] = { \\\"Red\\\", \\\"Green\\\", \\\"Blue\\\", “Black”,   \\n”White”, };\\npublic static voidmain(String[]args) {\\nfor(inti=0;i <20; ++i) { \\nCirclecircle=newCircle(color [(int)(Math.random()*colors.length)]);\\ncircle.setX(Math.random()*100); \\ncircle.setY(Math.random()*100);\\ncircle.setRadius(Math.random()*100); \\ncircle.draw();\\n}\\n}\\n}\\nBefore  Flyweight Design Patterns we must create 20 objects \\nin order to draw 20 circles .\\nDemo.java\\n\\nFlyweight -Solution\\n9\\nFlyweight pattern tries toreuse already existing similar kind objects by storing \\nthem and creates new object when no matching object is found.\\nA flyweight is an object through which we try to minimize memory usage by \\nsharing data as much as possible. \\nTwo common terms are used here:\\n—intrinsic state : color\\n—extrinsic state: size.  \\nThe first category (intrinsic) can be stored in the flyweight and is shareable. The \\nother one depends on the flyweight’s context and is non-shareable.\\nWe will demonstrate this pattern by drawing 20 circles of different locations \\nbut we will create only 5 objects\\n\\nFlyweight -Solution\\n10\\nOnly 5 colors are available so color property (intrinsic state) is \\nused to check already existingCircleobjects\\n\\nFlyweight -Solution\\n11\\nFor example, in each group all circles have the same color. Other parts of a circle s \\nstate, such as radius is  unique to each circle. After all, the values of this field \\nchange over time.\\nThis data represents the always changing context in which the circle exists, while \\nthe color remain constant for each circle.\\nThis constant data of an object is usually called theintrinsic state. It lives within \\nthe object; other objects can only read it, not change it. The rest of the object’s \\nstate, often altered “from the outside” by other objects, is called theextrinsic \\nstate.\\n\\nFlyweight -Solution\\n12\\n\\nShapeFactoryhas aHashMapofCirclehaving \\nkey as color (intrinsic state) of \\ntheCircleobject. Whenever a request comes \\nto create a circle of particular color \\ntoShapeFactory, it checks the circle object in \\nitsHashMap, if object ofCircle found, that \\nobject is returned otherwise a new object is \\ncreated, stored in hashmapfor future use, \\nand returned to client.\\n\\nFlyWeightPatternDemo, our demo class, will \\nuseShapeFactoryto get aShapeobject. It will \\npass information (red / green / blue/ white/ \\nblack/) toShapeFactoryto get the circle of \\ndesired color it needs.\\n\\nJava translation\\n13\\nCreate a factory to generate object of concrete class based on \\ngiven information.\\nShapeFactory.java\\n\\nJava translation\\n14\\nUse the factory to get object of concrete class by passing an \\ninformation such as color.\\nFlyweightPatternDemo.java\\n\\nJava translation\\n15\\n\\nVerify the output\\n\\nFlyweightClass diagram\\n16\\nTheFlyweightFactory\\nmanages a pool of\\nexisting  flyweights.\\nWiththefactory,clients\\ndon’t create flyweights\\ndirectly. Instead, they\\ncall the factory, passing\\nit bits of the intrinsic\\nstate of the desired\\nflyweight. The factory\\nlooks over previously\\ncreated flyweights and\\neither  returns  an\\nexisting  one  that\\nmatches search criteria\\nor creates a new one if\\nnothingisfound.\\nTheFlyweightclass contains the portion of the original object’s\\nstate that can be shared between multiple objects. The same\\nflyweightobjectcanbeusedinmanydifferentcontexts.Thestate\\nstoredinsideaflyweightiscalledintrinsic.Thestatepassedtothe\\nflyweight’smethodsiscalledextrinsic.\\n\\nPlan\\n•\\n•\\n•\\n•\\n•\\n17\\n\\nBridge pattern\\nIntent\\n\\nDecouple anabstractionfrom itsimplementationso that the\\ntwocanvaryindependently\\n\\nIn this pattern, the abstract class is separated from the\\nimplementation class and we provide a bridge interface\\nbetween them. This interface helps us to make concrete class\\nfunctionalities independent from the interface implementer\\nclass.Wecanmodifythesedifferentkindofclassesstructurally\\nwithoutaffectingeachother.\\n18\\n\\nExample : Before Bridge Design Pattern\\n19\\n•Remote is an abstract class. It contains:\\n•an instance variable sound\\n•two methods soundUpand soundDown\\n•two abstract methods onPressMiddleand onPressNine\\n•If it is remote for TV: onPressNinego to the channel nine.\\n•If it is remote forDVD: onPressNinepause.\\n•If it is Sonyremote: onPressMiddleopen menu.\\n•If it is Toshibaremote: onPressMiddleturn off.\\n\\nBridge pattern problem\\n20\\n•Problems\\n•Create a remote for LCD  creation of three new data types (RemoteLCD,\\nRemoteLCDSony, RemoteLCDToshiba).\\n•Code redundancy(duplication of methods)!\\n\\nJava Translation\\n21\\n\\nJava Translation\\n22\\n\\nJava Translation\\n23\\n\\nBridge-Solution \\nThe Bridge pattern attempts to solve this problem by switching from inheritance to \\nthe object composition. What this means is that you extract one of the dimensions into \\na separate class hierarchy, so that the original classes will reference an object of the new \\nhierarchy, instead of having all of its state and behaviors within one class.\\n24\\nAbstract class Remote has an Interface type\\n\\nJava Translation\\n25\\n\\nJava Translation\\n26\\n\\nJava Translation\\n27\\n\\nJava Translation\\n28\\n\\nBridge Pattern UML diagram\\n29\\n\\nPlan\\n•\\n•\\n•\\n•\\n•\\n30\\n\\nComposite design pattern\\nIntent\\n\\nCompositeisastructuraldesignpatternthatletsyoucompose\\nobjectsintotreestructuresandthenworkwiththesestructures\\nasiftheywereindividualobjects.\\no\\nIn other words, when we need to create a structure in a way\\nthattheobjectsinthestructurehastobetreatedthesameway,\\nwecanapplycompositedesignpattern\\no\\nIn object-oriented programming, we make a composite object\\nwhen we have many objects withcommon functionalities.This\\nrelationship is also termed a “has-a” relationship among\\nobjects.\\n31\\n\\nExample\\n32\\nLet's imagine asimple graphic applicationwhere users can draw\\nshapessuchascircles,squares,andgroupsofshapes.Eachshape\\ncanbemanipulatedindividually(moved,resized,colored)orasa\\ngroup.\\n•\\nLeaf:Individualshapeslikeacircleorasquare.\\n•\\nComposite:Agroupofshapesthatcancontaincircles,squares,\\norothergroups.\\n•\\nComponent:Thecommoninterfacethatdefinesoperationslike\\nmove,resize,andcolor.\\nUsers of the application can select a single shape or a group of\\nshapes and apply the same operations. This approach simplifies\\nthe management of the application's graphic objects, making\\noperationsoncomplexshapesaseasyasonsimpleshapes.\\n\\nComposite-Example\\n33\\nWe can think of any organization that has many \\ndepartments, and in turn each department has \\nmany employees to serve. \\nPlease note that actually all are employees of the \\norganization. \\nGroupings of employees create a department, and \\nthose departments ultimately can be grouped \\ntogether to build the whole organization.\\n•You have a set of employees\\n•An employee could be a manager(of a set of employees), a \\ndeveloper, or a designer\\nExample(Employees)\\n\\nUML Diagram\\n34\\n\\nJava Translation\\n35\\n\\nJava Translation\\n36\\n\\nJava Translation\\n37\\n\\nJava Translation\\n38\\n\\nComposite pattern-Solution\\n39\\nTheComponentinterface describes\\noperations that are common to both simple\\nandcomplexelementsofthetree.\\nTheLeafis a basic element of a tree that\\ndoesn’thavesub-elements.\\nTheContainer(akacomposite)isanelement\\nthat has sub-elements: leaves or other\\ncontainers. A container doesn’t know the\\nconcreteclassesofitschildren.Itworkswith\\nall sub-elements only via the component\\ninterface.\\nUpon receiving a request, a container\\ndelegates the work to its sub-elements,\\nprocesses intermediate results and then\\nreturnsthefinalresulttotheclient.\\n\\nPlan\\n•\\n•\\n•\\n•\\n•\\n40\\n\\nProxy design pattern\\n41\\nIntent\\n\\nProxyis a structural design pattern that lets you provide a\\nsubstitute or placeholder for another object. A proxy controls\\naccesstotheoriginalobject,allowingyoutoperformsomething\\neither before or after the request gets through to the\\noriginalobject.\\nTypesofproxies:\\n\\nProtectionproxy:controlsaccesstotheoriginalobject\\n\\nVirtualproxy:createanexpensiveobjectifneededonly\\n\\n.....\\n\\nProtection Proxy Problem\\n42\\nExample:\\nA very simple real life scenario is our University internet, which\\nrestricts few site access. The proxy first checks the host you are\\nconnectingto,ifitisnotpartofrestrictedsitelist,thenitconnects\\ntotherealinternet.ThisexampleisbasedonProtectionproxies.\\n\\nJava Translation-Solution\\n43\\n\\nJava Translation-Solution\\n44\\n\\nJava Translation-Solution\\n45\\nResult\\n\\nPoxy design pattern Structure\\n46\\nTheProxypatternsuggeststhatyoucreateanewproxyclasswith\\nthe same interface as an original service object. Then you update\\nyour app so that it passes the proxy object to all of the original\\nobject’s clients. Upon receiving a request from a client, the proxy\\ncreatesarealserviceobjectanddelegatesalltheworktoit.\\nTheService Interfacedeclares the interface of the\\nService.Theproxymustfollowthisinterfacetobeableto\\nmaskitselfasaserviceobject.\\nTheProxyclass has a reference field that points to a\\nservice object. After the proxy finishes its processing\\n(e.g., lazy initialization, logging, access control,\\ncaching,etc.),itpassestherequesttotheserviceobject.\\nTheServiceisaclassthatprovidessomeusefulbusiness\\nlogic.\\n\\nPlan\\n•\\n•\\n•\\n•\\n•\\n47\\n\\nAdapter Pattern\\n48\\nAdapteris a structural design pattern that allows objects with \\nincompatible interfaces tocollaborate.\\nAreallifeexamplecouldbeacaseofcardreaderwhichactsasan\\nadapter between memory card and a laptop. You plugin the\\nmemory card into card reader and card reader into the laptop so\\nthatmemorycardcanbereadvialaptop.\\n\\nProblem\\n49\\nImagine that you’re creating a stock market monitoring app. The\\napp downloads the stock data from multiple sources in XML\\nformatandthendisplaysnice-lookingchartsanddiagramsforthe\\nuser.\\n\\nAt some point, you decide to improve the app by integrating a\\nsmart 3rd-party analytics library. But there’s a catch: the\\nanalyticslibraryonlyworkswithdatainJSONformat.\\n\\nBad Solution\\n50\\nYou could change the library to work with XML. However, this \\nmight break some existing code that relies on the library. And \\nworse, you might not have access to the library’s source code in \\nthe first place, making this approach impossible.\\n\\nGood Solution\\n51\\nYou can create anadapter. This is a special object that converts \\nthe interface of one object so that another object can understand \\nit.\\nHere’s how it works:\\n\\nThe adapter gets an interface, compatible with one of the existing \\nobjects.\\n\\nUsing this interface, the existing object can safely call the adapter’s \\nmethods.\\n\\nUpon receiving a call, the adapter passes the request to the second \\nobject, but in a format and order that the second object expects.\\n\\nGood Solution\\n52\\nTo solve the dilemma of incompatible formats, you can create XML-to-\\nJSON adapters for every class of the analytics library that your code\\nworkswithdirectly.Thenyouadjustyourcodetocommunicatewiththe\\nlibrary only via these adapters. When an adapter receives a call, it\\ntranslates the incoming XML data into a JSON structure and passes the\\ncalltotheappropriatemethodsofawrappedanalyticsobject.\\n\\nStructure\\n53\\n\\nExample\\n54\\nWe have aMediaPlayerinterface and a concrete  classAudioPlayer\\nimplementing theMediaPlayerinterface.AudioPlayercan play mp3 \\nformat audio files by default\\n\\nExample\\n55\\nWe are having another interfaceAdvancedMediaPlayerand concrete \\nclasses implementing theAdvancedMediaPlayerinterface. These classes \\ncan play Vlcand Mp4 format files.\\n\\nExample\\n56\\nWe want to makeAudioPlayerto play other formats as well. To achieve \\nthis, we have created an adapter classMediaAdapterwhich implements \\ntheMediaPlayerinterface and usesAdvancedMediaPlayerobjects to play \\nthe required format.\\nAudioPlayeruses the adapter classMediaAdapterpassing it the desired audio type \\nwithout knowing the actual class which can play the desired format.\\nAdapterPatternDemo, our demo class will useAudioPlayerclass to play various\\nformats.\\n\\nStep 1\\n57\\n\\nCreate interfaces for Media Player and Advanced Media Player.\\n\\nStep 2\\n58\\n\\nCreate concrete classes implementing theAdvancedMediaPlayerinterface.\\n\\nStep 3\\n59\\n\\nCreate adapter class implementing theMediaPlayerinterface.\\n\\nStep 4\\n60\\n\\nCreate concrete class implementing theMediaPlayerinterface.\\n\\nStep 5\\n61\\n\\nUse the AudioPlayerto play different types of audio formats.\\n\\nStep 6\\n62\\n\\nVerify the output.\\n\\nQuestions? \\n63\",\"summary\":\"Here's a detailed summary of the provided text on Structural Design Patterns:\\n\\n## Chapter 5: Structural Design Patterns\\n\\n**Instructor:** Abed Safadi, Ph.D.\\n\\n**References:**\\n*   Richard N. Taylor, Nenad Medvidovie, Eric M. Dashofy: *Software Architecture Foundations, Theory, and Practice.*\\n*   Marck Richards: *Software Architecture Patterns.*\\n*   Erich Gamma, Richard Helm, Ralph Johnson & John Vlissides: *Design Patterns : Elements of Reusable Object-Oriented Software.*\\n*   Robert C. Martin: *Clean Architecture : A Craftsman’s Guide to Software Structure and Design.*\\n*   Websites notes\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Introduction to Structural Patterns\\n\\n*   **Focus:** Composition of objects and classes into larger structures.\\n*   **Goal:** Keep these structures flexible and efficient.\\n*   **Definition:** These patterns address problems related to the organization of objects in software.\\n*   **Essence:** To organize the compositional structure of objects in a standard and efficient way.\\n*   **Composition:** Refers to how classes and objects are put together to achieve specific functionalities or behaviors.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Flyweight Pattern\\n\\n*   **Intent:**\\n    *   Optimize the number of objects stored in an application's memory.\\n    *   Efficiently utilize available memory by sharing common parts of state among multiple objects, instead of keeping all data in each object.\\n    *   Used when a large number of similar objects need to be created.\\n    *   Reduces memory usage by sharing objects that are similar in some way, rather than creating new ones.\\n*   **Problem (Example before Flyweight):**\\n    *   Creating 20 `Circle` objects, each with its own `color`, `x`, `y`, `radius`.\\n    *   If each `Circle` instance holds all this data, creating many circles (even if some share colors) results in 20 distinct objects, consuming significant memory.\\n*   **Solution:**\\n    *   The Flyweight pattern reuses already existing similar objects by storing them.\\n    *   It creates a new object only when no matching object is found.\\n    *   Minimizes memory usage by sharing data as much as possible.\\n*   **Key Concepts (State Categories):**\\n    *   **Intrinsic State:**\\n        *   Shareable among multiple objects.\\n        *   Stored within the flyweight object (e.g., `color` of a circle).\\n        *   Remains constant for the object; other objects can only read it, not change it.\\n    *   **Extrinsic State:**\\n        *   Non-shareable; depends on the flyweight's context.\\n        *   Passed to the flyweight's methods (e.g., `x`, `y`, `radius` of a circle).\\n        *   Often altered \\\"from the outside\\\" by other objects.\\n*   **How it Works (ShapeFactory Example):**\\n    *   A `ShapeFactory` manages a `HashMap` of `Circle` objects, using the circle's `color` (intrinsic state) as the key.\\n    *   When a client requests a `Circle` of a particular color:\\n        1.  The `ShapeFactory` checks its `HashMap` for an existing `Circle` object with that `color`.\\n        2.  If found, the existing object is returned.\\n        3.  If not found, a new `Circle` object is created (with the specified `color`), stored in the `HashMap` for future use, and then returned to the client.\\n    *   The client then sets the `x`, `y`, and `radius` (extrinsic state) on the returned `Circle` object.\\n    *   This way, only a few `Circle` objects (one for each unique color) are created, while many circles with different locations and radii can be drawn.\\n*   **UML Diagram Elements:**\\n    *   **`Flyweight` class:** Contains the intrinsic (shareable) portion of the object's state. Extrinsic state is passed to its methods.\\n    *   **`FlyweightFactory`:** Manages a pool of existing flyweights. Clients request flyweights from the factory, passing intrinsic state. The factory either returns an existing matching flyweight or creates a new one.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Bridge Pattern\\n\\n*   **Intent:** Decouple an abstraction from its implementation so that the two can vary independently.\\n*   **Key Idea:**\\n    *   The abstract class is separated from the implementation class.\\n    *   A \\\"bridge interface\\\" is provided between them.\\n    *   This interface allows concrete class functionalities to be independent of the interface implementer class.\\n    *   Different kinds of classes (abstraction and implementation) can be modified structurally without affecting each other.\\n*   **Problem (Example before Bridge - Remote Control):**\\n    *   An `abstract Remote` class has general methods (`soundUp`, `soundDown`) and abstract methods (`onPressMiddle`, `onPressNine`) whose behavior depends on the device (TV, DVD) and brand (Sony, Toshiba).\\n    *   Direct inheritance leads to a complex hierarchy (e.g., `RemoteTV`, `RemoteDVD`, then `RemoteTVSony`, `RemoteTVToshiba`, etc.).\\n    *   Adding a new device type (e.g., `LCD`) or brand quickly multiplies the number of classes (`RemoteLCD`, `RemoteLCDSony`, `RemoteLCDToshiba`), causing significant code redundancy and a \\\"cartesian product\\\" issue.\\n*   **Solution:**\\n    *   Switches from inheritance to **object composition**.\\n    *   One of the dimensions (e.g., device type or brand) is extracted into a separate class hierarchy, defined by an interface.\\n    *   The original abstract class (`Remote`) holds a reference to an object of this new hierarchy (via its interface).\\n    *   **Example:**\\n        *   An `IDevice` interface is created with methods like `turnOn`, `turnOff`, `setChannel`, `pause`, etc.\\n        *   Concrete device classes (`TV`, `DVD`) implement `IDevice`.\\n        *   The `Remote` abstract class holds an `IDevice` instance.\\n        *   Specific `Remote` types (e.g., `SonyRemote`, `ToshibaRemote`) become refined abstractions that interact with the `IDevice` instance through its interface, independent of the concrete device type.\\n        *   This allows new remotes (abstractions) and new devices (implementations) to be added without affecting each other.\\n*   **UML Diagram Elements:**\\n    *   **`Abstraction`:** Defines the abstraction's interface and maintains a reference to an `Implementor` object.\\n    *   **`RefinedAbstraction`:** Extends `Abstraction` to provide concrete implementations.\\n    *   **`Implementor`:** Defines the interface for implementation classes. This is the \\\"bridge\\\" interface.\\n    *   **`ConcreteImplementorA`, `ConcreteImplementorB`:** Implement the `Implementor` interface.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Composite Design Pattern\\n\\n*   **Intent:**\\n    *   Lets you compose objects into tree structures.\\n    *   Allows working with these structures as if they were individual objects.\\n    *   Applies when objects in a structure need to be treated the same way.\\n*   **Key Concept:** Establishes a \\\"has-a\\\" relationship among objects where a composite object contains many other objects with common functionalities.\\n*   **Example (Graphic Application):**\\n    *   Users can draw shapes (circles, squares) and groups of shapes.\\n    *   Operations (move, resize, color) should apply to both individual shapes and entire groups uniformly.\\n    *   **Roles:**\\n        *   **Component:** The common interface (e.g., `Graphic`) that defines operations applicable to both simple and complex elements (e.g., `move`, `resize`, `color`).\\n        *   **Leaf:** Basic elements of the tree that don't have sub-elements (e.g., `Circle`, `Square`). They implement the `Component` interface.\\n        *   **Composite (Container):** Elements that have sub-elements (either `Leaf`s or other `Container`s). They also implement the `Component` interface.\\n        *   A `Container` works with all its sub-elements only via the `Component` interface. Upon receiving a request, it delegates the work to its sub-elements and aggregates results.\\n*   **Example (Employees):**\\n    *   An organization has employees. An employee can be a manager (who manages a set of employees), a developer, or a designer.\\n    *   All are essentially \\\"employees.\\\" Groupings of employees form departments, which form the organization.\\n    *   The pattern allows treating individual employees and departments (groups of employees) uniformly.\\n*   **UML Diagram Elements:**\\n    *   **`Component`:** Declares the interface for objects in the composition and for accessing and managing its child components.\\n    *   **`Leaf`:** Represents leaf objects in the composition. A leaf has no children.\\n    *   **`Composite`:** Defines behavior for components having children, and stores child components. It implements the `Component` interface and manages its children (add, remove, getChild).\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Proxy Design Pattern\\n\\n*   **Intent:** Provide a substitute or placeholder for another object.\\n*   **Function:** Controls access to the original object, allowing operations to be performed either before or after the request gets through to the original object.\\n*   **Types of Proxies:**\\n    *   **Protection Proxy:** Controls access to the original object based on permissions or restrictions (e.g., blocking access to certain websites).\\n    *   **Virtual Proxy:** Creates an expensive object only when it is actually needed (lazy initialization).\\n    *   *(Other types exist but are not detailed in the text.)*\\n*   **Problem (Protection Proxy Example):**\\n    *   Direct access to the `Internet` might allow users to connect to any host.\\n    *   Scenario: A university internet system needs to restrict access to certain websites.\\n*   **Solution (Protection Proxy):**\\n    *   Create a `ProxyInternet` class that acts as an intermediary.\\n    *   This `ProxyInternet` implements the same interface as the `RealInternet` (e.g., `Internet`).\\n    *   When a client requests to `connectTo(host)`:\\n        1.  The `ProxyInternet` first checks if the `host` is part of a restricted access list.\\n        2.  If the host is allowed, the proxy then delegates the request to the actual `RealInternet` object.\\n        3.  If the host is restricted, the proxy denies access without ever involving the `RealInternet`.\\n*   **UML Diagram Elements:**\\n    *   **`Service Interface`:** Declares the common interface that both the `Service` (real object) and `Proxy` must follow, allowing the proxy to mask itself as the service.\\n    *   **`Proxy` class:**\\n        *   Has a reference field that points to a `Service` object.\\n        *   Upon receiving a client request, it performs its own processing (e.g., access control, logging, caching, lazy initialization).\\n        *   After its processing, it passes the request to the `Service` object.\\n    *   **`Service` class:** The real object that provides the useful business logic.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Adapter Pattern\\n\\n*   **Intent:** Allows objects with incompatible interfaces to collaborate.\\n*   **Real-life Analogy:** A card reader acts as an adapter between a memory card (incompatible interface) and a laptop (expects a different interface).\\n*   **Problem (Stock Market Monitoring App):**\\n    *   An app downloads stock data in XML format.\\n    *   It needs to integrate a 3rd-party analytics library that *only* works with data in JSON format.\\n    *   **Bad Solution:** Modifying the library to accept XML is problematic (breaks existing code, source code might not be available).\\n*   **Good Solution:** Create an **Adapter**.\\n    *   **How it works:**\\n        1.  The adapter is a special object that converts the interface of one object so that another object can understand it.\\n        2.  The adapter gets an interface compatible with the *existing object* (the app that produces XML).\\n        3.  The existing object calls the adapter's methods.\\n        4.  Upon receiving a call, the adapter translates the incoming data (e.g., XML) into the format expected by the *second object* (the analytics library, expecting JSON).\\n        5.  Then, it passes the translated request to the appropriate methods of the wrapped analytics object.\\n*   **Example (Media Player):**\\n    *   `MediaPlayer` interface (default plays MP3). `AudioPlayer` implements `MediaPlayer`.\\n    *   `AdvancedMediaPlayer` interface (plays VLC, MP4). `VlcPlayer`, `Mp4Player` implement `AdvancedMediaPlayer`.\\n    *   **Goal:** Enable `AudioPlayer` to play other formats (VLC, MP4).\\n    *   **Solution:**\\n        1.  Create a `MediaAdapter` class that implements the `MediaPlayer` interface.\\n        2.  `MediaAdapter` internally holds a reference to an `AdvancedMediaPlayer` object.\\n        3.  When `AudioPlayer` (client) requests to play a format like \\\"vlc\\\" or \\\"mp4\\\" via `MediaAdapter`:\\n            *   The `MediaAdapter` determines which `AdvancedMediaPlayer` (e.g., `VlcPlayer` or `Mp4Player`) is needed.\\n            *   It then delegates the play request to the appropriate method of that `AdvancedMediaPlayer` object (`playVlc` or `playMp4`).\\n        4.  The `AudioPlayer` uses the `MediaAdapter` without needing to know the actual class that plays the desired format.\\n*   **UML Diagram Elements:**\\n    *   **`Target`:** The interface that the client expects to use (e.g., `MediaPlayer`).\\n    *   **`Client`:** Interacts with objects conforming to the `Target` interface (e.g., `AudioPlayer`).\\n    *   **`Adaptee`:** The existing class with an incompatible interface that needs to be adapted (e.g., `AdvancedMediaPlayer`).\\n    *   **`Adapter`:** Implements the `Target` interface and contains an instance of the `Adaptee`. It translates requests from the `Client` into a format understood by the `Adaptee`.\"}","timestamp":"2026-03-20 21:53:10"}
