{"file_size":4689970,"filename":"I3304-2024-2025-Part-1 (1).pdf","level":"info","message":"Input object for PDFDocument:","mime_type":"application/pdf","original_text":"\n\nI3304\nNetwork administration and \nsecurity\nAhmad Fadlallah\nAli RAAD\n1\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nReferenceTextbooks\n2\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nOutline\n•Introduction \n๏Introduction to the course\n๏Recall Network Basics (I2208)\n•Network Layer\n๏IP packet structure (Recall)\n๏Static Routing\n๏Dynamic Routing Algorithm\n๏Dynamic Routing Protocols\n๏NAT (Network Address Translation)\n•Transport Layer\n๏Function of the transport layer\n๏UDP Protocol\n๏TCP Protocol\n-Connection management\n-Flow control\n-Congestion control\n•Application Layer\nHTTP protocol\nFTP protocol\nMail protocols\nDNS\n•Introduction to Security\nSecurity services\nCryptography\nDigital Signature\nPrinciple of network security \nprotocols\n3\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nWhat’s the Internet: “nuts and bolts”view\n•Billions of connected computing \ndevices: \n๏hosts = end systems \n๏running network apps\n•Communication links\n๏fiber, copper, radio, satellite\n๏transmission rate: bandwidth\n•Packet switches: forward packets \n(chunks of data)\n๏Routers and switches\nWired links\nwireless\nlinks\nrouter\nsmartphone\nPC\nserver\nWireless laptop\nmobile network\nglobal ISP\nregional ISP\nhome \nnetwork\ninstitutional\nnetwork\n4\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\n“Fun” Internet-connected devices\nIP picture frame\nhttp://www.ceiva.com/\nWeb-enabled  toaster +\nweather forecaster\nInternet phones\nInternet \nrefrigerator\nSlingbox:  watch,\ncontrol cable TV remotely\nTweet-a-watt: \nmonitor energy  use\nsensorized,\nbed\nmattress\n5\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nWhat’s the Internet: “nuts and bolts” view\n•Internet: “network of networks”\n๏Interconnected ISPs\n6\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nWhat’s the Internet: “nuts and bolts” view\n•Protocolscontrol sending, \nreceiving of messages\n๏e.g., TCP, IP, HTTP, Skype,  \n802.11\n•Internet  standards\n๏RFC: Request for comments\n๏IETF: Internet Engineering Task \nForce\nmobile network\nglobal ISP\nregional ISP\nhome \nnetwork\ninstitutional\nnetwork\n7\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nWhat’s the Internet: a service view\n•Infrastructure that provides \nservices to applications:\n๏Web, VoIP, email, games, e-\ncommerce, social nets, ...\n•Provides programming \ninterface to apps\n๏hooks that allow sending \nand receiving  app programs \nto “connect”to Internet\n๏Provides service options, \nanalogous to postal service\nmobile network\nglobal ISP\nregional ISP\nhome \nnetwork\ninstitutional\nnetwork\n8\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nWhat’s a protocol?\n•“what’s the time?”\n•“I have a question”\n•introductions\n•Machines rather than \nhumans\n•All communication activity \nin Internet governed by \nprotocols\nHuman protocols\nNetwork protocols\n... specific messages sent\n... specific actions taken when messages \nreceived, or other events\nprotocolsdefine format, orderof \nmessages sent and received\namong network entities, and \nactions takenon message \ntransmission, receipt\n9\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nWhat’s a protocol?\nQ:other human protocols? \n10\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nWhy layering?\nDealing with complex systems:\n•Explicit structure allows identification, relationship of \ncomplex system’s pieces\n•Modularizationeases maintenance, updating of \nsystem\n๏Change of implementation of layer’s service \ntransparent to rest of system\n11\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nAnalogy\nIk vind \nkonijnen \nleuk\nL: Ducth\nFax:#\nIk vind \nkonijnen \nleuk\nL: Dutch\nI like \nrabbits\nMessage\nInformation \nfor the \nremote \ntranslator\nInformation \nfor the \nremote \nsecretary\nIk vind \nkonijnen \nleuk\nL: Ducth\nFax:#\nIk vind \nkonijnen \nleuk\nL: Ducth\nJ’aime \nbien les \nlapins\nArabic & English\nChinese & French\nProfessor B\nTranslator\nSecretary\nuse fax\nuse Dutch\nSecretary\nTranslator\nProfessor A\n12\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nReference Models\n•There are two competing models for how the \nsoftware is layered: the OSIand the TCPmodels.  \n•OSI (Open Systems Interconnection)\n๏Developed by ISO (International Standards \nOrganization)\n๏7 layers\n•TCP (Transfer Control Protocol)\n๏Used in the ARPANET and in the Internet.  \n๏Common mechanism that is surpassing the OSI Model.  \n๏5 layers\n13\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nReference Models\n14\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nInternet Protocol Stack\n•Application: supporting network applications\n๏FTP, SMTP, HTTP\n•Transport: process-process data transfer\n๏TCP, UDP\n•Network: routing of datagrams from source \nto destination\n๏IP, routing protocols\n•Link: data transfer between neighboring  \nnetwork elements\n๏Ethernet, 802.111 (WiFi), PPP\n•Physical: bits “on the wire”\n15\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nISO/OSI reference model\n•Presentation: allow applications to \ninterpret meaning of data, e.g., \nencryption, compression, machine-\nspecific conventions\n•Session: synchronization, check-\npointing, recovery of data exchange\n•Internet stack “missing”these \nlayers!\n๏these services, if needed, must be \nimplemented in application\n๏needed?\n16\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nsource\napplication\ntransport\nnetwork\nlink\nphysical\nH\nt\nH\nn\nM\nsegment\nH\nt\ndatagram\ndestination\napplication\ntransport\nnetwork\nlink\nphysical\nH\nt\nH\nn\nH\nl\nM\nH\nt\nH\nn\nM\nH\nt\nM\nM\nnetwork\nlink\nphysical\nlink\nphysical\nH\nt\nH\nn\nH\nl\nM\nH\nt\nH\nn\nM\nH\nt\nH\nn\nM\nH\nt\nH\nn\nH\nl\nM\nrouter\nswitch\nEncapsulation\nmessage\nM\nH\nt\nM\nH\nn\nframe\n17\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nReference Models\n•Headers, Data, and Trailers\n•Encapsulation\n18\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nTCP/IP MODEL\n19\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nInternet Layers\n•Internet Model\n๏Dominant model in data communications and networking \n๏5 ordered layers; often referred to as TCP/IP protocol suite \n20\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nInternet Layers\n21\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nPeer-to-Peer Processes\n22\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nAn exchange using the Internet model\n23\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nPhysical Layer\n•Physical characteristics of interfaces and media \n๏Representation of bits without interpretation \n๏Data rate: number of bits per second \n๏Synchronization of bits \n24\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nThe physical layer is responsible  for \ntransmitting  individual bits from one \nnode to the next.\nNote:\n25\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nTransmission Media\n26\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nData link Layer\nData Link Layer Responsibilities\n•Defines framesinto manageable data units \n๏Physical addressing \n๏Flow control \n๏Error control \n๏Access control \n27\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nThe data link layer is responsible for \ntransmitting  frames from \none node to the next.\nNote:\n28\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nNode-to-Node delivery\n29\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\n802.3 MAC frame\n•Preamble–7 bytesof alternating 0s and 1s to alert the receiver and allow it to \nsynchronize\n•Start Frame Delimiter (SFD) –1 byte –10101011 signals the beginning of a frame, \nlast chance for synchronization –last 2 bits are 11\n•Destination address (DA) –6 bytes –contains the physical address of the destination \nstation or stations\n•Source address (SA) –6 bytes –contains the physical address of the sender\n•Length/type–if less than 1518 then it defines the length of the data field –if more \nthan 1536 then it defines the type of the PDU packet that is encapsulated\n•Data–data encapsulated from upper-layer protocols : 46 ~ 1500 bytes\n•CRC–CRC-32\n30\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nNetwork layer\n•Network Layer Responsibilities\n๏Source-to-destination delivery, possibly across multiple \nnetworks \n๏Logical addressing \n๏Routing\n31\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nThe network layer is responsible  for \nthe delivery of packets from  the \noriginal source to the \nfinal destination.\nNote:\n32\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSource-to-Destination delivery\n33\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nPosition of IPv4 in TCP/IP protocol suite\nIPv4\n34\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIPv4\n•Best-effort delivery\n๏IPv4 is an unreliableand connectionlessdatagram protocol\n๏Abest-effort delivery service.\n๏best-effort IPv4 provides no error control or flow control(except for \nerror detection on the header).\n•Connectionless protocol\n๏Each datagram is handled independently\n๏Datagrams sent by the source to the same destination could\n-Arrive out of order\n-be lost or corrupted during transmission.\n๏IPv4 relies on a high-level protocol to take of all these problem.\n35\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIPv4 Datagrams\n•Packets in the IPv4 layer are called Datagrams.\n36\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nver\nlength\n32 bits\ndata \n(variable  length,\ntypically a TCP \nor UDP segment)\n16-bit identifier\nInternet\nchecksum\ntime to\nlive\n32 bit source IP address\nIP protocol version number\nheader length (bytes)\nmax number\nremaining hops\n(decremented at \neach router)\nfor\nfragmentation/\nreassembly\ntotal datagram\nlength (bytes)\nupper layer protocol\nto deliver payload to\nhead.\nlen\ntype of\nservice\n“type” of data \nflgs\nfragment\noffset\nupper\nlayer\n32 bit destination IP address\nOptions (if any)\nE.g. timestamp,\nrecord route\ntaken, specify\nlist of routers \nto visit.\nhow much overhead \nwith TCP?\n20 bytes of TCP\n20 bytes of IP\n= 40 bytes + app \nlayer overhead\nIP datagram format\n37\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIPv4 Datagram (cont’d)\n•A datagram is a variable-length packet consisting of a \nheaderand data.\n•Header\n๏Length : 20 –60 bytes\n๏Contains information essential to routing and delivery.\n•Version (VER) : It defines the Version of IPv4. it is 4.\n•Header Length (HLEN) : Defining the total length of \nthe datagram header in 4-byte words.\n38\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIPv4 Datagram (cont’d)\n•Protocol \n๏Defining the higher level protocol that uses the \nservices of the IP layer\n-TCP, UDP, ICMP, and IGMP\n-Multiplexing data from different higher level protocols\nValueProtocol\n1ICMP\n2IGMP\n6TCP\n8EGP\n17UDP\n89OSPF\n39\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIPv6 Datagram\n40\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIPv6 Datagram\n41\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSubnet with VLSM\n192.168.10.0/24\n42\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nRegular Subnet\n7subnets; The largest subnet needs 60hosts \nIf 3bits for subnet (8 subnets) 5bits for host (32 hosts)\nIf 6bits for host (64 hosts) 2bits for subnet (4 subnets)\n192.168.10.0/24\n43\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nExercise\n•A multinational  company  wishes to have an IPv4 addressing  plan for the new \nbranch it has created  in Beirut. The Beirut branch has 5 departments  as follows:\n๏Human Resources  Management  (HRM) with 12 staff;\n๏Engineering  (ENG) with 23 staff ;\n๏Information  system (IS) with 8 staff;\n๏Marketing  and sales (MS) with 50 staff;\n๏Accounting and auditing  (AA) with 15 staff.\n•In total,  the Beirut branch has 108 staff. The network  allocated  for the branch is \n192.168.100.0/24. While taking into account the evolution  of the branch, divide  the \nnetwork  into several  sub-networks  according  to the departments.\n•You should fill the below  table  for each department/  sub-network.  Briefly explain \nthe different  choices.\n44\nDept. \nName\nNetwork \naddress\nPrefix \nlength\nUsableIP address  range\n(First –Last)\nBroadcast address\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nForwarding -Routing\n223.1.1.1\n223.1.1.3\n223.1.1.4\n223.1.2.2\n223.1.2.1\n223.1.2.6\n223.1.3.2\n223.1.3.1\n223.1.3.27\n223.1.1.2\n223.1.7.0\n223.1.7.1\n223.1.8.0223.1.8.1\n223.1.9.1\n223.1.9.2\nDestination \nNetwork\nNext hopInterface\n0.0.0.0223.1.1.3FastEthernet\nFastEthernet\nDestination \nNetwork\nNext hopInterface\n223.1.3.0/24223.1.7.1FastEthernet0/0\n223.1.2.0/24223.1.9.1FastEthernet0/1\n45\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIntroduction to Routing\nStatic Routing\n•Static Route Characteristics:\n๏Must be configured manually\n๏Must be adjusted manually by \nthe administrator when there \nis a change in the topology\n๏Good for small non-redundant \nnetworks\n๏Often used in conjunction \nwith a dynamic routing \nprotocolfor configuring a \ndefault route\n46\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIntroduction to Routing\nDynamic Routing\n•Dynamic Routes Automatically:\n๏Discover remote networks\n๏Maintain up-to-date \ninformation\n๏Choose the best path to the \ndestination\n๏Find new best paths when \nthere is a topology change\n๏Dynamic routing can also \nshare static default routes \nwith the other routers.\n47\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nAddress Resolution -ARP\n48\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nMAC addresses and ARP\n•IP address: \n๏“Low” Network-layer address for interface\n๏Used for layer 3 (network layer) forwarding\n•MAC (or LAN or physical or Ethernet) address: \n๏Function: used “locally” to get frame from one interface to \nanother physically-connected interface (same network, in \nIP-addressing sense)\n๏48 bit MAC address (for most LANs) burned in NIC ROM, \nalso sometimes software settable\n๏e.g.: 1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD\nhexadecimal (base 16) notation\n(each “numeral” represents 4 bits)\n49\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nLAN addresses and ARP\neach adapter on LAN has unique LANaddress\nadapter\n1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD\n58-23-D7-FA-20-B0\n0C-C4-11-6F-E3-98\n71-65-F7-2B-08-53\nLAN\n(wired or\nwireless)\n50\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nLAN addresses (more)\n•MAC address allocation administered by IEEE\n•Manufacturer buys portion of MAC address space (to \nassure uniqueness)\n•Analogy:\n๏MAC address: like Social Security Number\n๏IP address: like postal address\n•MAC flat address  ➜portability \n๏can move LAN card from one LAN to another\n•IP hierarchical address not portable\n๏address depends on IP subnet to which node is attached\n51\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nARP: Address Resolution Protocol\n•ARP table: each IP node (host, \nrouter) on LAN has a ARP table\n–IP/MAC address mappings for some \nLAN nodes:\n•< IP address; MAC address; TTL>\n–TTL (Time To Live): time after which \naddress mapping will be forgotten \n(typically 20 min)\nQuestion:how to determine\ninterface’s MAC address, \nknowing its IP address?\n1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD\n58-23-D7-FA-20-B0\n0C-C4-11-6F-E3-98\n71-65-F7-2B-08-53\nLAN\n137.196.7.23\n137.196.7.78\n137.196.7.14\n137.196.7.88\nIP addressMAC addressTTL\n137.196.7.1458-23-D7-FA-20-B0\n20\n52\nUse arpcommand to display ARP table on Windows or Linux\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nARP protocol: same LAN\n1.A wants to send datagram to B\n๏B’s MAC address not in A’s ARP table.\n2.A broadcasts ARP query packet, containing B's IP address \n๏Destination MAC address = FF-FF-FF-FF-FF-FF\n๏All nodes on LAN receive ARP query \n3.B receives ARP packet, replies to A with its (B's) MAC address\n๏frame sent to A’s MAC address (unicast)\n4.A caches (saves) IP-to-MAC address pair in its ARP table until \ninformation becomes old (times out) \n๏soft state: information that times out (goes away) unless refreshed\n•ARP is “plug-and-play”:\n๏Nodes create their ARP tables without intervention from net \nadministrator\n53\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nARP operation\n54\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nHardware Type –\nEthernet is type 1\nProtocol Type-\nIPv4=x0800\nHardware Length: \nlength of Ethernet \nAddress (6)\nProtocol Length: \nlength of IPv4 \naddress (4)\nARP packet\n55\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nThe ARP packet is encapsulated within an Ethernet packet.\nNote: Type field for Ethernet is x0806\nEncapsulation of ARP packet\n56\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nFour cases using ARP\n57\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nARP Example \n58\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nARP –A each step\nARP: Who has this IP?\nARP: Who has this IP?\nARP: Who has this IP?\n59\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nDefault Gateways\n•Devices need the following information \nfor network access: IP address, subnet \nmask, and default gateway.\n•When a host sends a packet to a device \nthat is on the same IP network, the packet \nis forwarded out the host interface to the \ndestination device. The router does not \nneed to get involved.\n•When a host sends a packet to a device on \na different IP network, the packet is \nforwarded to the default gateway because \nthe host device cannot communicate with \ndevices outside of the local network.\n•The default gateway is the device that \nroutes traffic from the local network to \ndevices on remote networks, such as \ndevices on the Internet.\nRouters are also usually configured with their own default gateway.\n60\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\n•walkthrough: send datagram from A to B via R\n–Focus on addressing –at IP (datagram) and MAC layer \n(frame)\n–Assume A knows B’s IP address\n–Assume A knows IP address of first hop router, R (how?)\n–Assume A knows R’s MAC address (how?)\nR\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\n222.222.222.220\n111.111.111.110\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\n111.111.111.112\n111.111.111.111\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nA\n222.222.222.222\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\n222.222.222.221\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\nB\n61\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\n•A creates IP datagram with IP source A, destination B \n•A creates link-layer frame with R's MAC address as \ndestination address, frame contains A-to-B IP datagram\nR\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\n222.222.222.220\n111.111.111.110\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\n111.111.111.112\n111.111.111.111\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nA\n222.222.222.222\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\n222.222.222.221\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\nB\nIP\nEth\nPhy\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\nMAC src: 74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nMAC dest: E6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\n62\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nR\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\n222.222.222.220\n111.111.111.110\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\n111.111.111.112\n111.111.111.111\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nA\n222.222.222.222\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\n222.222.222.221\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\nB\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\n•Frame sent from A to R\n•Frame received at R, datagram removed, passed \nup to IP\nIP\nEth\nPhy\nIP\nEth\nPhy\nMAC src: 74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nMAC dest: E6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\n63\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nR\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\n222.222.222.220\n111.111.111.110\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\n111.111.111.112\n111.111.111.111\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nA\n222.222.222.222\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\n222.222.222.221\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\nB\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\n•R forwards datagram with IP source A, destination B \n•R creates link-layer frame with B's MAC address as \ndestination address, frame contains A-to-B IP \ndatagram\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\nMAC src: 1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\nMAC dest: 49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\nIP\nEth\nPhy\nIP\nEth\nPhy\n64\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nR\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\n222.222.222.220\n111.111.111.110\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\n111.111.111.112\n111.111.111.111\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nA\n222.222.222.222\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\n222.222.222.221\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\nB\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\n•R forwards datagram with IP source A, destination B \n•R creates link-layer frame with B's MAC address as \ndestination address, frame contains A-to-B IP \ndatagram\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\nMAC src: 1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\nMAC dest: 49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\nIP\nEth\nPhy\nIP\nEth\nPhy\n65\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nR\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\n222.222.222.220\n111.111.111.110\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\n111.111.111.112\n111.111.111.111\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\nA\n222.222.222.222\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\n222.222.222.221\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\nB\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\n•R forwards datagram with IP source A, destination B \n•R creates link-layer frame with B's MAC address as dest, frame \ncontains A-to-B IP datagram\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\nMAC src: 1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\nMAC dest: 49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\nIP\nEth\nPhy\n* Check out the online interactive exercises for more \nexamples:  http://gaia.cs.umass.edu/kurose_ross/interactive/\n66\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nIntroduction to Routing\nRouter Packet Forwarding Decision\n•What happens when the router receives the frame \nfrom the host device?\n67\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \nSend a Packet\n•PC1 must determine if the destination IPv4 address is on the same network. \n•If it is on the same network, PC1 will obtain the destination MAC address from its ARP cache or use an \nARP request.\n•Because the destination network is on a different network, PC1 forwards the packet to its default \ngateway.\n68\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \nSend a Packet\n•To determine the MAC address of the default gateway, PC1 checks its ARP table for \nthe IPv4 address of the default gateway and its corresponding MAC address. \n๏An ARP request is sent if it is not found.\n•When PC1 has the MAC address of Router R1, it can forward the packet. \n69\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \nForward to the Next Hop\n•R1 examines the destination MAC address which matches the MAC address \nof the receiving interface and copies the frame into its buffer.\n•R1 identifies the Ethernet Type field as 0x800 which indicates that the \nEthernet frame contains an IPv4 packet in the data portion of the frame.\n70\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \nForward to the Next Hop\n•R1 de-encapsulates the Ethernet frame.\n•Because the destination IPv4 address of the packet, 192.168.4.10,   does not match \nany of the directly connected networks on R1, R1 searches the routing table for a \ncorresponding route.\n๏R1’s Routing Table has a route for the 192.168.4.0/24 network.\n71\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \nForward to the Next Hop\n•The routethat R1 finds to the 192.168.4.0/24 network has a next-hopaddressof \n192.168.2.2 and an exit interface of FastEthernet0/1.\n•This will require that the IPv4 packet be encapsulated in a new Ethernet frame with \nthe destination MAC address of the IPv4 address of the next-hop router, 192.168.2.2\n72\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \nForward to the Next Hop\n•Because the exit interface is on an Ethernet network, R1 must resolve the \nnext-hop IPv4 address with a destination MAC address using ARP, assuming \nit is not in its ARP cache.\n•When R1 has the MAC address for the next-hop, the Ethernet frame is \nforwarded out of the FastEthernet0/1 interface of R1.\n73\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\nPacket Routing\n•R2 examines the destination MAC address\n๏Because it matches the MAC address of its receiving interface, R2 copies the \nframe into its buffer.\n•R2 determines that that frame contains an IPv4 packet in the data portion \nof the frame.\n74\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\nPacket Routing\n•R2 de-encapsulates the Ethernet frame.\n•Because the destination IP address is on a different network, \nthe routing table is searched to find a corresponding route for \nthe destination IPv4 address. \n75\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\nPacket Routing\n•The routing table of R2 has a routeto the 192.168.4.0/24 network \nwith a next-hop IPv4 address of 192.168.3.2 and an exit interface of \nSerial 0/0/0.   \n•Because the exit interface is not Ethernet, R2 does not have to \nresolve the next-hop IP-v4 address with a destination MAC address.\n76\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\nPacket Routing\n•The IPv4 packet is encapsulatedinto a new data link frame used by \nthe exit interface and sent out the Serial 0/0/0 exit interface.\n•Because there are no MAC addresses on serial interfaces, R2 sets the \ndata link destination address to an equivalent of a broadcast.\n77\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\nReach the Destination\n•R3 copies the data link PPP frame into its buffer.\n•R3 de-encapsulatesthe data link PPP frame.\n•R3 searches the routing table for the destination IPv4 address of the \npacket.\n78\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\nReach the Destination\n•Because the destination network is on R3’s directly connected network, the \npacket can be sent directly and does not need to be sent to another router.\n•Because the exit interface is a directly connected Ethernet network, R3 \nmust resolve the destination IPv4 address of the packet with a destination \nMAC address by either finding it in its ARP cache or send out an ARP \nrequest.\n79\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nInternet Control Message Protocol \n•The Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) \n•Specified in [RFC 792], \n•Used by hosts and routers to communicate network-\nlayer information to each other. \n•Most typical use of ICMP is for error reporting\n•Often considered part of IP, but architecturally it lies \njust above IP, as ICMP messages are carried inside IP \ndatagrams. \n๏ICMP messages are carried as IP payload\n80\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nICMP Type and Code \nTypeCode Description\n00echo reply (ping)\n30destination network unreachable\n31destination host unreachable\n32destination protocol unreachable\n33destination port unreachable\n36destination network unknown\n37destination host unknown\n80echo request (ping)\n90route advertisement\n100router discovery\n110TTL expired\n120bad IP header\n81\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nTrace Route –ICMP\n•Source sends series of UDP segments (or ICMP Echo request) to destination host\n๏First has TTL =1\n๏Second has TTL=2, etc.\n๏Unlikely port number\n•When n\nth\ndatagram arrives to n\nth\nrouter:\n๏Router discards datagram\n๏Sends to source an ICMP message (type 11, code 0)\n๏Datagram includes router IP address. Traceroute does DNS lookup to find name of router \n(if any)\n•When ICMP message arrives, source calculates RTT\n•Traceroute repeat the process 3 times (To get average RTT)\n•Stopping criterion\n๏UDP segment eventually arrives at destination host\n๏Destination returns ICMP “port unreachable” packet (type 3, code 3)\n82\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nTrace Route –ICMP\n83\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nTransport layer\nThe transport layer is responsible for delivering segments from a source process to a \nfinal destination process.\n84\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nTransport layer\n•Transport Layer Responsibilities\n๏Process-to-process delivery of entire message \n๏Port addressing \n๏Segmentation and reassembly \n๏Connection control: connectionless or connection-oriented \n๏End-to-end flow control \n๏End-to-end error control \n85\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nApplication Layer\n•The application layer is responsible for providing \nservices to the user.\n86\n\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\nThanks !\n87","storage_path":"uploads\\1774037965141_I3304_2024_2025_Part_1__1_.pdf","summary":"Here is a detailed summary of the provided text, organized into logical bullet points:\n\n**I3304: Network Administration and Security - Course Overview**\n*   **Course Title:** I3304 - Network Administration and Security (2023-2024)\n*   **Instructors:** Ahmad Fadlallah, Ali RAAD\n*   **Course Outline:**\n    *   **Introduction:** Course introduction, recall Network Basics (I2208).\n    *   **Network Layer:** IP packet structure (recall), Static Routing, Dynamic Routing Algorithms/Protocols, NAT (Network Address Translation).\n    *   **Transport Layer:** Function of the transport layer, UDP Protocol, TCP Protocol (Connection management, Flow control, Congestion control).\n    *   **Application Layer:** HTTP protocol, FTP protocol, Mail protocols, DNS.\n    *   **Introduction to Security:** Security services, Cryptography, Digital Signature, Principle of network security protocols.\n\n**What is the Internet?**\n*   **\"Nuts and Bolts\" View:**\n    *   Billions of connected computing devices (hosts/end systems) running network applications.\n    *   Communication links (fiber, copper, radio, satellite) with transmission rate defined by bandwidth.\n    *   Packet switches (routers and switches) forward packets (chunks of data).\n    *   Described as a \"network of networks\" interconnected by ISPs (Internet Service Providers).\n    *   Communication activity is governed by **protocols** (e.g., TCP, IP, HTTP, 802.11).\n    *   **Internet Standards:** Defined by RFC (Request for Comments) and IETF (Internet Engineering Task Force).\n*   **\"Service View\":**\n    *   An infrastructure providing services to applications (Web, VoIP, email, games, e-commerce, social networks).\n    *   Offers a programming interface (hooks) for applications to \"connect\" and send/receive data.\n    *   Provides service options, analogous to a postal service.\n\n**Protocols and Layering**\n*   **What's a Protocol?**\n    *   Defines the format, order of messages sent and received among network entities.\n    *   Specifies actions taken on message transmission or receipt.\n    *   Governs all communication activity in the Internet.\n    *   Distinction: Human protocols (e.g., introductions) vs. Network protocols (machine-to-machine).\n*   **Why Layering?**\n    *   **Explicit structure:** Allows identification and relationship of complex system pieces.\n    *   **Modularization:** Eases maintenance and updating.\n    *   **Transparency:** Changes in one layer's implementation are transparent to the rest of the system.\n\n**Network Reference Models**\n*   **Two Competing Models:**\n    *   **OSI (Open Systems Interconnection) Model:**\n        *   Developed by ISO (International Standards Organization).\n        *   Comprises 7 layers.\n    *   **TCP/IP (Transmission Control Protocol/Internet Protocol) Model:**\n        *   Used in ARPANET and the Internet; a common, dominant mechanism.\n        *   Comprises 5 layers.\n*   **Internet Protocol Stack (TCP/IP 5-Layer Model):**\n    *   **Application Layer:** Supports network applications (e.g., FTP, SMTP, HTTP).\n    *   **Transport Layer:** Process-to-process data transfer (e.g., TCP, UDP).\n    *   **Network Layer:** Routing of datagrams from source to destination (e.g., IP, routing protocols).\n    *   **Link Layer:** Data transfer between neighboring network elements (e.g., Ethernet, 802.11/WiFi, PPP).\n    *   **Physical Layer:** Deals with bits \"on the wire.\"\n*   **OSI Layers \"Missing\" in Internet Stack:**\n    *   **Presentation Layer:** Allows applications to interpret data meaning (e.g., encryption, compression, machine-specific conventions).\n    *   **Session Layer:** Handles synchronization, checkpointing, and recovery of data exchange.\n    *   In the Internet stack, these services, if needed, must be implemented within the application layer.\n\n**Encapsulation**\n*   **Process:** As data moves down the protocol stack, each layer adds its own header (and sometimes a trailer) to the data received from the layer above.\n*   **Headers, Data, and Trailers:** A message (M) from the application layer becomes a segment with a transport header (Ht), then a datagram with a network header (Hn), and finally a frame with a link header (Hl) and trailer (Hl).\n*   **Peer-to-Peer Processes:** Each layer on the sending host logically communicates with its corresponding layer on the receiving host.\n\n**Detailed Layer Responsibilities**\n*   **Physical Layer:**\n    *   **Responsibility:** Transmitting individual bits from one node to the next.\n    *   **Characteristics:** Defines physical interfaces and media, representation of bits (without interpretation), data rate (bits per second), synchronization of bits.\n*   **Data Link Layer:**\n    *   **Responsibility:** Transmitting frames from one node to the next.\n    *   **Key Responsibilities:** Defines frames, physical addressing (MAC addresses), flow control, error control, access control.\n    *   **802.3 MAC Frame Structure (Ethernet):**\n        *   **Preamble (7 bytes):** Alternating 0s and 1s for receiver synchronization.\n        *   **Start Frame Delimiter (SFD) (1 byte):** `10101011` signals frame start, last chance for synchronization.\n        *   **Destination Address (DA) (6 bytes):** Physical address of destination station(s).\n        *   **Source Address (SA) (6 bytes):** Physical address of the sender.\n        *   **Length/Type:** If < 1518, defines data field length; if > 1536, defines type of encapsulated PDU packet.\n        *   **Data (46-1500 bytes):** Encapsulated upper-layer protocol data.\n        *   **CRC (Cyclic Redundancy Check):** CRC-32 for error detection.\n*   **Network Layer:**\n    *   **Responsibility:** Delivery of packets from the original source to the final destination (possibly across multiple networks).\n    *   **Key Responsibilities:** Logical addressing (IP addresses), Routing.\n\n**IPv4 Protocol**\n*   **Position:** Sits within the Network Layer of the TCP/IP protocol suite.\n*   **Characteristics:**\n    *   **Best-effort delivery:** Unreliable and connectionless datagram protocol.\n    *   Provides no error control or flow control (except for error detection on the header).\n    *   **Connectionless:** Each datagram is handled independently; datagrams from the same source to destination may arrive out of order, be lost, or corrupted. Relies on higher-level protocols for reliability.\n*   **IPv4 Datagrams:**\n    *   Packets at the IPv4 layer are called datagrams.\n    *   Variable-length packet consisting of a header and data.\n    *   **Header:** Length is 20-60 bytes, contains information essential for routing and delivery.\n    *   **Key Header Fields:**\n        *   **Version (VER):** Defines the IPv4 version (always 4).\n        *   **Header Length (HLEN):** Total length of the datagram header in 4-byte words.\n        *   **Type of Service:** (Differentiated Services Code Point)\n        *   **Total Length:** Total length of the datagram (header + data) in bytes.\n        *   **Identifier, Flags, Fragment Offset:** Used for fragmentation and reassembly.\n        *   **Time to Live (TTL):** Maximum number of hops remaining (decremented at each router); prevents infinite loops.\n        *   **Protocol:** Defines the higher-level protocol using IP services (e.g., 1=ICMP, 6=TCP, 17=UDP, 89=OSPF).\n        *   **Header Checksum:** For error detection on the header.\n        *   **Source IP Address (32 bits):** IP address of the sender.\n        *   **Destination IP Address (32 bits):** IP address of the final recipient.\n        *   **Options (if any):** E.g., timestamp, record route, specify routers.\n    *   **Overhead:** 20 bytes for IP header + 20 bytes for TCP header = 40 bytes minimum.\n*   **IPv6 Datagram:** Mentioned with diagrams as the next generation IP protocol.\n*   **Subnetting with VLSM:** A practical application for creating an IPv4 addressing plan for a network with varying host requirements in different departments.\n\n**Routing**\n*   **Forwarding vs. Routing:** Forwarding is the process of moving a packet from a router’s input link to the appropriate output link; routing is the process of determining the end-to-end path.\n*   **Static Routing:**\n    *   **Characteristics:** Must be configured manually; requires manual adjustment by administrator for topology changes; good for small, non-redundant networks; often used with dynamic routing for configuring a default route.\n*   **Dynamic Routing:**\n    *   **Characteristics:** Automatically discovers remote networks; maintains up-to-date information; chooses the best path to the destination; finds new best paths when topology changes; can share static default routes with other routers.\n\n**Address Resolution Protocol (ARP)**\n*   **Purpose:** Resolves an IP address to a corresponding MAC (Media Access Control) address.\n*   **MAC Address (LAN / Physical / Ethernet Address):**\n    *   Function: Used locally to get a frame from one interface to another physically-connected interface on the same network.\n    *   Format: 48-bit hexadecimal address (e.g., 1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD), burned into NIC ROM (sometimes software settable).\n    *   Administered by IEEE to ensure uniqueness (manufacturers buy portions of the address space).\n    *   Analogy: MAC address is like a Social Security Number (flat, portable); IP address is like a postal address (hierarchical, depends on subnet).\n*   **ARP Table:**\n    *   Each IP node (host, router) on a LAN maintains an ARP table.\n    *   Stores IP/MAC address mappings for known LAN nodes.\n    *   Includes: IP address, MAC address, and TTL (Time To Live), which is the time after which the mapping will be forgotten (typically 20 min).\n*   **ARP Protocol (Same LAN Scenario):**\n    1.  Host A wants to send a datagram to Host B, but B's MAC address is not in A's ARP table.\n    2.  A broadcasts an ARP query packet containing B's IP address. The destination MAC address is `FF-FF-FF-FF-FF-FF` (broadcast).\n    3.  All nodes on the LAN receive the ARP query.\n    4.  B receives the query and replies to A with its (B's) MAC address (unicast).\n    5.  A caches the IP-to-MAC address pair in its ARP table until it times out (\"soft state\").\n    *   **\"Plug-and-play\":** Nodes create their ARP tables without administrator intervention.\n*   **ARP Packet Structure:** Includes Hardware Type (e.g., Ethernet=1), Protocol Type (e.g., IPv4=x0800), Hardware Length (6 for Ethernet), Protocol Length (4 for IPv4), Operation (request/reply), Sender MAC/IP, Target MAC/IP.\n*   **Encapsulation:** An ARP packet is encapsulated within an Ethernet frame (Ethernet Type field is `x0806`).\n\n**Packet Forwarding and Routing Decisions**\n*   **Default Gateways:**\n    *   Devices need IP address, subnet mask, and default gateway for network access.\n    *   If the destination is on the same IP network, the packet is forwarded directly to the destination.\n    *   If the destination is on a different IP network, the packet is forwarded to the default gateway (a router).\n    *   The default gateway routes traffic between the local network and remote networks (e.g., the Internet).\n*   **Routing to Another LAN (Walkthrough A -> R -> B):**\n    1.  Host A creates an IP datagram (Source IP = A, Destination IP = B).\n    2.  A creates a link-layer frame (Source MAC = A's MAC, Destination MAC = R's MAC) containing the IP datagram. (R's MAC obtained via ARP if not known).\n    3.  The frame is sent from A to Router R.\n    4.  R receives the frame, removes the IP datagram, and passes it to its IP layer.\n    5.  R determines the next hop for the destination B from its routing table.\n    6.  R creates a *new* link-layer frame (Source MAC = R's MAC for the *next* interface, Destination MAC = B's MAC) containing the *original* IP datagram. (B's MAC obtained via ARP if not known).\n    7.  The new frame is sent from R to B.\n*   **Router Packet Forwarding Decision (Multi-hop Example PC1 -> R1 -> R2 -> R3 -> PC4):**\n    *   **Host to Gateway:** PC1 determines destination (PC4) is remote, sends packet to its default gateway (R1) using R1's MAC address (resolved via ARP).\n    *   **Gateway Processing (R1):** R1 examines destination MAC (matches its interface), de-encapsulates the Ethernet frame to get the IPv4 packet. R1 checks its routing table for PC4's IP. Finds a route to a next-hop (R2) via an exit interface. Re-encapsulates the IPv4 packet into a new Ethernet frame for R2 using R2's MAC address (resolved via ARP).\n    *   **Intermediate Router Processing (R2):** R2 receives the frame, de-encapsulates. Checks its routing table for PC4's IP. Finds a route to next-hop (R3) via a Serial interface. Re-encapsulates the IPv4 packet into a new data link frame for the serial link (no MAC addresses on serial, often broadcast equivalent).\n    *   **Final Router to Destination (R3):** R3 receives the serial frame, de-encapsulates. Checks its routing table for PC4's IP. Finds PC4 is on a directly connected network. Resolves PC4's IP to MAC address via ARP (if not cached). Re-encapsulates the IPv4 packet into a final Ethernet frame for PC4.\n\n**Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP)**\n*   **Purpose:** Used by hosts and routers to communicate network-layer information to each other.\n*   **Primary Use:** Error reporting.\n*   **Architectural Position:** Architecturally lies just above IP; ICMP messages are carried as IP payload within IP datagrams.\n*   **ICMP Type and Code Examples:**\n    *   `Type 0, Code 0`: Echo reply (ping response).\n    *   `Type 3, Code 0-7`: Destination unreachable (network, host, protocol, port unreachable, etc.).\n    *   `Type 8, Code 0`: Echo request (ping request).\n    *   `Type 11, Code 0`: TTL expired (used by Traceroute).\n*   **Traceroute Tool (uses ICMP):**\n    *   Source sends a series of UDP segments (or ICMP Echo requests) to the destination.\n    *   Each successive segment has an incrementing TTL value (TTL=1, then TTL=2, etc.).\n    *   When an `n`-th datagram arrives at the `n`-th router, the router discards it (because TTL becomes 0) and sends an ICMP \"Time Exceeded\" message (Type 11, Code 0) back to the source. This message includes the router's IP address.\n    *   The source calculates the Round Trip Time (RTT) based on receiving the ICMP message.\n    *   The process repeats (usually 3 times per TTL value) until the destination host is reached.\n    *   **Stopping Criterion:** When the UDP segment finally arrives at the destination, the destination returns an ICMP \"Port Unreachable\" packet (Type 3, Code 3) because it's an unlikely port number.\n\n**Transport and Application Layers (Briefly)**\n*   **Transport Layer:**\n    *   **Responsibility:** Delivering segments from a source *process* to a final destination *process*.\n    *   **Key Responsibilities:** Process-to-process delivery, port addressing, segmentation and reassembly, connection control (connectionless/connection-oriented), end-to-end flow control, end-to-end error control.\n*   **Application Layer:**\n    *   **Responsibility:** Providing services directly to the user.","timestamp":"2026-03-20 22:19:59"}
{"level":"info","message":"Mapping JSON to PDFDocument: {\"filename\":\"I3304-2024-2025-Part-1 (1).pdf\",\"file_size\":4689970,\"mime_type\":\"application/pdf\",\"storage_path\":\"uploads\\\\1774037965141_I3304_2024_2025_Part_1__1_.pdf\",\"original_text\":\"\\n\\nI3304\\nNetwork administration and \\nsecurity\\nAhmad Fadlallah\\nAli RAAD\\n1\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nReferenceTextbooks\\n2\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nOutline\\n•Introduction \\n๏Introduction to the course\\n๏Recall Network Basics (I2208)\\n•Network Layer\\n๏IP packet structure (Recall)\\n๏Static Routing\\n๏Dynamic Routing Algorithm\\n๏Dynamic Routing Protocols\\n๏NAT (Network Address Translation)\\n•Transport Layer\\n๏Function of the transport layer\\n๏UDP Protocol\\n๏TCP Protocol\\n-Connection management\\n-Flow control\\n-Congestion control\\n•Application Layer\\nHTTP protocol\\nFTP protocol\\nMail protocols\\nDNS\\n•Introduction to Security\\nSecurity services\\nCryptography\\nDigital Signature\\nPrinciple of network security \\nprotocols\\n3\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s the Internet: “nuts and bolts”view\\n•Billions of connected computing \\ndevices: \\n๏hosts = end systems \\n๏running network apps\\n•Communication links\\n๏fiber, copper, radio, satellite\\n๏transmission rate: bandwidth\\n•Packet switches: forward packets \\n(chunks of data)\\n๏Routers and switches\\nWired links\\nwireless\\nlinks\\nrouter\\nsmartphone\\nPC\\nserver\\nWireless laptop\\nmobile network\\nglobal ISP\\nregional ISP\\nhome \\nnetwork\\ninstitutional\\nnetwork\\n4\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\n“Fun” Internet-connected devices\\nIP picture frame\\nhttp://www.ceiva.com/\\nWeb-enabled  toaster +\\nweather forecaster\\nInternet phones\\nInternet \\nrefrigerator\\nSlingbox:  watch,\\ncontrol cable TV remotely\\nTweet-a-watt: \\nmonitor energy  use\\nsensorized,\\nbed\\nmattress\\n5\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s the Internet: “nuts and bolts” view\\n•Internet: “network of networks”\\n๏Interconnected ISPs\\n6\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s the Internet: “nuts and bolts” view\\n•Protocolscontrol sending, \\nreceiving of messages\\n๏e.g., TCP, IP, HTTP, Skype,  \\n802.11\\n•Internet  standards\\n๏RFC: Request for comments\\n๏IETF: Internet Engineering Task \\nForce\\nmobile network\\nglobal ISP\\nregional ISP\\nhome \\nnetwork\\ninstitutional\\nnetwork\\n7\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s the Internet: a service view\\n•Infrastructure that provides \\nservices to applications:\\n๏Web, VoIP, email, games, e-\\ncommerce, social nets, ...\\n•Provides programming \\ninterface to apps\\n๏hooks that allow sending \\nand receiving  app programs \\nto “connect”to Internet\\n๏Provides service options, \\nanalogous to postal service\\nmobile network\\nglobal ISP\\nregional ISP\\nhome \\nnetwork\\ninstitutional\\nnetwork\\n8\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s a protocol?\\n•“what’s the time?”\\n•“I have a question”\\n•introductions\\n•Machines rather than \\nhumans\\n•All communication activity \\nin Internet governed by \\nprotocols\\nHuman protocols\\nNetwork protocols\\n... specific messages sent\\n... specific actions taken when messages \\nreceived, or other events\\nprotocolsdefine format, orderof \\nmessages sent and received\\namong network entities, and \\nactions takenon message \\ntransmission, receipt\\n9\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhat’s a protocol?\\nQ:other human protocols? \\n10\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nWhy layering?\\nDealing with complex systems:\\n•Explicit structure allows identification, relationship of \\ncomplex system’s pieces\\n•Modularizationeases maintenance, updating of \\nsystem\\n๏Change of implementation of layer’s service \\ntransparent to rest of system\\n11\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nAnalogy\\nIk vind \\nkonijnen \\nleuk\\nL: Ducth\\nFax:#\\nIk vind \\nkonijnen \\nleuk\\nL: Dutch\\nI like \\nrabbits\\nMessage\\nInformation \\nfor the \\nremote \\ntranslator\\nInformation \\nfor the \\nremote \\nsecretary\\nIk vind \\nkonijnen \\nleuk\\nL: Ducth\\nFax:#\\nIk vind \\nkonijnen \\nleuk\\nL: Ducth\\nJ’aime \\nbien les \\nlapins\\nArabic & English\\nChinese & French\\nProfessor B\\nTranslator\\nSecretary\\nuse fax\\nuse Dutch\\nSecretary\\nTranslator\\nProfessor A\\n12\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nReference Models\\n•There are two competing models for how the \\nsoftware is layered: the OSIand the TCPmodels.  \\n•OSI (Open Systems Interconnection)\\n๏Developed by ISO (International Standards \\nOrganization)\\n๏7 layers\\n•TCP (Transfer Control Protocol)\\n๏Used in the ARPANET and in the Internet.  \\n๏Common mechanism that is surpassing the OSI Model.  \\n๏5 layers\\n13\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nReference Models\\n14\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nInternet Protocol Stack\\n•Application: supporting network applications\\n๏FTP, SMTP, HTTP\\n•Transport: process-process data transfer\\n๏TCP, UDP\\n•Network: routing of datagrams from source \\nto destination\\n๏IP, routing protocols\\n•Link: data transfer between neighboring  \\nnetwork elements\\n๏Ethernet, 802.111 (WiFi), PPP\\n•Physical: bits “on the wire”\\n15\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nISO/OSI reference model\\n•Presentation: allow applications to \\ninterpret meaning of data, e.g., \\nencryption, compression, machine-\\nspecific conventions\\n•Session: synchronization, check-\\npointing, recovery of data exchange\\n•Internet stack “missing”these \\nlayers!\\n๏these services, if needed, must be \\nimplemented in application\\n๏needed?\\n16\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nsource\\napplication\\ntransport\\nnetwork\\nlink\\nphysical\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nM\\nsegment\\nH\\nt\\ndatagram\\ndestination\\napplication\\ntransport\\nnetwork\\nlink\\nphysical\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nH\\nl\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nM\\nM\\nnetwork\\nlink\\nphysical\\nlink\\nphysical\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nH\\nl\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nH\\nn\\nH\\nl\\nM\\nrouter\\nswitch\\nEncapsulation\\nmessage\\nM\\nH\\nt\\nM\\nH\\nn\\nframe\\n17\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nReference Models\\n•Headers, Data, and Trailers\\n•Encapsulation\\n18\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTCP/IP MODEL\\n19\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nInternet Layers\\n•Internet Model\\n๏Dominant model in data communications and networking \\n๏5 ordered layers; often referred to as TCP/IP protocol suite \\n20\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nInternet Layers\\n21\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nPeer-to-Peer Processes\\n22\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nAn exchange using the Internet model\\n23\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nPhysical Layer\\n•Physical characteristics of interfaces and media \\n๏Representation of bits without interpretation \\n๏Data rate: number of bits per second \\n๏Synchronization of bits \\n24\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nThe physical layer is responsible  for \\ntransmitting  individual bits from one \\nnode to the next.\\nNote:\\n25\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTransmission Media\\n26\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nData link Layer\\nData Link Layer Responsibilities\\n•Defines framesinto manageable data units \\n๏Physical addressing \\n๏Flow control \\n๏Error control \\n๏Access control \\n27\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nThe data link layer is responsible for \\ntransmitting  frames from \\none node to the next.\\nNote:\\n28\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nNode-to-Node delivery\\n29\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\n802.3 MAC frame\\n•Preamble–7 bytesof alternating 0s and 1s to alert the receiver and allow it to \\nsynchronize\\n•Start Frame Delimiter (SFD) –1 byte –10101011 signals the beginning of a frame, \\nlast chance for synchronization –last 2 bits are 11\\n•Destination address (DA) –6 bytes –contains the physical address of the destination \\nstation or stations\\n•Source address (SA) –6 bytes –contains the physical address of the sender\\n•Length/type–if less than 1518 then it defines the length of the data field –if more \\nthan 1536 then it defines the type of the PDU packet that is encapsulated\\n•Data–data encapsulated from upper-layer protocols : 46 ~ 1500 bytes\\n•CRC–CRC-32\\n30\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nNetwork layer\\n•Network Layer Responsibilities\\n๏Source-to-destination delivery, possibly across multiple \\nnetworks \\n๏Logical addressing \\n๏Routing\\n31\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nThe network layer is responsible  for \\nthe delivery of packets from  the \\noriginal source to the \\nfinal destination.\\nNote:\\n32\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSource-to-Destination delivery\\n33\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nPosition of IPv4 in TCP/IP protocol suite\\nIPv4\\n34\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv4\\n•Best-effort delivery\\n๏IPv4 is an unreliableand connectionlessdatagram protocol\\n๏Abest-effort delivery service.\\n๏best-effort IPv4 provides no error control or flow control(except for \\nerror detection on the header).\\n•Connectionless protocol\\n๏Each datagram is handled independently\\n๏Datagrams sent by the source to the same destination could\\n-Arrive out of order\\n-be lost or corrupted during transmission.\\n๏IPv4 relies on a high-level protocol to take of all these problem.\\n35\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv4 Datagrams\\n•Packets in the IPv4 layer are called Datagrams.\\n36\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nver\\nlength\\n32 bits\\ndata \\n(variable  length,\\ntypically a TCP \\nor UDP segment)\\n16-bit identifier\\nInternet\\nchecksum\\ntime to\\nlive\\n32 bit source IP address\\nIP protocol version number\\nheader length (bytes)\\nmax number\\nremaining hops\\n(decremented at \\neach router)\\nfor\\nfragmentation/\\nreassembly\\ntotal datagram\\nlength (bytes)\\nupper layer protocol\\nto deliver payload to\\nhead.\\nlen\\ntype of\\nservice\\n“type” of data \\nflgs\\nfragment\\noffset\\nupper\\nlayer\\n32 bit destination IP address\\nOptions (if any)\\nE.g. timestamp,\\nrecord route\\ntaken, specify\\nlist of routers \\nto visit.\\nhow much overhead \\nwith TCP?\\n20 bytes of TCP\\n20 bytes of IP\\n= 40 bytes + app \\nlayer overhead\\nIP datagram format\\n37\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv4 Datagram (cont’d)\\n•A datagram is a variable-length packet consisting of a \\nheaderand data.\\n•Header\\n๏Length : 20 –60 bytes\\n๏Contains information essential to routing and delivery.\\n•Version (VER) : It defines the Version of IPv4. it is 4.\\n•Header Length (HLEN) : Defining the total length of \\nthe datagram header in 4-byte words.\\n38\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv4 Datagram (cont’d)\\n•Protocol \\n๏Defining the higher level protocol that uses the \\nservices of the IP layer\\n-TCP, UDP, ICMP, and IGMP\\n-Multiplexing data from different higher level protocols\\nValueProtocol\\n1ICMP\\n2IGMP\\n6TCP\\n8EGP\\n17UDP\\n89OSPF\\n39\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv6 Datagram\\n40\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIPv6 Datagram\\n41\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSubnet with VLSM\\n192.168.10.0/24\\n42\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nRegular Subnet\\n7subnets; The largest subnet needs 60hosts \\nIf 3bits for subnet (8 subnets) 5bits for host (32 hosts)\\nIf 6bits for host (64 hosts) 2bits for subnet (4 subnets)\\n192.168.10.0/24\\n43\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nExercise\\n•A multinational  company  wishes to have an IPv4 addressing  plan for the new \\nbranch it has created  in Beirut. The Beirut branch has 5 departments  as follows:\\n๏Human Resources  Management  (HRM) with 12 staff;\\n๏Engineering  (ENG) with 23 staff ;\\n๏Information  system (IS) with 8 staff;\\n๏Marketing  and sales (MS) with 50 staff;\\n๏Accounting and auditing  (AA) with 15 staff.\\n•In total,  the Beirut branch has 108 staff. The network  allocated  for the branch is \\n192.168.100.0/24. While taking into account the evolution  of the branch, divide  the \\nnetwork  into several  sub-networks  according  to the departments.\\n•You should fill the below  table  for each department/  sub-network.  Briefly explain \\nthe different  choices.\\n44\\nDept. \\nName\\nNetwork \\naddress\\nPrefix \\nlength\\nUsableIP address  range\\n(First –Last)\\nBroadcast address\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nForwarding -Routing\\n223.1.1.1\\n223.1.1.3\\n223.1.1.4\\n223.1.2.2\\n223.1.2.1\\n223.1.2.6\\n223.1.3.2\\n223.1.3.1\\n223.1.3.27\\n223.1.1.2\\n223.1.7.0\\n223.1.7.1\\n223.1.8.0223.1.8.1\\n223.1.9.1\\n223.1.9.2\\nDestination \\nNetwork\\nNext hopInterface\\n0.0.0.0223.1.1.3FastEthernet\\nFastEthernet\\nDestination \\nNetwork\\nNext hopInterface\\n223.1.3.0/24223.1.7.1FastEthernet0/0\\n223.1.2.0/24223.1.9.1FastEthernet0/1\\n45\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIntroduction to Routing\\nStatic Routing\\n•Static Route Characteristics:\\n๏Must be configured manually\\n๏Must be adjusted manually by \\nthe administrator when there \\nis a change in the topology\\n๏Good for small non-redundant \\nnetworks\\n๏Often used in conjunction \\nwith a dynamic routing \\nprotocolfor configuring a \\ndefault route\\n46\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIntroduction to Routing\\nDynamic Routing\\n•Dynamic Routes Automatically:\\n๏Discover remote networks\\n๏Maintain up-to-date \\ninformation\\n๏Choose the best path to the \\ndestination\\n๏Find new best paths when \\nthere is a topology change\\n๏Dynamic routing can also \\nshare static default routes \\nwith the other routers.\\n47\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nAddress Resolution -ARP\\n48\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nMAC addresses and ARP\\n•IP address: \\n๏“Low” Network-layer address for interface\\n๏Used for layer 3 (network layer) forwarding\\n•MAC (or LAN or physical or Ethernet) address: \\n๏Function: used “locally” to get frame from one interface to \\nanother physically-connected interface (same network, in \\nIP-addressing sense)\\n๏48 bit MAC address (for most LANs) burned in NIC ROM, \\nalso sometimes software settable\\n๏e.g.: 1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD\\nhexadecimal (base 16) notation\\n(each “numeral” represents 4 bits)\\n49\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nLAN addresses and ARP\\neach adapter on LAN has unique LANaddress\\nadapter\\n1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD\\n58-23-D7-FA-20-B0\\n0C-C4-11-6F-E3-98\\n71-65-F7-2B-08-53\\nLAN\\n(wired or\\nwireless)\\n50\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nLAN addresses (more)\\n•MAC address allocation administered by IEEE\\n•Manufacturer buys portion of MAC address space (to \\nassure uniqueness)\\n•Analogy:\\n๏MAC address: like Social Security Number\\n๏IP address: like postal address\\n•MAC flat address  ➜portability \\n๏can move LAN card from one LAN to another\\n•IP hierarchical address not portable\\n๏address depends on IP subnet to which node is attached\\n51\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nARP: Address Resolution Protocol\\n•ARP table: each IP node (host, \\nrouter) on LAN has a ARP table\\n–IP/MAC address mappings for some \\nLAN nodes:\\n•< IP address; MAC address; TTL>\\n–TTL (Time To Live): time after which \\naddress mapping will be forgotten \\n(typically 20 min)\\nQuestion:how to determine\\ninterface’s MAC address, \\nknowing its IP address?\\n1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD\\n58-23-D7-FA-20-B0\\n0C-C4-11-6F-E3-98\\n71-65-F7-2B-08-53\\nLAN\\n137.196.7.23\\n137.196.7.78\\n137.196.7.14\\n137.196.7.88\\nIP addressMAC addressTTL\\n137.196.7.1458-23-D7-FA-20-B0\\n20\\n52\\nUse arpcommand to display ARP table on Windows or Linux\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nARP protocol: same LAN\\n1.A wants to send datagram to B\\n๏B’s MAC address not in A’s ARP table.\\n2.A broadcasts ARP query packet, containing B's IP address \\n๏Destination MAC address = FF-FF-FF-FF-FF-FF\\n๏All nodes on LAN receive ARP query \\n3.B receives ARP packet, replies to A with its (B's) MAC address\\n๏frame sent to A’s MAC address (unicast)\\n4.A caches (saves) IP-to-MAC address pair in its ARP table until \\ninformation becomes old (times out) \\n๏soft state: information that times out (goes away) unless refreshed\\n•ARP is “plug-and-play”:\\n๏Nodes create their ARP tables without intervention from net \\nadministrator\\n53\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nARP operation\\n54\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nHardware Type –\\nEthernet is type 1\\nProtocol Type-\\nIPv4=x0800\\nHardware Length: \\nlength of Ethernet \\nAddress (6)\\nProtocol Length: \\nlength of IPv4 \\naddress (4)\\nARP packet\\n55\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nThe ARP packet is encapsulated within an Ethernet packet.\\nNote: Type field for Ethernet is x0806\\nEncapsulation of ARP packet\\n56\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nFour cases using ARP\\n57\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nARP Example \\n58\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nARP –A each step\\nARP: Who has this IP?\\nARP: Who has this IP?\\nARP: Who has this IP?\\n59\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nDefault Gateways\\n•Devices need the following information \\nfor network access: IP address, subnet \\nmask, and default gateway.\\n•When a host sends a packet to a device \\nthat is on the same IP network, the packet \\nis forwarded out the host interface to the \\ndestination device. The router does not \\nneed to get involved.\\n•When a host sends a packet to a device on \\na different IP network, the packet is \\nforwarded to the default gateway because \\nthe host device cannot communicate with \\ndevices outside of the local network.\\n•The default gateway is the device that \\nroutes traffic from the local network to \\ndevices on remote networks, such as \\ndevices on the Internet.\\nRouters are also usually configured with their own default gateway.\\n60\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•walkthrough: send datagram from A to B via R\\n–Focus on addressing –at IP (datagram) and MAC layer \\n(frame)\\n–Assume A knows B’s IP address\\n–Assume A knows IP address of first hop router, R (how?)\\n–Assume A knows R’s MAC address (how?)\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\n61\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•A creates IP datagram with IP source A, destination B \\n•A creates link-layer frame with R's MAC address as \\ndestination address, frame contains A-to-B IP datagram\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\nMAC src: 74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nMAC dest: E6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\n62\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•Frame sent from A to R\\n•Frame received at R, datagram removed, passed \\nup to IP\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\nMAC src: 74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nMAC dest: E6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\n63\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•R forwards datagram with IP source A, destination B \\n•R creates link-layer frame with B's MAC address as \\ndestination address, frame contains A-to-B IP \\ndatagram\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\nMAC src: 1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\nMAC dest: 49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\n64\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•R forwards datagram with IP source A, destination B \\n•R creates link-layer frame with B's MAC address as \\ndestination address, frame contains A-to-B IP \\ndatagram\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\nMAC src: 1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\nMAC dest: 49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\n65\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nR\\n1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\n222.222.222.220\\n111.111.111.110\\nE6-E9-00-17-BB-4B\\nCC-49-DE-D0-AB-7D\\n111.111.111.112\\n111.111.111.111\\n74-29-9C-E8-FF-55\\nA\\n222.222.222.222\\n49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\n222.222.222.221\\n88-B2-2F-54-1A-0F\\nB\\nAddressing: routing to another LAN\\n•R forwards datagram with IP source A, destination B \\n•R creates link-layer frame with B's MAC address as dest, frame \\ncontains A-to-B IP datagram\\nIP src: 111.111.111.111\\nIP dest: 222.222.222.222\\nMAC src: 1A-23-F9-CD-06-9B\\nMAC dest: 49-BD-D2-C7-56-2A\\nIP\\nEth\\nPhy\\n* Check out the online interactive exercises for more \\nexamples:  http://gaia.cs.umass.edu/kurose_ross/interactive/\\n66\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nIntroduction to Routing\\nRouter Packet Forwarding Decision\\n•What happens when the router receives the frame \\nfrom the host device?\\n67\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nSend a Packet\\n•PC1 must determine if the destination IPv4 address is on the same network. \\n•If it is on the same network, PC1 will obtain the destination MAC address from its ARP cache or use an \\nARP request.\\n•Because the destination network is on a different network, PC1 forwards the packet to its default \\ngateway.\\n68\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nSend a Packet\\n•To determine the MAC address of the default gateway, PC1 checks its ARP table for \\nthe IPv4 address of the default gateway and its corresponding MAC address. \\n๏An ARP request is sent if it is not found.\\n•When PC1 has the MAC address of Router R1, it can forward the packet. \\n69\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nForward to the Next Hop\\n•R1 examines the destination MAC address which matches the MAC address \\nof the receiving interface and copies the frame into its buffer.\\n•R1 identifies the Ethernet Type field as 0x800 which indicates that the \\nEthernet frame contains an IPv4 packet in the data portion of the frame.\\n70\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nForward to the Next Hop\\n•R1 de-encapsulates the Ethernet frame.\\n•Because the destination IPv4 address of the packet, 192.168.4.10,   does not match \\nany of the directly connected networks on R1, R1 searches the routing table for a \\ncorresponding route.\\n๏R1’s Routing Table has a route for the 192.168.4.0/24 network.\\n71\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nForward to the Next Hop\\n•The routethat R1 finds to the 192.168.4.0/24 network has a next-hopaddressof \\n192.168.2.2 and an exit interface of FastEthernet0/1.\\n•This will require that the IPv4 packet be encapsulated in a new Ethernet frame with \\nthe destination MAC address of the IPv4 address of the next-hop router, 192.168.2.2\\n72\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks: \\nForward to the Next Hop\\n•Because the exit interface is on an Ethernet network, R1 must resolve the \\nnext-hop IPv4 address with a destination MAC address using ARP, assuming \\nit is not in its ARP cache.\\n•When R1 has the MAC address for the next-hop, the Ethernet frame is \\nforwarded out of the FastEthernet0/1 interface of R1.\\n73\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nPacket Routing\\n•R2 examines the destination MAC address\\n๏Because it matches the MAC address of its receiving interface, R2 copies the \\nframe into its buffer.\\n•R2 determines that that frame contains an IPv4 packet in the data portion \\nof the frame.\\n74\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nPacket Routing\\n•R2 de-encapsulates the Ethernet frame.\\n•Because the destination IP address is on a different network, \\nthe routing table is searched to find a corresponding route for \\nthe destination IPv4 address. \\n75\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nPacket Routing\\n•The routing table of R2 has a routeto the 192.168.4.0/24 network \\nwith a next-hop IPv4 address of 192.168.3.2 and an exit interface of \\nSerial 0/0/0.   \\n•Because the exit interface is not Ethernet, R2 does not have to \\nresolve the next-hop IP-v4 address with a destination MAC address.\\n76\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nPacket Routing\\n•The IPv4 packet is encapsulatedinto a new data link frame used by \\nthe exit interface and sent out the Serial 0/0/0 exit interface.\\n•Because there are no MAC addresses on serial interfaces, R2 sets the \\ndata link destination address to an equivalent of a broadcast.\\n77\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nReach the Destination\\n•R3 copies the data link PPP frame into its buffer.\\n•R3 de-encapsulatesthe data link PPP frame.\\n•R3 searches the routing table for the destination IPv4 address of the \\npacket.\\n78\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nSwitching Packets Between Networks\\nReach the Destination\\n•Because the destination network is on R3’s directly connected network, the \\npacket can be sent directly and does not need to be sent to another router.\\n•Because the exit interface is a directly connected Ethernet network, R3 \\nmust resolve the destination IPv4 address of the packet with a destination \\nMAC address by either finding it in its ARP cache or send out an ARP \\nrequest.\\n79\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nInternet Control Message Protocol \\n•The Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) \\n•Specified in [RFC 792], \\n•Used by hosts and routers to communicate network-\\nlayer information to each other. \\n•Most typical use of ICMP is for error reporting\\n•Often considered part of IP, but architecturally it lies \\njust above IP, as ICMP messages are carried inside IP \\ndatagrams. \\n๏ICMP messages are carried as IP payload\\n80\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nICMP Type and Code \\nTypeCode Description\\n00echo reply (ping)\\n30destination network unreachable\\n31destination host unreachable\\n32destination protocol unreachable\\n33destination port unreachable\\n36destination network unknown\\n37destination host unknown\\n80echo request (ping)\\n90route advertisement\\n100router discovery\\n110TTL expired\\n120bad IP header\\n81\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTrace Route –ICMP\\n•Source sends series of UDP segments (or ICMP Echo request) to destination host\\n๏First has TTL =1\\n๏Second has TTL=2, etc.\\n๏Unlikely port number\\n•When n\\nth\\ndatagram arrives to n\\nth\\nrouter:\\n๏Router discards datagram\\n๏Sends to source an ICMP message (type 11, code 0)\\n๏Datagram includes router IP address. Traceroute does DNS lookup to find name of router \\n(if any)\\n•When ICMP message arrives, source calculates RTT\\n•Traceroute repeat the process 3 times (To get average RTT)\\n•Stopping criterion\\n๏UDP segment eventually arrives at destination host\\n๏Destination returns ICMP “port unreachable” packet (type 3, code 3)\\n82\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTrace Route –ICMP\\n83\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTransport layer\\nThe transport layer is responsible for delivering segments from a source process to a \\nfinal destination process.\\n84\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nTransport layer\\n•Transport Layer Responsibilities\\n๏Process-to-process delivery of entire message \\n๏Port addressing \\n๏Segmentation and reassembly \\n๏Connection control: connectionless or connection-oriented \\n๏End-to-end flow control \\n๏End-to-end error control \\n85\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nApplication Layer\\n•The application layer is responsible for providing \\nservices to the user.\\n86\\n\\nI3304 -Network Administration and Security2023-2024\\nThanks !\\n87\",\"summary\":\"Here is a detailed summary of the provided text, organized into logical bullet points:\\n\\n**I3304: Network Administration and Security - Course Overview**\\n*   **Course Title:** I3304 - Network Administration and Security (2023-2024)\\n*   **Instructors:** Ahmad Fadlallah, Ali RAAD\\n*   **Course Outline:**\\n    *   **Introduction:** Course introduction, recall Network Basics (I2208).\\n    *   **Network Layer:** IP packet structure (recall), Static Routing, Dynamic Routing Algorithms/Protocols, NAT (Network Address Translation).\\n    *   **Transport Layer:** Function of the transport layer, UDP Protocol, TCP Protocol (Connection management, Flow control, Congestion control).\\n    *   **Application Layer:** HTTP protocol, FTP protocol, Mail protocols, DNS.\\n    *   **Introduction to Security:** Security services, Cryptography, Digital Signature, Principle of network security protocols.\\n\\n**What is the Internet?**\\n*   **\\\"Nuts and Bolts\\\" View:**\\n    *   Billions of connected computing devices (hosts/end systems) running network applications.\\n    *   Communication links (fiber, copper, radio, satellite) with transmission rate defined by bandwidth.\\n    *   Packet switches (routers and switches) forward packets (chunks of data).\\n    *   Described as a \\\"network of networks\\\" interconnected by ISPs (Internet Service Providers).\\n    *   Communication activity is governed by **protocols** (e.g., TCP, IP, HTTP, 802.11).\\n    *   **Internet Standards:** Defined by RFC (Request for Comments) and IETF (Internet Engineering Task Force).\\n*   **\\\"Service View\\\":**\\n    *   An infrastructure providing services to applications (Web, VoIP, email, games, e-commerce, social networks).\\n    *   Offers a programming interface (hooks) for applications to \\\"connect\\\" and send/receive data.\\n    *   Provides service options, analogous to a postal service.\\n\\n**Protocols and Layering**\\n*   **What's a Protocol?**\\n    *   Defines the format, order of messages sent and received among network entities.\\n    *   Specifies actions taken on message transmission or receipt.\\n    *   Governs all communication activity in the Internet.\\n    *   Distinction: Human protocols (e.g., introductions) vs. Network protocols (machine-to-machine).\\n*   **Why Layering?**\\n    *   **Explicit structure:** Allows identification and relationship of complex system pieces.\\n    *   **Modularization:** Eases maintenance and updating.\\n    *   **Transparency:** Changes in one layer's implementation are transparent to the rest of the system.\\n\\n**Network Reference Models**\\n*   **Two Competing Models:**\\n    *   **OSI (Open Systems Interconnection) Model:**\\n        *   Developed by ISO (International Standards Organization).\\n        *   Comprises 7 layers.\\n    *   **TCP/IP (Transmission Control Protocol/Internet Protocol) Model:**\\n        *   Used in ARPANET and the Internet; a common, dominant mechanism.\\n        *   Comprises 5 layers.\\n*   **Internet Protocol Stack (TCP/IP 5-Layer Model):**\\n    *   **Application Layer:** Supports network applications (e.g., FTP, SMTP, HTTP).\\n    *   **Transport Layer:** Process-to-process data transfer (e.g., TCP, UDP).\\n    *   **Network Layer:** Routing of datagrams from source to destination (e.g., IP, routing protocols).\\n    *   **Link Layer:** Data transfer between neighboring network elements (e.g., Ethernet, 802.11/WiFi, PPP).\\n    *   **Physical Layer:** Deals with bits \\\"on the wire.\\\"\\n*   **OSI Layers \\\"Missing\\\" in Internet Stack:**\\n    *   **Presentation Layer:** Allows applications to interpret data meaning (e.g., encryption, compression, machine-specific conventions).\\n    *   **Session Layer:** Handles synchronization, checkpointing, and recovery of data exchange.\\n    *   In the Internet stack, these services, if needed, must be implemented within the application layer.\\n\\n**Encapsulation**\\n*   **Process:** As data moves down the protocol stack, each layer adds its own header (and sometimes a trailer) to the data received from the layer above.\\n*   **Headers, Data, and Trailers:** A message (M) from the application layer becomes a segment with a transport header (Ht), then a datagram with a network header (Hn), and finally a frame with a link header (Hl) and trailer (Hl).\\n*   **Peer-to-Peer Processes:** Each layer on the sending host logically communicates with its corresponding layer on the receiving host.\\n\\n**Detailed Layer Responsibilities**\\n*   **Physical Layer:**\\n    *   **Responsibility:** Transmitting individual bits from one node to the next.\\n    *   **Characteristics:** Defines physical interfaces and media, representation of bits (without interpretation), data rate (bits per second), synchronization of bits.\\n*   **Data Link Layer:**\\n    *   **Responsibility:** Transmitting frames from one node to the next.\\n    *   **Key Responsibilities:** Defines frames, physical addressing (MAC addresses), flow control, error control, access control.\\n    *   **802.3 MAC Frame Structure (Ethernet):**\\n        *   **Preamble (7 bytes):** Alternating 0s and 1s for receiver synchronization.\\n        *   **Start Frame Delimiter (SFD) (1 byte):** `10101011` signals frame start, last chance for synchronization.\\n        *   **Destination Address (DA) (6 bytes):** Physical address of destination station(s).\\n        *   **Source Address (SA) (6 bytes):** Physical address of the sender.\\n        *   **Length/Type:** If < 1518, defines data field length; if > 1536, defines type of encapsulated PDU packet.\\n        *   **Data (46-1500 bytes):** Encapsulated upper-layer protocol data.\\n        *   **CRC (Cyclic Redundancy Check):** CRC-32 for error detection.\\n*   **Network Layer:**\\n    *   **Responsibility:** Delivery of packets from the original source to the final destination (possibly across multiple networks).\\n    *   **Key Responsibilities:** Logical addressing (IP addresses), Routing.\\n\\n**IPv4 Protocol**\\n*   **Position:** Sits within the Network Layer of the TCP/IP protocol suite.\\n*   **Characteristics:**\\n    *   **Best-effort delivery:** Unreliable and connectionless datagram protocol.\\n    *   Provides no error control or flow control (except for error detection on the header).\\n    *   **Connectionless:** Each datagram is handled independently; datagrams from the same source to destination may arrive out of order, be lost, or corrupted. Relies on higher-level protocols for reliability.\\n*   **IPv4 Datagrams:**\\n    *   Packets at the IPv4 layer are called datagrams.\\n    *   Variable-length packet consisting of a header and data.\\n    *   **Header:** Length is 20-60 bytes, contains information essential for routing and delivery.\\n    *   **Key Header Fields:**\\n        *   **Version (VER):** Defines the IPv4 version (always 4).\\n        *   **Header Length (HLEN):** Total length of the datagram header in 4-byte words.\\n        *   **Type of Service:** (Differentiated Services Code Point)\\n        *   **Total Length:** Total length of the datagram (header + data) in bytes.\\n        *   **Identifier, Flags, Fragment Offset:** Used for fragmentation and reassembly.\\n        *   **Time to Live (TTL):** Maximum number of hops remaining (decremented at each router); prevents infinite loops.\\n        *   **Protocol:** Defines the higher-level protocol using IP services (e.g., 1=ICMP, 6=TCP, 17=UDP, 89=OSPF).\\n        *   **Header Checksum:** For error detection on the header.\\n        *   **Source IP Address (32 bits):** IP address of the sender.\\n        *   **Destination IP Address (32 bits):** IP address of the final recipient.\\n        *   **Options (if any):** E.g., timestamp, record route, specify routers.\\n    *   **Overhead:** 20 bytes for IP header + 20 bytes for TCP header = 40 bytes minimum.\\n*   **IPv6 Datagram:** Mentioned with diagrams as the next generation IP protocol.\\n*   **Subnetting with VLSM:** A practical application for creating an IPv4 addressing plan for a network with varying host requirements in different departments.\\n\\n**Routing**\\n*   **Forwarding vs. Routing:** Forwarding is the process of moving a packet from a router’s input link to the appropriate output link; routing is the process of determining the end-to-end path.\\n*   **Static Routing:**\\n    *   **Characteristics:** Must be configured manually; requires manual adjustment by administrator for topology changes; good for small, non-redundant networks; often used with dynamic routing for configuring a default route.\\n*   **Dynamic Routing:**\\n    *   **Characteristics:** Automatically discovers remote networks; maintains up-to-date information; chooses the best path to the destination; finds new best paths when topology changes; can share static default routes with other routers.\\n\\n**Address Resolution Protocol (ARP)**\\n*   **Purpose:** Resolves an IP address to a corresponding MAC (Media Access Control) address.\\n*   **MAC Address (LAN / Physical / Ethernet Address):**\\n    *   Function: Used locally to get a frame from one interface to another physically-connected interface on the same network.\\n    *   Format: 48-bit hexadecimal address (e.g., 1A-2F-BB-76-09-AD), burned into NIC ROM (sometimes software settable).\\n    *   Administered by IEEE to ensure uniqueness (manufacturers buy portions of the address space).\\n    *   Analogy: MAC address is like a Social Security Number (flat, portable); IP address is like a postal address (hierarchical, depends on subnet).\\n*   **ARP Table:**\\n    *   Each IP node (host, router) on a LAN maintains an ARP table.\\n    *   Stores IP/MAC address mappings for known LAN nodes.\\n    *   Includes: IP address, MAC address, and TTL (Time To Live), which is the time after which the mapping will be forgotten (typically 20 min).\\n*   **ARP Protocol (Same LAN Scenario):**\\n    1.  Host A wants to send a datagram to Host B, but B's MAC address is not in A's ARP table.\\n    2.  A broadcasts an ARP query packet containing B's IP address. The destination MAC address is `FF-FF-FF-FF-FF-FF` (broadcast).\\n    3.  All nodes on the LAN receive the ARP query.\\n    4.  B receives the query and replies to A with its (B's) MAC address (unicast).\\n    5.  A caches the IP-to-MAC address pair in its ARP table until it times out (\\\"soft state\\\").\\n    *   **\\\"Plug-and-play\\\":** Nodes create their ARP tables without administrator intervention.\\n*   **ARP Packet Structure:** Includes Hardware Type (e.g., Ethernet=1), Protocol Type (e.g., IPv4=x0800), Hardware Length (6 for Ethernet), Protocol Length (4 for IPv4), Operation (request/reply), Sender MAC/IP, Target MAC/IP.\\n*   **Encapsulation:** An ARP packet is encapsulated within an Ethernet frame (Ethernet Type field is `x0806`).\\n\\n**Packet Forwarding and Routing Decisions**\\n*   **Default Gateways:**\\n    *   Devices need IP address, subnet mask, and default gateway for network access.\\n    *   If the destination is on the same IP network, the packet is forwarded directly to the destination.\\n    *   If the destination is on a different IP network, the packet is forwarded to the default gateway (a router).\\n    *   The default gateway routes traffic between the local network and remote networks (e.g., the Internet).\\n*   **Routing to Another LAN (Walkthrough A -> R -> B):**\\n    1.  Host A creates an IP datagram (Source IP = A, Destination IP = B).\\n    2.  A creates a link-layer frame (Source MAC = A's MAC, Destination MAC = R's MAC) containing the IP datagram. (R's MAC obtained via ARP if not known).\\n    3.  The frame is sent from A to Router R.\\n    4.  R receives the frame, removes the IP datagram, and passes it to its IP layer.\\n    5.  R determines the next hop for the destination B from its routing table.\\n    6.  R creates a *new* link-layer frame (Source MAC = R's MAC for the *next* interface, Destination MAC = B's MAC) containing the *original* IP datagram. (B's MAC obtained via ARP if not known).\\n    7.  The new frame is sent from R to B.\\n*   **Router Packet Forwarding Decision (Multi-hop Example PC1 -> R1 -> R2 -> R3 -> PC4):**\\n    *   **Host to Gateway:** PC1 determines destination (PC4) is remote, sends packet to its default gateway (R1) using R1's MAC address (resolved via ARP).\\n    *   **Gateway Processing (R1):** R1 examines destination MAC (matches its interface), de-encapsulates the Ethernet frame to get the IPv4 packet. R1 checks its routing table for PC4's IP. Finds a route to a next-hop (R2) via an exit interface. Re-encapsulates the IPv4 packet into a new Ethernet frame for R2 using R2's MAC address (resolved via ARP).\\n    *   **Intermediate Router Processing (R2):** R2 receives the frame, de-encapsulates. Checks its routing table for PC4's IP. Finds a route to next-hop (R3) via a Serial interface. Re-encapsulates the IPv4 packet into a new data link frame for the serial link (no MAC addresses on serial, often broadcast equivalent).\\n    *   **Final Router to Destination (R3):** R3 receives the serial frame, de-encapsulates. Checks its routing table for PC4's IP. Finds PC4 is on a directly connected network. Resolves PC4's IP to MAC address via ARP (if not cached). Re-encapsulates the IPv4 packet into a final Ethernet frame for PC4.\\n\\n**Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP)**\\n*   **Purpose:** Used by hosts and routers to communicate network-layer information to each other.\\n*   **Primary Use:** Error reporting.\\n*   **Architectural Position:** Architecturally lies just above IP; ICMP messages are carried as IP payload within IP datagrams.\\n*   **ICMP Type and Code Examples:**\\n    *   `Type 0, Code 0`: Echo reply (ping response).\\n    *   `Type 3, Code 0-7`: Destination unreachable (network, host, protocol, port unreachable, etc.).\\n    *   `Type 8, Code 0`: Echo request (ping request).\\n    *   `Type 11, Code 0`: TTL expired (used by Traceroute).\\n*   **Traceroute Tool (uses ICMP):**\\n    *   Source sends a series of UDP segments (or ICMP Echo requests) to the destination.\\n    *   Each successive segment has an incrementing TTL value (TTL=1, then TTL=2, etc.).\\n    *   When an `n`-th datagram arrives at the `n`-th router, the router discards it (because TTL becomes 0) and sends an ICMP \\\"Time Exceeded\\\" message (Type 11, Code 0) back to the source. This message includes the router's IP address.\\n    *   The source calculates the Round Trip Time (RTT) based on receiving the ICMP message.\\n    *   The process repeats (usually 3 times per TTL value) until the destination host is reached.\\n    *   **Stopping Criterion:** When the UDP segment finally arrives at the destination, the destination returns an ICMP \\\"Port Unreachable\\\" packet (Type 3, Code 3) because it's an unlikely port number.\\n\\n**Transport and Application Layers (Briefly)**\\n*   **Transport Layer:**\\n    *   **Responsibility:** Delivering segments from a source *process* to a final destination *process*.\\n    *   **Key Responsibilities:** Process-to-process delivery, port addressing, segmentation and reassembly, connection control (connectionless/connection-oriented), end-to-end flow control, end-to-end error control.\\n*   **Application Layer:**\\n    *   **Responsibility:** Providing services directly to the user.\"}","timestamp":"2026-03-20 22:19:59"}
